<title>The Monitor: A Publication of the Jamestown Foundation: The Fortnight in Review - Vol.I, No.11</title>
<h1>The Fortnight in Review - Vol.I, No.11</h1>
Jamestown Foundation (<i>brdcast@mx.jamestown.org</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 6 Dec 1996 13:29:58 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#66">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#66">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#66">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#66">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Jamestown Foundation: "9 December 1996 Monitor - Vol.II, No.229"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Jamestown Foundation: "6 December 1996 Monitor - Vol.II, No.228"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
THE FORTNIGHT IN REVIEW<br>
<p>
	Despite a political scandal that rocked the Kremlin and a brouhaha over the<br>
firing of a top military commander, President Boris Yeltsin's swift recovery<br>
from heart surgery this past fortnight seemed set to right Russia's listing<br>
ship of state and to end, for the time being at least, talk of a lame duck<br>
presidency. Yeltsin's restored presence appeared also to be manifested in a<br>
decision to withdraw the last of the federal troops from Chechnya, where<br>
plans for a presidential election are proceeding apace, and the Kremlin was<br>
further buoyed by the unexpectedly successful debut of a Russian Eurobond<br>
issue. U.S.-Russian relations, meanwhile, survived yet another spy scandal,<br>
but Moscow found itself largely isolated at an OSCE Summit in Lisbon.<br>
Finally, the defeat of incumbent Mircea Snegur in Moldova's December 1<br>
presidential election marked a welcome exception to the general trend of<br>
authoritarianism that has been evident throughout parts of the former Soviet<br>
Union. <br>
<p>
YELTSIN -- BACK IN THE SADDLE<br>
	Boris Yeltsin's transfer to a sanitarium near Moscow on November 22<br>
appeared to change the balance of power in the Kremlin. Clearly back in<br>
charge, the president shed the "lame duck" label and critics stopped making<br>
snide references to the "regency" of presidential aide Anatoly Chubais. But<br>
all was not smooth sailing for Russia's leaders. On November 15, as Yeltsin<br>
prepared to leave the hospital, a Moscow newspaper published the transcript<br>
of an incriminating conversation in which Chubais and two other Yeltsin<br>
aides allegedly discussed ways of hushing up covert funding for Yeltsin's<br>
election campaign. Publication seemed timed to embarrass Yeltsin and<br>
discredit Chubais, whose energies are focused on building an efficient<br>
mechanism of presidential power. Chubais denied the conversation had ever<br>
taken place and Yeltsin's confidence in his chief of staff appeared<br>
unshaken. At the same time, however, Yeltsin made a number of moves<br>
apparently intended to boost the status of one of Chubais' fiercest rivals,<br>
Moscow mayor Yuri Luzhkov. The most striking of these was to invite Luzhkov<br>
-- apparently as a counterweight to Chubais -- to attend the first meeting<br>
of a new consultative body of Russia's top decision-makers. <br>
<p>
MENDING FENCES WITH CHECHNYA<br>
	Another sign of Yeltsin's waxing authority came on November 23, when the<br>
president signed a controversial decree ordering the last two brigades of<br>
federal troops still in Chechnya to withdraw before January 27, the date set<br>
for presidential and parliamentary elections in the republic. Withdrawal was<br>
supported by army chiefs but strongly opposed by Interior Minister Anatoly<br>
Kulikov. Later the same day, the Russian and Chechen prime ministers met to<br>
sign an interim agreement covering topics of economic importance such as the<br>
resumption of oil and gas deliveries between Chechnya and Russia. A more<br>
detailed agreement between the two governments is due to be signed after the<br>
January elections.<br>
	Communists and nationalists in the Russian Duma denounced both the<br>
withdrawal and the interim agreement. Their threats to impeach the president<br>
and vote no confidence in the government came to nothing, however. Deputies<br>
lost their nerve when Yeltsin made it clear that, if they carried out their<br>
threats, he would dissolve parliament. Instead, the Duma on November 29<br>
merely urged Yeltsin to "reconsider" his decisions. Yeltsin ignored the<br>
Duma's appeal. On December 1, the troop withdrawal from Chechnya began.<br>
Opinion polls indicated that the Russian public strongly supported the move.<br>
<p>
CHECHEN ELECTION CAMPAIGN UNDER WAY<br>
	Five candidates declared their intention to run for president of Chechnya,<br>
but the only serious contenders appeared to be incumbent president Zelimkhan<br>
Yandarbiev and Prime Minister Aslan Maskhadov. Earlier, Yandarbiev had said<br>
that the Chechen resistance forces had decided to unite behind him in order<br>
to avoid splitting their ranks. But Maskhadov told Chechen television on<br>
November 25 that "an election with only one candidate is not an election."<br>
Yandarbiev supports a harder line in relations with Moscow than Maskhadov<br>
and was the main initiator within the Chechen leadership of the creation of<br>
a strict Islamic state in Chechnya. From all indications, Yandarbiev's<br>
candidacy is supported by Chechnya's Islamic clergy, while Moscow clearly<br>
hopes that Maskhadov, a former colonel in the Soviet Army, will emerge<br>
victorious. Though seen by Moscow as a moderate, Maskhadov enjoys enormous<br>
popularity inside Chechnya, where he is given much of the credit for the<br>
victory over the Russian army. <br>
<p>
RUSSIA'S DEBUT EUROBOND ISSUE: HEAVILY OVERSUBSCRIBED<br>
	On the financial front, the Russian government raised $1 billion on<br>
November 21 when it made its first international bond issue since the 1917<br>
Revolution. This was double the amount the government originally planned to<br>
raise. At 9.25 percent, yield was about a third higher than for the<br>
equivalent U.S. government bonds, reflecting higher perceived risk, but keen<br>
western interest in the issue was seen as a sign of confidence that Russia's<br>
long-awaited economic turnaround will soon begin. Optimism surged with<br>
Yeltsin's strong recovery from surgery and investors submitted bids in<br>
excess of $2 billion.<br>
	In another sign of confidence, the Russian government announced an annual<br>
range for the ruble against the dollar. Until now, Moscow had confined<br>
itself to setting six-monthly targets. The ruble will start 1997 within a<br>
range of 5,500-6,100 rubles to the dollar, and will gradually decline to<br>
5,750-6,350 rubles by the end of the year.<br>
<p>
CONFUSION IN THE DEFENSE MINISTRY<br>
	But the good news elsewhere did not extend to the Defense Ministry, which<br>
created yet another embarrassing personnel muddle on December 2 when it<br>
announced that Ground Forces commander-in-chief Vladimir Semenov had been<br>
dismissed for actions dishonoring his uniform. The popular Semenov protested<br>
the allegations contained in the dismissal order, and the controversy<br>
deepened as neither the Defense Ministry, the Russian General Prosecutor's<br>
Office, nor the Interior Ministry could shed any light on what the charges<br>
against Semenov might be. Meanwhile, the Russian president's office<br>
announced publicly that Boris Yeltsin had approved the dismissal of Semenov<br>
in principal only, and that the decision still had to be considered by a<br>
presidential commission that oversees high level military appointments.<br>
Defense Minister Igor Rodionov, already taking some heat for the halting<br>
pace of Russian military reform, had apparently exceeded his authority in<br>
announcing Semenov's sacking. The conflict presented a picture of confusion<br>
at the top of the military hierarchy and, Defense Ministry denials<br>
notwithstanding, appeared to be the cause of a last-minute decision by<br>
Rodionov to postpone an important official visit to the U.S.<br>
<p>
FOREIGN POLICY: THE SPIES AMONG US<br>
	For Russia and the U.S., the fortnight began with the conclusion of one spy<br>
scandal and the uncovering of another, neither of which redounded to the<br>
glory of the American intelligence community. The episode that came to a<br>
close involved Vladimir Galkin, a former mid-level Soviet KGB agent, who<br>
returned to Russia a hero on November 17 following a U.S. Justice Department<br>
decision to drop espionage charges against him. But Galkin had scarcely<br>
gotten settled back in Moscow when, on November 18, U.S. authorities charged<br>
Harold Nicholson, a former CIA station chief, with spying for Moscow.<br>
Nicholson is believed to have been recruited by the Kremlin during a 1994<br>
trip to Malaysia, and U.S. intelligence personnel were said to have been<br>
stunned by the possibility that he had launched his espionage activities<br>
less than eight weeks after the conviction of Aldrich Ames, the most<br>
notorious spy in CIA history. Unlike Ames, moreover, Nicholson was seen as a<br>
rising star with excellent prospects to ascend to a leadership position in<br>
the agency's hierarchy. <br>
	Nicholson, who on November 27 pled innocent to the spying charges, is the<br>
highest-ranking CIA employee ever to be charged with espionage. He allegedly<br>
received more than $180,000 from Moscow, and, although not believed to have<br>
been as serious a security breach as Ames, is thought to have turned over to<br>
the Kremlin a wealth of secret materials, including the identities of<br>
undercover CIA operatives and details of the agency's activities around the<br>
world. Ironically, an FBI affidavit submitted for the case suggested that<br>
the Russian Foreign Intelligence Service may have inadvertently provided one<br>
of the clues that led to Nicholson's arrest.<br>
<p>
THE LONELY ROAD TO LISBON<br>
	Despite a nearly two month period during which Moscow had emitted mixed<br>
signals on the issue of NATO enlargement, the country's political elites<br>
closed ranks in opposition to the alliance's expansion plans in the days<br>
leading up the December 2-3 OSCE Summit in Lisbon. Boris Yeltsin punctuated<br>
Moscow's new-found solidarity when he took a hard line on the issue during<br>
talks on November 29 with Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and Foreign<br>
Minister Yevgeny Primakov. In a restatement of Moscow's long-held position<br>
on the issue, Yeltsin also urged the Summit participants to work toward the<br>
construction of a new European security system in which the OSCE rather than<br>
NATO would play the central role. <br>
	As was the case at the OSCE's 1994 Summit in Budapest, however, Russia's<br>
efforts toward this end won little backing. In addition, Moscow's support<br>
for the increasingly authoritarian president of Belarus, Aleksandr<br>
Lukashenko, and for his besieged counterpart in Serbia, Slobodan Milosevic,<br>
left the Russian delegation isolated. For all of that, Moscow was successful<br>
in some of the lesser skirmishing that took place in Lisbon. In the Summit's<br>
declaration on a 21st century European security model, for example, Russia<br>
won inclusion of a passage saying that OSCE member states "will not<br>
strengthen their security at the expense of the security of other states." A<br>
Summit document on arms control carried a similar declaration. But Russia's<br>
most significant victory may have been an agreement to review the 1990 CFE<br>
Treaty, which the Kremlin argues has long since been overtaken by<br>
geopolitical changes in Europe. Moscow would like to alter the treaty's bloc<br>
approach to weapons' ceilings and will undoubtedly try to win a relaxation<br>
of restrictions placed on the deployment of Russian arms in the Leningrad<br>
and North Caucasus military districts. <br>
<p>
AUTHORITARIAN GOVERNMENTS IN THE CIS: MOLDOVA BUCKS THE TREND<br>
	With Petru Lucinschi's victory over incumbent Mircea Snegur in the December<br>
1 presidential election, Moldova becomes a refreshing exception to the trend<br>
toward establishment of authoritarian presidencies in most CIS countries.<br>
Pioneered by Russia's Boris Yeltsin, and emulated most recently by the<br>
Belarusan and Armenian presidents in forms tailored to local circumstances,<br>
the model sorely tempted Snegur. The failure of his bid for reelection and<br>
personal rule signifies first and foremost the failure of that model in<br>
Moldova. The outcome, uncertain till the last moment, is to be welcomed not<br>
only on purely democratic considerations -- which are more than sufficient<br>
in themselves -- but also on pragmatic grounds. The national<br>
authoritarianism that Snegur and his latter-day allies strove to introduce<br>
could have compromised the efforts to solve the country's problems, with<br>
potential reverberations far beyond Moldova's borders. <br>
	The magnitude and complexity of those problems belie the country's small<br>
size and relative obscurity. Situated along a geopolitical fault line, and<br>
at a traditional crossroads of competing great-power interests, Moldova<br>
became the first target of unprovoked Russian military aggression and<br>
"peacemaking" in the post-Soviet period; and it is the sole European country<br>
in which Russia continues to station troops against the country's will. Its<br>
multiethnic population includes compactly settled minorities whose watchful<br>
mother countries are Russia, Ukraine, Turkey, and Bulgaria. Moscow seeks to<br>
restore some form of control over Moldova, while neighboring Romania<br>
ultimately hopes to incorporate Moldova outright. Formerly producing up to<br>
one third of the ex-USSR's marketable output of certain foodstuffs, Moldova<br>
has an immense but currently wasted agricultural export potential, whose<br>
revival requires intensive farming. On the plus side, Moldova boasts a rare<br>
degree of tension-free interethnic coexistence -- including a<br>
precedent-setting case of ethnic-territorial autonomy -- owing to tolerant<br>
official and popular attitudes. (The Transdniester conflict is not seen as<br>
interethnic by either participants or observers). Politically, that<br>
interethnic tranquillity is predicated on Moldova's independence from both<br>
Russia and Romania.<br>
<p>
SNEGUR: A CAMPAIGN TO DIVIDE<br>
	Snegur's reelection strategy entailed concessions in both of those<br>
directions, hoping for support or at least benign acceptance of his bid for<br>
a presidential regime, at the cost of concessions potentially fatal to<br>
Moldova's independence. Since embarking on his campaign, as far back as<br>
early 1995, the president ceased any serious effort at obtaining the<br>
withdrawal of Russian troops from Moldova; signed a protocol with Russia on<br>
mutual military assistance against unspecified foreign aggression; and<br>
tranquilized potential Western supporters with assurances that Boris Yeltsin<br>
was going to withdraw the troops and help settle the Transdniester conflict<br>
equitably. Internally, in a high-risk gamble, Snegur allied himself with<br>
pro-Romanian forces, particularly the Popular Front, and endorsed some of<br>
their agenda, at the same time flirting with national-Communist holdovers in<br>
Romania itself. The dynamic and dedicated Front leaders -- proving far more<br>
effective than most of the president's old guard -- ended up devising<br>
Snegur's campaign strategy, dominating his staff, writing his speeches, and<br>
setting the tone of the presidential press.<br>
	Snegur needed the Front because his newly-created personal party was slow<br>
to catch on. Named Party of Rebirth and Conciliation, and openly<br>
dedicated--along with a would-be coalition named the "Pro-Snegur Movement"<br>
-- to advance the president's fortunes, the party and Snegur himself adopted<br>
a strategy of political polarization, not conciliation. Their discourse<br>
turned highly inflammatory and openly sought to intimidate. The president<br>
routinely labeled his competitors and their supporters, including the<br>
parliamentary majority, traitors to the nation and enemies of the people;<br>
adopted the tactic of abusing specific politicians by name in his public<br>
speeches; called for the establishment of presidential rule in place of the<br>
constitution in force, which  Snegur himself had promulgated in 1994; and<br>
warned that he would "turn to the people" in a referendum to dissolve the<br>
parliament, although the constitution does not entitle the president to take<br>
any such steps.<br>
	Snegur also acted unconstitutionally in unilaterally dismissing Defense<br>
Minister Pavel Creanga when the latter refused to guarantee the military's<br>
support for Snegur's reelection. The Constitutional Court ruled the<br>
dismissal unconstitutional and reinstated the minister, but the president<br>
unlawfully declared himself in "direct command" of the army and personally<br>
took over the minister's main functions. In another disconcerting move,<br>
which defied a parliamentary vote, the president took over control of the<br>
security service for the protection of state officials, expanded it,<br>
entrusted it to the brother of the presidential party's and presidential<br>
campaign's chief, and declined to account to parliament for the financing<br>
and activities of that service.<br>
	Perhaps the central, and surely the most productive track in Snegur's<br>
reelection campaign, was his attack on the government and parliament over<br>
economic reforms. This undoubtedly accounts for a large part of Snegur's 39<br>
percent of the vote in the first round and 46 percent in the second. Snegur<br>
scuttled the pro-reform consensus that had previously united him, Lucinschi,<br>
and Prime Minister Andrei Sangheli. The president conducted a populist<br>
campaign decrying the social costs of the reforms, encouraging inflationary<br>
demands on the state budget from labor unions and professional groups, and<br>
bombarding the parliament and government with presidential messages<br>
demanding immediate disbursement of benefits and entitlements from an empty<br>
treasury. The president succeeded in pinning on Sangheli, his most feared<br>
competitor, the blame for the social costs of the reforms. It proved to be<br>
the decisive factor in holding Sangheli to only 10 percent of the vote in<br>
the first round and eliminating him from the race. But the atmosphere Snegur<br>
created through his electoral tactics may complicate his successor's task in<br>
carrying out the next stage of the reforms after the election.<br>
	It is commonplace in Moldova to observe that the boycott by Transdniester<br>
leaders of the election substantially helped Snegur because of his<br>
unpopularity in that region. As he undoubtedly realized, his reelection<br>
prospects would probably have been close to nil from the outset, had<br>
Transdniester's electorate  (41 percent Moldovan, 28 percent Ukrainian, 25<br>
percent Russian) been given an opportunity to participate in the balloting.<br>
A further commonplace observation in Chisinau is that Snegur's victory would<br>
have suited Tiraspol by relieving pressure on it to renounce secession.<br>
Snegur is widely thought to have been less than eager to bring back to the<br>
fold a region that would vote massively against him. <br>
<p>
DEMAGOGUERY UNDONE<br>
	Snegur's volte-face and the manner of his defeat bring a disappointing end<br>
to a once-promising presidency. His service includes almost eight<br>
consecutive years as Moldova's highest elected official: head of the<br>
legislature (1989-1990), president of the republic elected by the parliament<br>
(1990-91), and popularly elected president (December 1991-January 1997).<br>
Snegur contributed substantially to the national movement in the final years<br>
of Soviet rule, bravely resisted the August 1991 Soviet putsch, launched the<br>
state-building process and economic reforms in the newly independent<br>
country, and actively cultivated relations with the West. He also displayed<br>
weaknesses and made mistakes, mostly born of inexperience and provincial<br>
isolation, and correctable in time. Yet the last two years have witnessed a<br>
steady decline in his performance, a growing ambition to prolong his rule at<br>
almost any price, and an all-consuming concentration on intra-elite<br>
political conflict to the detriment of the affairs of state.<br>
	A presidential bid for personal rule may have succeeded almost by default<br>
several years ago, but by 1996 Moldovan society had evolved enough elite<br>
groups sufficiently self-confident to block the attempt. State officials who<br>
may easily have collaborated or gone along with a presidential fiat were now<br>
more difficult to find. The defense minister, the Constitutional Court, the<br>
Cabinet of ministers, the governing Agrarian-Democratic party, and the<br>
parliamentary leadership stood their ground with the constitution and the<br>
law in hand. <br>
	The strategy of intimidation proved less effective than might have been<br>
expected from a population conditioned from Soviet days to obey and vote for<br>
the number one leader and to fear reprisals for the slightest disobedience.<br>
The electorate preferred Lucinschi's more modern message, "European" image,<br>
and emphasis on the need to divide and distribute political power. His<br>
victory, fairly narrow though it is, reflects a slow maturation of Moldova's<br>
society and a break with the Soviet-era mystique of power, monolithism, and<br>
"vozhdism." It ultimately suggests that presidential regimes may not<br>
necessarily be the wave of the future in the ex-Soviet space. <br>
________________________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
"The Fortnight in Review" is prepared by Senior Analysts Elizabeth Teague<br>
(Russia), Stephen Foye (Security and Foreign Policy), Vladimir Socor<br>
(Non-Russian republics), and Analyst Igor Rotar (Chechnya and Transcaucasus). <br>
