<!-- body="start" -->
MONITOR - A DAILY BRIEFING ON THE POST-SOVIET STATES<br>
<p>
IN THIS ISSUE:<br>
<p>
* OSCE leaders decide to pursue new conventional arms talks<br>
* The dismissal of a Russian military commander generates controversy<br>
* Elections in Chechnya to proceed as planned<br>
* Chechnya tries to crack down on oil bootleggers; looks for pipeline=<br>
 profits<br>
* Russia's unpaid coal miners launch protest action<br>
* Yabloko seeks to become the democratic alternative in Russia's next<br>
presidential election<br>
* Moldova's president-elect to pursue stability and heal divisions in<br>
post-Snegur era...<br>
* ...But has overrated the importance of his contacts in Moscow<br>
<p>
NEWS:<br>
<p>
ESTONIAN MINORITY GOVERNMENT INSTALLED. A minority government took office<br>
yesterday in Estonia, following the involuntary withdrawal of the Reform<br>
party's six ministers. Prime Minister Tiit Vahi did not succeed in bringing<br>
former prime minister Edgar Savisaar's controversial Center party into the<br>
government. Vahi's Coalition party and the Rural Union bloc continue their<br>
partnership in the reshuffled government, which is said to count on the firm<br>
support of 41 out of 101 parliamentary deputies. Vahi acceded in principle<br>
to Rural Union's demand for protective customs tariffs. Estonia's highly<br>
regarded ambassador to the U.S., Toomas Ilves, takes over from the Reform<br>
party's Siim Kallas as foreign minister. (BNS, Radio Tallinn, December 2-3)<br>
<p>
RUSSIA'S NUCLEAR SAFETY AGENCY IS BROKE. The Russian Federal Committee for<br>
Nuclear and Radiation Safety -- Gosatomnadzor -- has no money, owes more<br>
than 682 million rubles, and can no longer function since its communications<br>
have been cut off. The committee monitors safety at all civilian nuclear<br>
facilities, including the Arzamas-16 and Chelyabinsk-70 nuclear centers.<br>
Besides losing domestic and international telephone and fax service, the<br>
committee can no longer use the special "Iskra" system linking it to the<br>
nuclear power plants. (Interfax, November 27, Nezavisimaya gazeta, November=<br>
 30)=20<br>
<p>
MOSCOW DENIES BIOLOGICAL WEAPONS CHARGE. A Russian Foreign Ministry<br>
spokesman on November 28 denied an accusation, leveled by a U.S. arms<br>
control official, that Moscow may be producing biological weapons. The<br>
spokesman reiterated Moscow's claim that it has never developed, produced,<br>
or stored biological weapons. John Holum, director of the U.S. Arms Control<br>
and Disarmament Agency, had made the accusation during an international<br>
conference in Geneva devoted to reviewing the 1975 Biological Weapons<br>
Convention. (Reuter, November 26; Itar-Tass, November 28)<br>
<p>
INDIAN JET DEAL WORTH ALMOST $1.5 BILLION. Boris Kuzyk, President Boris<br>
Yeltsin's assistant for military and technical cooperation, has said that<br>
the November 30 deal to supply India with up to 50 Su-30MK jet fighters was<br>
worth almost $1.5 billion. A representative of the arms export company<br>
Rosvooruzheniye said that India will get the first 8 of the aircraft by the<br>
end of next year and might eventually be licensed to build it. (Interfax,<br>
December 2)<br>
<p>
UZBEKISTAN EASES FOREIGN INVESTMENT. Joint ventures will benefit from more<br>
favorable tax regulations in Uzbekistan next year. Investments carried out<br>
in accordance with the republic's investment program will not incur taxes on<br>
profits for seven years. In addition, for joint ventures where foreign<br>
participation is 50 percent or more, the tax rate will decrease with the<br>
size of the investment. The new tax regime will also benefit existing joint<br>
ventures. (Interfax, November 30)<br>
<p>
PERSPECTIVE:<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN FEDERATION<br>
<p>
LISBON SUMMIT DECREES NEW CONVENTIONAL ARMS TALKS. Russia won little support<br>
in Lisbon yesterday during the first of a two-day Summit of the Organization<br>
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in its efforts to promote the<br>
OSCE -- rather than NATO -- as the paramount security organization in<br>
Europe. Moscow had lobbied for the same goal, with similar results, at the<br>
last OSCE Summit, in Budapest in 1994. Yesterday, Russian prime minister<br>
Viktor Chernomyrdin forcefully put forward the Russian position: NATO<br>
expansion would create new fault lines in Europe that would worsen "the<br>
whole geopolitical situation in the world=85." But to most of the 54 nations<br>
represented at the meeting, Russia's objections were a "foregone<br>
conclusion", and, as Czech prime minister Vaclav Klaus put it, they saw the<br>
need to get on with the work at hand. In his own remarks to the forum, U.S.<br>
vice president Al Gore discounted Moscow's concerns and said that NATO would<br>
press ahead with its enlargement plans. (Reuters, UPI, December 2)<br>
<p>
Perhaps the most important result of the summit's first day was the decision<br>
to, in effect, reopen the 1991 Conventional Forces in Europe (CFE) treaty.<br>
These new negotiations will commence in January in Vienna and could last as<br>
long as 18 months. Besides the 30 NATO, former Warsaw Pact, and Soviet Union<br>
successor states presently party to the treaty, other OSCE members might be<br>
included. Under the terms of the CFE treaty, these 30 countries destroyed<br>
more than 50,000 pieces of military equipment.=20<br>
<p>
Russia has longed complained, however, that the treaty has been overtaken by<br>
the geopolitical changes in Europe, especially in its bloc approach to<br>
weapons' ceilings. The Russians would also like any future arms treaty to<br>
include more than the 5 categories of weapons covered by the present<br>
document. And they have been especially upset with the restrictions placed<br>
on their deployment of arms in the Leningrad and North Caucasus military<br>
districts. At the mandated 5-year treaty review conference held earlier this<br>
year the 30 signatories amended the treaty to give Russia at least a<br>
temporary respite from these restrictions. However, although all 30 of them<br>
were to have ratified this amendment by the current summit, less than<br>
one-third actually did so. That fact suggests that Europe could well be<br>
going back to the drawing board on the issue of conventional arms.=20<br>
<p>
QUESTIONS SURROUND DISMISSAL OF RUSSIAN GROUND FORCES COMMANDER. Russia's<br>
political and military leaderships staggered into another embarrassing<br>
personnel controversy yesterday when it was announced that Ground Forces<br>
commander-in-chief Vladimir Semenov had been sacked for actions that<br>
"besmirched the honor and dignity of a serviceman and [that were]<br>
incompatible with his duties." Initial reports suggested that the dismissal<br>
order had been drawn up by the Defense Ministry leadership and approved by<br>
Boris Yeltsin. But the president's press service later clarified that<br>
Yeltsin had agreed to the dismissal in principle only, and that the decision<br>
had still to be considered by a presidential commission tasked with<br>
reviewing such high level military personnel questions. One source suggested<br>
that Semenov had been suspended, not dismissed, and Yuri Baturin, the<br>
secretary of Russia's Defense Council and the chairman of the Presidential<br>
Commission on Military Appointments, said that he had been unaware of the<br>
order for Semenov's dismissal.=20<br>
<p>
By day's end, moreover, the 56-year-old Semenov had still not managed to<br>
learn the specifics of the charges against him, and had suggested that he<br>
would fight in court to clear his name. According to one report, Semenov was<br>
told by Defense Minister Igor Rodionov only that the accusations were<br>
related to the activities of Semenov's wife, who works in the Moscow office<br>
of the Russian military helicopter manufacturer, Rosvertol. Russia's main<br>
Military Prosecutor's Office, which is known to be investigating a number of<br>
top defense officials on various corruption charges, said yesterday that<br>
Semenov figures in none of those investigations and that it possesses no<br>
materials that might have led to the general's dismissal. (Itar-Tass, Radio<br>
Russia, Interfax, AP, Reuter, December 2)<br>
<p>
Semenov's apparent sacking was all the more unexpected because it came as<br>
his star appeared to be rising. In June of this year he was promoted to Army<br>
General, and his name was bandied about at that time as a possible candidate<br>
for the vacant defense minister's post and later, and more seriously, for<br>
that of General Staff chief. Semenov's Ground Forces have been the service<br>
hardest hit by the military's funding and morale problems of recent years,<br>
and they are slated for reductions under a military reform plan currently<br>
being implemented by the Defense Ministry. But the decision last month to<br>
downgrade the status of Russia's Airborne Forces and to subordinate some<br>
paratrooper units to the military districts was a victory for Semenov and<br>
appeared to raise the possibility that the Ground Forces might regain some<br>
of their former luster. While it remains to be seen whether the dismissal of<br>
Semenov will have any impact on the Ground Forces' status, the inept way in<br>
which it was carried out only served to illustrate anew the confusion and<br>
lack of professionalism that often characterize the actions of Russia's<br>
military-political leadership.=20<br>
<p>
CHECHEN ELECTION OFFICIAL INSISTS ELECTIONS WILL PROCEED AS PLANNED. The<br>
chairman of Chechnya's Central Election Commission, Mumadi Saydaev, has<br>
denied that parliamentary and presidential elections, due to be held on<br>
January 27, will be postponed. Russian human rights activist Sergei Kovalev<br>
called last week for a postponement to allow an accurate register of voters<br>
to be drawn up. Saydaev admitted that there are difficulties with voter<br>
registration and that no solution has yet been found to the problem of where<br>
and how former residents, who fled Chechnya to escape the fighting, will<br>
vote. But he denied that these problems are sufficient reason for postponing<br>
the elections. (Itar-Tass, December 2)<br>
<p>
CHECHNYA BATTLES OIL BOOTLEGGERS, LOOKS TO SHARE IN PIPELINE PROFITS. "About<br>
3,000 tons of oil are illegally extracted in Chechnya every day. The market<br>
price for our oil is about $80 per ton. So we're losing about $240,000 every<br>
day!" Khodzhakhmed Yarikhanov, president of the Chechen oil monopoly YUNKO,<br>
told the Monitor. Homemade gasoline is sold everywhere in Chechnya. It is<br>
surprisingly easy to make: crude oil is simply distilled in a homemade<br>
still. The quality of the resulting product is low, but serviceable, if a<br>
driver is not finicky about his car. All efforts by the Chechen government<br>
to ban illegal production and trading have so far failed. Yarikhanov says<br>
the authorities intend to redouble the battle against the "oil mafias" but<br>
acknowledges that establishing a state monopoly will not be easy. "Moscow<br>
has not yet handed over a kopeck of the promised compensation. There's no<br>
work in the republic and the underground oil business is the only way many<br>
Chechens can feed their families," he told Monitor.<br>
<p>
The government in Grozny also intends to organize a guard for the Chechen<br>
sector of the pipeline which is projected to transport Azerbaijani oil to<br>
western markets. "In this case, the interests of Russia and Chechnya<br>
coincide, since we too are interested in the 'northern variant' for<br>
transporting Azerbaijani oil," Yarikhanov says. The interim agreement signed<br>
by the Russian and Chechen prime ministers on November 23 called for the<br>
question of the joint transportation of oil to be resolved by December 1,<br>
but Russian government sources now say that agreement will not be reached<br>
before the middle of this month at the earliest. (Trud, November 28) Chechen<br>
leaders will negotiate for some one-seventh or one-eighth of the profits,<br>
arguing that this proportion of the pipeline passes through Chechen=<br>
 territory.<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN COAL MINERS TO STRIKE. A national strike of indefinite duration,<br>
called for by the Independent Trade Union of Coal Miners, is scheduled to<br>
start today. Some 80 percent of the total workforce in the coal mining<br>
sector is affiliated with the union. The miners accuse the Russian<br>
government of being "neither willing nor able" to solve the problems of the<br>
industry, and their representatives have called for the government's<br>
resignation. (Interfax, November 22)<br>
<p>
The planned protest action has both economic and political aims. The<br>
workers' main economic demand is the payment of overdue wages, which, as in<br>
other sectors of the Russian economy, have reached enormous proportions.<br>
According to union deputy chairman Ivan Mokhnachuk, some 2.4 trillion rubles<br>
are now owed in unpaid wages. Non-payment by customers has been a major<br>
factor in the development of this situation: the total amount owed for<br>
unpaid coal deliveries is said to amount to 7.45 trillion rubles.(Itar-Tass,<br>
December 2) The miners also seek an increase in government support for the<br>
industry, from the 5.8 trillion rubles earmarked for it in the 1997 draft<br>
budget to a hefty 12-14 trillion rubles. (Interfax, November 22) The level<br>
of state assistance to the coal industry contained in the 1997 budget<br>
actually represents a reduction of 5 percent in nominal terms when compared<br>
to the funding currently being paid out by the government to the coal<br>
sector. (Interfax, November 23)<br>
<p>
The World Bank has been providing support to the Russian coal industry and<br>
it is expected that a decision on the granting of the second tranche of a<br>
$500 million credit will be taken after December 10. However, the president<br>
of the coal mining company Rosugol, Yuri Malyshev, has questioned the<br>
usefulness of the World Bank's assistance. According to Malyshev, little of<br>
the first $250 million given by the bank actually reached the mining regions<br>
and enterprises. Malyshev also criticized the fact that the World Bank<br>
credit can be used only to close mining pits and to improve social<br>
conditions, and not to expand the sector as might be required. Trade union<br>
leader Vitally Budko has voiced similar complaints, and has accused the<br>
government of appropriating the World Bank credit for other ends. (Interfax,<br>
November 23) Indeed, Russia's minister of labor, Gennady Melikyan, has<br>
admitted that the first tranche of the World Bank's credit was not spent<br>
directly on the coal industry. (Itar-Tass, December 2)<br>
<p>
YABLOKO TO TURN ITSELF INTO A POLITICAL PARTY. The Yabloko movement led by<br>
the economist Grigory Yavlinsky held its fifth congress near Moscow this<br>
past weekend. The main decision adopted at the two-day meeting was that<br>
Yabloko will reorganize itself over the next 2-3 years into a political<br>
party in order to be ready to contest the next presidential election, due in<br>
the year 2000. Yavlinsky said the task of the new party will be to present<br>
voters with a democratic alternative to the corrupt and oligarchic political<br>
system which, he said, has taken root in Russia today. At present, he said,<br>
the only alternatives to the present system offered to voters are<br>
nationalist or Communist ones. But he acknowledged that a major hurdle<br>
facing anyone trying to create a mass democratic party in Russia is the<br>
strong aversion among the population to the very concept of a political<br>
party; this, he said, is the legacy of the rule of the CPSU. Guests<br>
attending the two-day congress included Sergei Belyaev of the pro-government<br>
"Russia is Our Home" movement, which has also announced plans to turn itself<br>
into a party, and former Soviet president Mikhail Gorbachev. (Itar-Tass,<br>
NTV, December 1)<br>
<p>
THE WESTERN REGION<br>
<p>
MOLDOVAN PRESIDENT-ELECT OUTLINES GOALS. Petru Lucinschi, who won Moldova's<br>
December 1 presidential runoff, told his first post-election briefing<br>
yesterday that the overarching goal of his presidency will be political<br>
stability. Lucinschi, who ran as an independent candidate, said he would<br>
appoint a non-party cabinet of national trust supported by the existing<br>
parliamentary majority. He also pledged to respect the division of powers<br>
between the branches of government, to ensure political representation of<br>
various social and ethnic groups, and to negotiate actively Transdniester's<br>
autonomy within a single Moldovan state. This agenda contrasts with defeated<br>
incumbent Mircea Snegur's quest for a presidential regime, his campaign<br>
strategy based on political and ethnic polarization, and his virtual<br>
acceptance of the Russian-imposed stalemate in Transdniester.<br>
<p>
On foreign policy, Lucinschi reaffirmed Moldova's neutrality, its choice to<br>
stay out of NATO while participating in NATO's Partnership for Peace<br>
program, nonparticipation in CIS military undertakings, interest in economic<br>
cooperation with Russia, Ukraine, and non-CIS neighbor Romania, active<br>
membership in European institutions, and future accession to the European<br>
Union. Lucinschi stated that he would seek to use former contacts in Moscow<br>
in order to improve Moldovan-Russian relations, and that he would actively<br>
seek the withdrawal of Russian troops from Moldova. Except on this latter<br>
point, on which Lucinschi sounds firmer than Snegur, Lucinschi's foreign<br>
policy agenda generally seems to spell continuity with Snegur's. (Flux,<br>
Basapress, December 2)<br>
<p>
A MOSCOW CONNECTION? Lucinschi's presumed Moscow contacts (see above) date<br>
back to the end of the Gorbachev era when Lucinschi was a CPSU Politburo<br>
member and a Central Committee secretary responsible for the mass media.<br>
Those contacts are perceived in Chisinau as a political asset, but are<br>
greatly overrated and in any case politically irrelevant today. Moscow<br>
passed up several opportunities to support Lucinschi -- or for that matter<br>
Prime Minister Andrei Sangheli, Snegur's other rival -- in this election.<br>
The Russian government conspicuously declined to lean on the Transdniester<br>
authorities to allow the region's residents to vote -- a prospect feared by<br>
Snegur, whose support in that region is close to nil since his alliance with<br>
the Romanian-oriented Popular Front. Moscow also withheld from Lucinschi and<br>
Sangheli any hint of flexibility on the ratification of the interstate<br>
treaty and the implementation of the troop withdrawal agreement, which<br>
Snegur's two challengers had tried to elicit during the presidential<br>
campaign. The Duma and Federation Council embarrassed Lucinschi with two<br>
aggressively anti-Moldovan statements during and immediately after<br>
Lucinschi's pre-election visit to Moscow. Snegur's passivity in the face of<br>
faits accomplis in Transdniester appeared to suit Russian policy.<br>
<p>
Moldova's residual Party of Communists, whose candidate Vladimir Voronin<br>
received 10 percent of the vote in the first round of the presidential<br>
election, attacked Lucinschi for introducing perestroika in Moldova as its<br>
party leader in 1989-90 and ultimately breaking up that party. Nevertheless,<br>
Communist voters -- mostly ethnic Russians -- rallied behind Lucinschi in<br>
the runoff because of Snegur's alliance with nationalist pro-Romanian<br>
groups. While Snegur -- who once was a Moldovan CP Politburo member under<br>
Lucinschi -- struck up a tactical alliance with the Moldovan "right wing" in<br>
this campaign, Lucinschi positioned himself as a representative of European<br>
social-democracy.<br>
____________________________________________________________________________=<br>
