<!-- body="start" -->
November 18, 1996 <br>
 <br>
To Our Readers <br>
<i>&gt;From Bill Geimer </i><br>
	President, The Jamestown Foundation <br>
 <br>
We regret to inform you that we will be unable to continue  providing our <br>
publications to you free of charge. <br>
 <br>
For the last eighteen months, it has been our privilege to distribute <br>
Jamestown's daily Monitor, the Fortnight In Review, and Prism to thousands <br>
of readers throughout the world.  We have been gratified to learn from your <br>
comments that so many of you believe that these publications are without <br>
equal.  We agree and, moreover, are determined to make them even better in <br>
the months and years ahead.  But we cannot do this without help from you. <br>
 <br>
The Jamestown Foundation is a not-for-profit educational organization whose <br>
mission is to provide information and analysis on developments in the former <br>
Soviet Union to the widest possible audience.  The way to reach the widest <br>
possible audience is of course to distribute the publications at no cost to our <br>
readers, and we would dearly love to continue doing this.  Unfortunately, we <br>
can't. <br>
 <br>
The Monitor, Fortnight In Review, and Prism have been made possible by the <br>
generosity of a handful of private donors.  They have contributed resources to <br>
the program because they believe, as do we, that it is crucial that <br>
governments, and the policy and business communities, achieve a realistic <br>
understanding of the enormous changes which have been taking place in the <br>
FSU, and which affect the peace and security of our planet. <br>
 <br>
However the generosity of these wonderful people is necessarily finite, and <br>
the time has come for our readers to share the burden of sustaining and <br>
expanding these valuable periodicals. <br>
 <br>
As we convert our publications to a paid-subscription basis, we will look <br>
primarily to the business community for revenue.  Businesses will be <br>
expected to pay on an annual basis what consultants tell us is market value:  <br>
the daily Monitor ($1,495), the Fortnight In Review ($715), Prism ($595). <br>
 <br>
But, consistent with our educational public purpose, we will provide these <br>
publications to individuals in the academic world, and in other not-for-profit <br>
organizations, at greatly reduced rates.   <br>
 <br>
For a single annual subscription fee of $100 we will send you all three of our <br>
publications, the Monitor, the Fortnight, and Prism.  Each year we publish <br>
over 250 issues of the Monitor,  26 Fortnights, and 12 issues of Prism.  We <br>
think you'll agree that this price is, to put it mildly, a bargain. <br>
 <br>
<i>&gt;From students, we are asking a nominal annual fee of $10 for all three </i><br>
publications. <br>
 <br>
If you would like to continue to receive Jamestown's publications, please print <br>
out the form below and send it along with your payment by postal mail.  Your <br>
subscription will begin as soon as we receive your payment.  If we do not <br>
receive your order before November 29, we will remove you from our <br>
distribution list. <br>
 <br>
Again, we regret very much the need to make this change.  We hope that you <br>
understand.  <br>
 <br>
Sincerely, <br>
 <br>
William W. Geimer <br>
 <br>
