THE FORTNIGHT IN REVIEW<br>
<p>
	Russian president Boris Yeltsin's heart surgery had little immediate impact<br>
on the well-publicized intriguing that has dominated Kremlin politics and<br>
disrupted the government's decision making. Not surprisingly, this political<br>
infighting continued over the past fortnight to hamstring efforts by the<br>
Federal government to assert authority over Russia's often clamorous<br>
regions. In the area of foreign policy, a muted reaction to the results of<br>
the U.S. presidential election was pushed into the background by a bizarre<br>
spy wrangle between Washington and Moscow. Russia was more active in the<br>
"near abroad," where Moscow made a bid to secure the long-term presence of<br>
its Black Sea Fleet in Crimea, and to restore a degree of control over<br>
offshore mineral resources in the Caspian Sea. Moscow's gambits in these<br>
areas were part of a broader attempt at halting or even reversing certain<br>
processes underway since the dissolution of the USSR.<br>
<p>
PRESIDENT FOR A DAY <br>
	Viktor Chernomyrdin became president of Russia for a day on November 6,<br>
when Boris Yeltsin underwent long-awaited heart surgery and delegated his<br>
presidential powers to the prime minister. Less than 24 hours later, Yeltsin<br>
took those powers back. The president seemed keen to impress the world that<br>
he had resumed control after four months as a lame duck. Doctors said<br>
Yeltsin's recovery was going well and that the president should be back to<br>
work early in the new year. Parliamentary leader Aleksandr Shokhin quipped<br>
that the real reason for Yeltsin's hasty resumption of powers was that his<br>
aide, Anatoly Chubais, did not want to spend a minute longer than necessary<br>
playing the part of Chernomyrdin's deputy.<br>
	The Russian media, meanwhile, questioned for the first time the political<br>
role of Yeltsin's daughter, Tatyana Dyachenko. In a commentary reminiscent<br>
of the debate provoked some years ago by U.S. First Lady Hillary Clinton,<br>
the journalist Tatyana Koshkareva wrote in Nezavisimaya gazeta on November<br>
10 that family members, of course, cannot be prevented from exerting an<br>
influence over state leaders. But can anything be done, she wondered, to<br>
make such people publicly accountable? "Which is worse," Koshkareva asked:<br>
"To admit that Yeltsin's daughter has played a part in state affairs, or to<br>
continue to shroud Dyachenko's Kremlin role in a veil of mystery?"<br>
	For its part, the Duma was more than open about its concern over the role<br>
of Chief-of-Staff Chubais. Russia's constitution mentions the presidential<br>
administration but is vague about its powers and responsibilities. Now the<br>
Communist-dominated Duma has asked the Constitutional Court to rule on<br>
whether Chubais has usurped powers that the constitution formally vests in<br>
other branches of government. Chubais is indeed a powerful figure on the<br>
Kremlin scene. He has combined posts that were, in Yeltsin's first<br>
administration, exercised by three separate officials. These are the post of<br>
former chief-of-staff Sergei Filatov and the gatekeeping functions of former<br>
aide Viktor Ilyushin and bodyguard Aleksandr Korzhakov. Yeltsin, normally a<br>
master of the art of divide and rule, has allowed this to happen. Some<br>
commentators believe Yeltsin trusts Chubais because Dyachenko does so.<br>
<p>
WEAK STATE, STRONG REGIONS <br>
	Although Chubais' powers are vast, they are wielded in an environment in<br>
which the Kremlin's writ often runs little further than the Moscow<br>
ring-road. "Many Russian regions have turned into little feudal kingdoms,"<br>
Obshchaya gazeta commented this month. Chubais has indicated that the<br>
weakness of the state is his main concern, and that he is determined to<br>
correct this situation by tightening Moscow's control over the regions. The<br>
only lever he has at his disposal is financial. A large (and growing)<br>
majority of Russian regions depend on the federal center for financial<br>
support, and almost all of them are in arrears with their contributions to<br>
the federal budget. This (as well as pressure from the IMF) is why Chubais<br>
established the Extraordinary Commission on Taxation. It gives him a means<br>
of reasserting federal authority over the regions by reminding them that<br>
they do not -- as many had begun to think -- exercise unfettered control<br>
over the valuable resources on their territories.<br>
	But Chubais has a competitor in his struggle for control over the regions<br>
-- Moscow mayor Yuri Luzhkov. Luzhkov is building a network of contacts<br>
between the Moscow municipality and regions ranging from Arkhangelsk and St.<br>
Petersburg to Saratov and Kaliningrad. Luzhkov also leads an unofficial<br>
coalition of donor-regions, that is, regions which make net contributions to<br>
the federal budget. (Every fourth tax ruble is contributed by Moscow,<br>
Luzhkov likes to point out.) Luzhkov's network promotes the interests of the<br>
big Moscow-based banks and financial institutions and develops contacts that<br>
will come in useful if the Moscow mayor decides to make a bid for the<br>
presidency.<br>
<p>
CHECHNYA -- THE ONE THAT GOT AWAY? <br>
	In recent days, Luzhkov has also formed an alliance with the breakaway<br>
republic of Chechnya, taking its war-torn capital of Grozny under Moscow's<br>
patronage and promising various forms of aid. But, although Chechnya is<br>
behaving like an independent state, its leaders continue to express a strong<br>
interest in maintaining economic ties to Russia. With such considerations in<br>
mind, the parliamentarian Sergei Shakhrai has come up with a plan for<br>
establishing a free economic zone throughout Chechnya. Shakhrai hopes that<br>
the plan will satisfy the republic's demand for independence while, at the<br>
same time, creating sufficient financial inducements to persuade Chechnya to<br>
remain within Russia when, in five years time, the question of its status<br>
returns to the agenda. Shakhrai's draft is currently being debated by both<br>
government and parliament.<br>
<p>
KEEPING PEACE IN THE ARMED FORCES <br>
	Since the dissolution of the Soviet Union, Russia's president has carefully<br>
cultivated key segments of the uniformed military. With one eye on the<br>
presidency himself, Viktor Chernomyrdin has in recent months continued that<br>
policy in his role as stand-in for the ailing president. But Chernomyrdin's<br>
semi-stewardship of the Kremlin's relations with the military leadership --<br>
he has also been chairing meetings of Russia's Defense Council -- has come<br>
at a time when wage and payment arrears have combined with a host of other<br>
long-festering problems to create a near crisis situation among armed forces<br>
personnel.<br>
	Such concerns prompted Chernomyrdin to meet in Ryazan on November 1 with<br>
disgruntled soldiers and cadets from the local Airborne Forces garrison.<br>
There, Chernomyrdin conveyed the government's concern over the soldiers'<br>
plight, and pledged to clear up the wage and payment arrears. That<br>
performance was reprised on November 12, when Chernomyrdin presided over a<br>
White House meeting of Russia's political and military leaderships. Although<br>
the proceedings were reported to have ended on a positive note, it was<br>
unclear afterward whether the government would be able to guarantee the<br>
funding that the Defense Ministry appears implicitly to have requested in<br>
exchange for its commitment to cut Russia's military machine. Moreover,<br>
assurances from Chernomyrdin to the Top Brass that similar reductions would<br>
be imposed upon Russia's other "power structures" seemed likely to provoke<br>
intense opposition within the Kremlin among the powerful leaders of those<br>
agencies.<br>
<p>
POST-ELECTION RELATIONS: MORE OF THE SAME? <br>
	In general, Russia's political elite reacted with relief to incumbent<br>
president Bill Clinton's reelection victory on November 5, but few in Moscow<br>
evidenced any conviction that recent U.S. political developments presaged a<br>
new honeymoon in relations between the two countries. Some Russian observers<br>
pointed to the U.S. Republican party's continued control of Congress as a<br>
particular reason for pessimism, and there were accusations that the U.S.<br>
election results could even propel Washington to adopt a much harder line<br>
toward Russia. But, with a number of potentially divisive issues on the<br>
horizon -- including NATO enlargement and ratification of the START II<br>
Treaty -- most observers foresaw the future of bilateral relations as, at<br>
best, a mixed bag in which the two sides would continue as before to lurch<br>
between confrontation and cooperation.<br>
	Indeed, one week before the election a seemingly innocuous incident<br>
occurred that threatened to turn into a genuine diplomatic donnybrook. On<br>
October 29 the FBI arrested a former Soviet intelligence officer as he<br>
arrived at JFK airport in New York. U.S. authorities accused Aleksandr<br>
Galkin of having attempted in 1991 to procure classified documents on the<br>
Strategic Defense Initiative. The arrest incensed Russia's intelligence<br>
community, which called it a "dirty trick" and a contravention of an<br>
unspoken agreement between the two countries not to arrest former<br>
intelligence personnel. As the days passed representatives of Russia's<br>
Foreign Security Service stepped up their threats to retaliate if Galkin<br>
were not released. A full crisis was averted only at the 11th hour, when<br>
U.S. authorities agreed on November 14 to drop the charges against Galkin.<br>
<p>
MIXED SIGNALS ON NATO ENLARGEMENT <br>
	Russian policy on an issue of central importance to its entire political<br>
elite -- NATO enlargement -- took an unlikely turn on October 30 as Russia's<br>
recently appointed Security Council secretary, Ivan Rybkin, called publicly<br>
for Russia to be admitted into NATO's political structures. That remark and<br>
several other developments led several Russian dailies on November 1 to the<br>
conclusion that the Security Council would soon play a more prominent role<br>
in Russia's dealings with NATO. On the same day, moreover, it was also<br>
reported that Rybkin's remarks had reflected the well-considered position of<br>
unnamed individuals within the president's administration.<br>
	Rybkin's initiative directly contradicted Moscow's long-standing, official<br>
policy toward the Western alliance, however, and on November 5 Russian<br>
foreign minister Yevgeny Primakov effectively told Rybkin to leave diplomacy<br>
and NATO policy to the Foreign Ministry. But the rebuff was ignored, and on<br>
November 12 Rybkin again proposed that Russia join NATO, and this time added<br>
that Moscow might also look forward eventually to entering the alliance's<br>
military wing. The mixed signals coming out of Moscow appeared to leave NATO<br>
leaders perplexed, and also raised the prospect of a conflict on the issue<br>
between Russia's Security Council and its Foreign Ministry.<br>
<p>
THE BLACK SEA: RUSSIA OVERPLAYS ITS HAND <br>
	Moscow may have missed an opportunity for an advantageous settlement of its<br>
dispute with Ukraine over the ex-Soviet Black Sea Fleet and naval bases in<br>
Crimea. Barely two weeks earlier, Moscow had appeared poised for a<br>
breakthrough -- thanks to its insistence that resolution of the dispute must<br>
precede the signing of an interstate political treaty with Ukraine and<br>
Russian recognition of Ukraine's borders. Ukrainian leaders, already<br>
subjected to Russian leverage on trade and energy issues, and concerned that<br>
any of the likely successors to President Boris Yeltsin might prove even<br>
more difficult to deal with, appeared to lose their nerve. Ukrainian<br>
president Leonid Kuchma's October 24 meetings in Moscow with Yeltsin and<br>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin appeared to set the stage for a quick<br>
signing of the package of agreements on the fleet and its bases.<br>
	Yet the follow-up rounds of talks, held on October 31 and November 6 and<br>
expected to be the last, ended in renewed disagreement. Ukrainian leaders<br>
seemed to regain their bearings as Yeltsin's seemingly restored health<br>
lessened at least this source of pressure on Kiev to make concessions for a<br>
quick agreement. More importantly perhaps, hardening Russian demands,<br>
believed to have originated with Chernomyrdin, ultimately helped stiffen<br>
Kiev's spine. Officials pointed out that Ukraine had "reached the limit of<br>
concessions" after having earlier accepted a lopsided partition of the fleet<br>
in Russia's favor and its long-term basing in Ukraine, rather than either<br>
declaring the fleet Ukrainian property or setting a timetable for its<br>
withdrawal from Ukrainian territory.<br>
	The follow-up talks were "marked by tensions and a heavy atmosphere,"<br>
according to top Ukrainian officials. Russia's chief delegates, Deputy Prime<br>
Minister Valery Serov and navy commander-in-chief Adm. Feliks Gromov,<br>
presented demands aiming to maximize Russia's presence and rights in<br>
Sevastopol while minimizing those of Ukraine. The Russian side opposed the<br>
siting of Ukraine's naval command in Sevastopol, claiming this right<br>
exclusively for the Russian command. It sought to restrict Ukrainian ships<br>
to anchorages in only one bay and demanded that the coastal infrastructure<br>
in Sevastopol, as well as other bases, be transferred to Russian ownership<br>
rather than being leased to the Russian fleet. The Russian side also<br>
insisted on retaining ground-based forces attached to the fleet in excess of<br>
the ceilings set by the Conventional Forces in Europe (CFE) treaty.<br>
	The Ukrainian side, led by Deputy Prime Minister Vasyl Durdinets and First<br>
Deputy Defense Minister Col. Gen. Ivan Bizhan, asserted that the siting of<br>
Ukraine's naval command in Sevastopol and Ukrainian ownership of the coastal<br>
infrastructure to be leased to Russia are non-negotiable prerogatives of<br>
Ukrainian state sovereignty. The Ukrainian side called for the removal of<br>
the Russian ground-based forces that exceed CFE limits. And, in keeping with<br>
those CFE norms, it insisted that the agreement on the status of the Russian<br>
fleet and naval bases in Ukraine must stipulate upper limits to the forces<br>
allowed to be stationed in Ukraine as well as define the procedure for their<br>
rotation. In addition, Kiev proposed charging rent totaling between $1.4<br>
billion and $2.1 billion annually, depending on the aggregate size of the<br>
land and water areas leased to the Russian fleet. That part of the Black Sea<br>
fleet to be leased to Russia, with its coastal facilities, currently<br>
occupies 46,000 hectares of Ukrainian territory, much of it expensive<br>
Crimean land. Ukraine is willing to deduct the value of that rent from its<br>
debts to Russia, or to accept deliveries of Russian natural gas as payment<br>
for rent during the 20-year leasing period.<br>
	The Russian delegation broke off the talks, declining to set a date for<br>
their resumption, and senior military figures called for unilateral Russian<br>
action to appropriate the fleet and bases. Meanwhile, the Russian Duma<br>
threatened to discuss and adopt a draft law conferring "Russian status" on<br>
the city of Sevastopol. Only three weeks earlier, the chamber had<br>
overwhelmingly adopted a bill (which would require Federation Council and<br>
presidential approval to become law) halting the Black Sea Fleet's partition<br>
and declaring the fleet and its coastal facilities Russian property.<br>
Although such demands contradict official policy in Moscow, the Kremlin has<br>
recently begun using them as an additional argument for rushing Kiev into<br>
making concessions. For all of that, the latest rounds of talks seemed to<br>
demonstrate that excessive demands can backfire on Moscow, a result made<br>
even more likely when those demands are accompanied by territorial claims to<br>
Sevastopol from Russian presidential hopefuls or the Duma.<br>
<p>
NEW TWIST IN LEGAL BATTLE OVER CASPIAN RESOURCES <br>
	With regard to the Caspian Sea, Russian diplomacy is pressing for the<br>
adoption of a convention that would place a large part of seabed oil and gas<br>
deposits under the common jurisdiction of all the riparian states, rather<br>
than under national control. Those deposits, estimated to be immense despite<br>
still incomplete exploration, are concentrated in areas that would fall<br>
under Azerbaijani, Kazakh, or Turkmen jurisdiction if the sea and seabed<br>
were legally divided among the riparian countries.<br>
	Until very recently Moscow had refused to recognize any sectoral division<br>
in the Caspian Sea. In late October, however, Russia unveiled a new approach<br>
at the five-country negotiations on the Caspian Sea's legal status. It<br>
announced that it could accept national sectors and economic zones within<br>
certain limits, beyond which there would be created a large zone of common<br>
jurisdiction of the five countries. Moscow coordinated its position as usual<br>
with Tehran, its ally on this and other regional issues. Russian foreign<br>
minister Yevgeny Primakov officially introduced Moscow's revised proposals<br>
at the November 12 meeting in Ashgabat of the five Caspian countries'<br>
foreign ministers.<br>
	Russia now offers to recognize a 45-mile offshore economic zone for each<br>
country. It is also prepared to discuss, on a case-by-case basis, national<br>
jurisdiction over oil and gas deposits beyond the 45-mile line at sites<br>
where drilling is already in progress. All other deposits should be<br>
"commonly owned" through joint-stock companies of the five Caspian<br>
countries, Primakov insisted. Moreover, he proposed a "double-tender system"<br>
giving riparian countries first claim, ahead of non-Caspian bidders, in any<br>
future oil and gas contracts. As a sweetener he offered Russian recognition<br>
of 10- to 20-mile national fishing zones if the deal over minerals goes through.<br>
	Common jurisdiction as outlined by Primakov would entitle Russia to share<br>
in the other countries' mineral resources, secure a substantial cut in<br>
extraction projects undertaken by Western companies, impose the routing of<br>
export pipelines through Russia, and otherwise push its own interests in any<br>
decisions on production and marketing of  Caspian oil and gas. By the same<br>
token it would enable Moscow to restrict the ability of Azerbaijan,<br>
Kazakhstan, and Turkmenistan to make their own transactions with Western<br>
partners. It would also introduce an unpredictable Iranian factor into the<br>
equation.<br>
	The double-tender rule would in practice give Russian oil companies<br>
preemptive rights over Western companies in prospecting and developing new<br>
deposits. Russia could profit massively, and yet, when unable to cope with<br>
technical problems because of its own technological retardation, Russia and<br>
its oil companies could either consent to involvement by Western companies<br>
for a price or frustrate Western involvement. This would be the likely<br>
result of the "common jurisdiction" system even in the absence of any<br>
purposeful obstruction. It would create legal havoc in the Caspian Sea, draw<br>
dividing lines through Azerbaijani, Kazakhstani, and Turkmen oil and gas<br>
deposits, produce political complications, and, obviously, discourage<br>
Western investments.<br>
	The three former Soviet republics around the Caspian Sea well understand<br>
that their independence and development are at stake. Azerbaijan and<br>
Kazakhstan champion sectoral division and national, as opposed to common,<br>
jurisdiction over mineral resources. Turkmenistan avoids taking a clear-cut<br>
position on the legal issue, but has until now followed the national<br>
approach in practice. At the Ashgabat negotiations, Turkmenistan appeared<br>
swayed into signing with Russia and Iran a statement of intent to discuss<br>
the creation of a joint company for offshore oil and gas prospecting and<br>
exploration. The apparent sop to its two neighbors does not look likely to<br>
advance their agenda in any significant way. Neither did the meeting of the<br>
five foreign ministers. Its only practical result was to relegate the issue<br>
to yet another group of experts for further negotiations.<br>
<p>
"The Fortnight in Review" is prepared by Senior Analysts Elizabeth Teague<br>
(Russia), Stephen Foye (Security and Foreign Policy), and Vladimir Socor<br>
(Non-Russian republics). <br>
