<!-- body="start" -->
THE FORTNIGHT IN REVIEW<br>
<p>
RUSSIA AND THE WEST: STILL DANCING TO DIFFERENT DRUMMERS<br>
	Clashes between Moscow and Washington on arms control issues meant that, as<br>
regards security policy, the past fortnight opened and closed on sour notes.<br>
In between, the music played only slightly more sweetly, as Moscow inched<br>
grudgingly toward accommodation on NATO enlargement. Inside Russia,<br>
President Boris Yeltsin entered the final stages of preparation for heart<br>
surgery while debate raged over who, if anyone, was running the country.<br>
Meanwhile, in the heart of Europe, the age-old struggle for geopolitical<br>
influence took on new forms.<br>
<p>
STARTING AND STOPPING <br>
	Hopes that the Russian parliament might be convinced to move quickly toward<br>
ratification of the START II Treaty were dashed during U.S. defense<br>
secretary William Perry's October 17 appearance in Moscow before three<br>
parliamentary committees. Reports indicated the questioning was harsh,<br>
particularly from Vladimir Zhirinovsky and members of his so-called Liberal<br>
Democratic party. But even a relative moderate like Vladimir Lukin, head of<br>
the Duma's International Affairs Committee, said chances of ratification<br>
were minimal. Russian objections to the treaty, which was ratified by the<br>
U.S. Senate last January, seemed to center on NATO's planned expansion and<br>
the related but more general sentiment that the West is riding roughshod<br>
over Russia's security interests. Another Duma committee head, retired gen.<br>
Lev Rokhlin, complained that START II would freeze Russia's strategic<br>
inferiority vis-a-vis the West because Moscow does not have the money to<br>
take full advantage of the treaty's limits. Perry's attempts to persuade<br>
deputies that ratification of the treaty would ultimately save Russia money<br>
appeared to fall on deaf ears.<br>
	Russian fears that the U.S. intends to violate the ABM Treaty sounded the<br>
fortnight's second sour note and stoked reluctance to sign on to START II.<br>
On October 30 it was announced that Moscow had canceled at the last moment<br>
the planned signing of a "partial" U.S.-Russian agreement on distinguishing<br>
battlefield from strategic ballistic missiles. The ceremony was to have<br>
formalized a much publicized joint statement signed by Russian foreign<br>
minister Yevgeny Primakov and U.S. secretary of state Warren Christopher on<br>
September 24. That agreement dealt with long-negotiated demarcation criteria<br>
distinguishing between low speed -- or "low side" -- strategic and theater<br>
systems. The Russians apparently decided they were no longer interested in a<br>
partial agreement and would sign nothing until an agreement setting out both<br>
low and "high side" parameters was reached.<br>
<p>
EDGING TOWARD ACCOMMODATION ON NATO <br>
	Russian and Western leaders continued warily to circle each other on NATO<br>
enlargement. President Bill Clinton brought the issue into the U.S.<br>
presidential campaign when he called on October 22 for NATO to accept new<br>
members in time for the alliance's 50th anniversary in 1999. While<br>
reiterating that Moscow would be granted no veto power over NATO's admission<br>
of new members, Clinton pushed for an agreement between Moscow and Brussels<br>
and declared that Russia would be among the beneficiaries of an enlarged<br>
NATO. Moscow's cool reaction to Clinton's speech did not belie the<br>
impression that Russian leaders, despite their continuing bitterness over<br>
NATO's plans, may be moving toward a grudging acceptance of expansion.<br>
Aleksandr Lebed was the most vocal proponent of that position but, following<br>
his ouster, Defense Minister Igor Rodionov and others have also hinted at a<br>
willingness to deal with Brussels. In an article published on October 22,<br>
Primakov said Russia no longer "confines itself to an excessively negative<br>
attitude" toward expansion, and indicated that Moscow was looking instead to<br>
negotiate "rules of conduct" that would suit all parties.<br>
<p>
RUSSIA SPEAKS UP IN THE MIDDLE EAST<br>
	In what Moscow billed as an effort to raise its profile in the Middle East,<br>
Foreign Minister Primakov embarked October 28 on a five-nation tour of the<br>
region. Primakov's visit came in the wake of renewed violence between<br>
Israelis and Palestinians and at a time when U.S.-brokered peace talks had<br>
degenerated into mutual recriminations. Arriving in Egypt on October 30,<br>
Primakov urged Israel to adhere to the "land for peace" principle agreed to<br>
at the 1991 Madrid peace conference, and warned that failure to do so could<br>
provoke a new cycle of violence. But even as Moscow attempted to use its<br>
friendly relations with some of the Arab states to counter Washington's<br>
dominant influence in the region, it professed to see itself challenged for<br>
the main supporting role by the European Union and, particularly, France.<br>
Russian diplomats warned the EU against trying to supplant Russia in the<br>
region, and Primakov found himself denying that his long planned trip had<br>
been launched as a reaction to French president Jacques Chirac's tour of the<br>
region a week earlier.<br>
<p>
POWER VACUUM IN MOSCOW <br>
	Tensions sharpened in Moscow as the countdown continued toward President<br>
Boris Yeltsin's heart surgery. On October 22, Yeltsin canceled all meetings<br>
to undergo medical tests and rest prior to the operation expected to take<br>
place in early November. Anticipating a prolonged absence, Yeltsin tried to<br>
make peace among his squabbling colleagues. In a broadcast October 25, he<br>
reprimanded feuding ministers and told them to pull together or face<br>
dismissal. In place of the headstrong Aleksandr Lebed, Yeltsin appointed<br>
loyalist Ivan Rybkin as Security Council secretary and envoy to Chechnya. On<br>
his first visit to the region, Rybkin assured Chechen leaders that he would<br>
adhere to the peace accords brokered by Lebed. Turning a blind eye to<br>
developments in the breakaway republic, Moscow seemed to be reconciling<br>
itself to eventual Chechen independence.<br>
	As the date for surgery approached, Yeltsin announced the creation of a new<br>
Consultative Council consisting of himself, Prime Minister Viktor<br>
Chernomyrdin, and the speakers of the two houses of the Russian parliament.<br>
Yeltsin's aide Anatoly Chubais was to sit in for Yeltsin while he was in<br>
hospital. This placed Chubais, who admitted that the council was his<br>
brainchild, on an equal footing with the prime minister. The council was<br>
seen both as way of defusing potentially destabilizing conflicts between<br>
Chernomyrdin and Chubais and as a means of involving the Communist-dominated<br>
parliament in running the state. <br>
	At first, the council was warmly welcomed by parliamentary leaders. But<br>
before the "permanent four" could hold their first meeting, controversy<br>
erupted over Yeltsin's appointment of Boris Berezovsky, a banker and media<br>
mogul, as deputy secretary of the Security Council. Berezovsky is president<br>
of the LogoVAZ banking group and sits on the board of Russia's<br>
semi-privatized Public Television (ORT). He was one of a group of six<br>
financiers who put up $3 million to bankroll Yeltsin's reelection campaign<br>
in the summer. (Another member of the group, banker Vladimir Potanin, was<br>
appointed first deputy prime minister after the election.) Berezovsky is<br>
commonly described as a member of the "Chubais clan" of "Westernisers," as<br>
opposed to (among others) the oil and gas clan headed by Chernomyrdin and<br>
the now discredited military-industrial clan centered on disgraced<br>
presidential bodyguard Aleksandr Korzhakov. One key difference between the<br>
clans is the varying extent to which they want to open Russia up to<br>
competition from the world economy.<br>
	Duma Speaker Gennady Seleznev protested vehemently against Berezovsky's<br>
appointment. Saying he was sure Chubais was behind it, Seleznev demanded<br>
Chubais' resignation and said he would not participate in the "permanent<br>
four" as long as Chubais remained. Russian commentators concurred that<br>
Berezovsky's appointment was evidence that Chubais' "clan" had gained the<br>
upper hand in the Kremlin. Yeltsin's sickness meant he was no longer able to<br>
maintain the balance between competing clans and presidential rivals.<br>
Chubais, they wrote, was forming "a shadow cabinet" that represented a<br>
potential challenge to the official cabinet led by Chernomyrdin. Conflict<br>
between the premier and the new, within-Kremlin opposition seemed only a<br>
matter of time.<br>
<p>
RUSSIA: A WEAK STATE <br>
	Communist party leader Gennady Zyuganov capitalized on the disarray by<br>
demanding Yeltsin's resignation: "The president cannot steer the ship, which<br>
is sailing in stormy seas almost without fuel and with the officers fighting<br>
on the bridge," Zyuganov declared. But preoccupation with Kremlin intrigues<br>
sometimes obscured the real weakness of the Russian state and the fact that<br>
the Kremlin's writ often extends little further than the Moscow ring-road.<br>
In recent months, conflicts between the Kremlin and the regions have<br>
frequently resulted in defeat for the federal center. Last week, it was the<br>
turn of Tatarstan. The federal government, acutely embarrassed by its<br>
inability to collect federal taxes (as a result of which the IMF announced<br>
that it was withholding the October tranche of its extended loan to Russia),<br>
published a hit-list of companies which it accused of persistently failing<br>
to pay up. Outcry met the news that one of the companies on the list was the<br>
Kama Truck Plant, located in the Volga republic of Tatarstan which jealously<br>
guards its autonomy from Moscow. Moscow's "high-handed" behavior,<br>
"reminiscent of the [Brezhnev] era of stagnation," was furiously denounced<br>
by Tatarstan's president Shaimiev who flew to Moscow to get the decision<br>
reversed. Moscow may be able to browbeat firms in less assertive regions.<br>
But its loss of face in the Kama affair was an object lesson for those who<br>
forget that, in some arenas, the Kremlin is little more than one of a number<br>
of gangs competing for influence over Russia's increasingly differentiated<br>
regions.<br>
<p>
STRUGGLE FOR THE HEART OF EUROPE<br>
	The collapse of the USSR did not, of course, end the East-West contest. It<br>
did however move the main focus of that contest from west-central to<br>
east-central Europe. The fault-line runs today between the Baltic and the<br>
Black Seas, through the regions once described by Oscar Halecki as the<br>
"borderlands of western civilization." Those borderlands are now independent<br>
countries, but the former metropolis still seems unreconciled to their<br>
permanent independence. <br>
Russia's Foreign Ministry reacted angrily to three recent resolutions of the<br>
U.S. House of Representatives. These called for promoting Baltic security<br>
(short of admitting the three states to NATO), supporting Ukraine's<br>
independence, and encouraging the withdrawal of Russian troops from Moldova.<br>
The Russian Foreign Ministry blasted the resolutions as "prejudiced and<br>
unfriendly toward Russia" and condemned Congress for "passing judgment on<br>
the countries of the former USSR and instructing them how to manage their<br>
relations." "We do not," the Foreign Ministry went on, "accept any<br>
interference in our relations with neighboring countries... To play a<br>
constructive role in U.S.-Russian relations, Congress should revise its<br>
attitude to CIS integration." A textbook illustration of Moscow's claim to a<br>
sphere of influence in Eastern Europe, the statement recalled post-World War<br>
II pronouncements rejecting outside interference in Soviet relations with<br>
its neighbors. The statement added weight to recent assertions by Foreign<br>
Minister Primakov and other Russian officials that Moscow's attitude to the<br>
West will depend on Western and, in particular, U.S. acceptance of<br>
Russia-led "integration" of the ex-Soviet space.<br>
	The struggle over the borderlands has taken different forms in Ukraine,<br>
Belarus and Moldova. In Ukraine, it revolves around the Black Sea Fleet and<br>
its Crimean bases, protracted negotiations over which entered a new and<br>
perhaps final phase this fortnight. Some Ukrainian officials gave signs of<br>
tiring of the constant, uphill effort to assert national interests while<br>
defusing political tensions with Russia and locally, and negotiating for<br>
Russian fuel deliveries and debt relief besides. Russia's Duma increased the<br>
pressure on Kiev through two resolutions, one mandating a Russian grab of<br>
the still-undivided Black Sea Fleet and the other claiming Sevastopol for<br>
Russia. <br>
	Although Russia's Foreign Ministry distanced itself from the two Duma<br>
resolutions, many pro-government and even democratic deputies voted in favor<br>
or failed to oppose them; and Prime Minister Chernomyrdin called the Duma's<br>
action a warning to Kiev to relent on the fleet and the bases. Moreover,<br>
Chernomyrdin reiterated that the fleet dispute must be resolved before the<br>
signing of the long-delayed interstate treaty between Russia and Ukraine,<br>
which Kiev sees as a means of securing final and definitive Russian<br>
recognition of Ukraine's borders. In a demonstration of Ukraine's will to<br>
settle the fleet dispute, Ukrainian president Leonid Kuchma rushed to Moscow<br>
to meet with an ailing President Yeltsin and offer a number of additional<br>
concessions.<br>
	Claims that Sevastopol is Russian territory, made against the backdrop of<br>
Yeltsin's illness by presidential aspirants Aleksandr Lebed and Yury<br>
Luzhkov, heightened Kiev's sense of urgency. As Kuchma put it, Kiev's "sole<br>
wish" at this point is to settle the fleet dispute and sign the political<br>
treaty. Kiev seems convinced, perhaps correctly, that it ought to get such a<br>
deal as is available while Yeltsin is still in power, since Moscow could<br>
become more intractable under Yeltsin's prospective successors. Accordingly,<br>
Kiev indicated willingness to lease naval bases to Russia for 20 years and<br>
to settle for Ukrainian basing rights in only one of Sevastopol's five bays.<br>
It was perhaps these and other concessions that precipitated the<br>
resignation, on the eve of Kuchma's visit to Moscow, of no fewer than three<br>
Ukrainian admirals. Negotiations are now supposed to be completed within the<br>
next two weeks.<br>
	The Black Sea Fleet means not only ships but, more importantly, a vast if<br>
crumbling coastal infrastructure, one of the world's most strategic<br>
locations, and an opportunity for Russia to secure a bridgehead on Ukrainian<br>
territory. A Russian military presence in Crimea could fuel Russian<br>
irredentism, keep Kiev under political pressure, encourage centrifugal<br>
trends in other parts of Ukraine, and give Russia a lever over the strategic<br>
calculations of Turkey, Bulgaria, Romania and Moldova. <br>
	Russian troops are already entrenched in Moldova. Moscow denies being bound<br>
by Chernomyrdin's signature on a 1994 bilateral agreement to withdraw its<br>
troops from Moldova. This October, all the leading candidates in Moldova's<br>
upcoming presidential election -- incumbent Mircea Snegur, Speaker Petru<br>
Lucinschi and Prime Minister Andrei Sangheli -- were in Moscow for talks<br>
with Chernomyrdin and other Russian officials. Each of the three was seeking<br>
assurances -- without specifying a time-table -- that the troops would<br>
eventually be withdrawn. In a break with precedent, however, Chernomyrdin<br>
announced that he had conferred with Transdniester leader Igor Smirnov, who<br>
acts as host to Russian troops in the breakaway Moldovan region. Smirnov was<br>
in Moscow to attend a Duma committee meeting which finalized a bill giving<br>
Russian troops in Moldova the status of forces permanently stationed abroad.<br>
The Speaker of the upper house of the Russian parliament, Yegor Stroyev,<br>
indicated that Russia has not abandoned its traditional view of Moldova as<br>
Russia's southern border when he declared that "Russian-Moldovan common<br>
interests were determined as long ago as the reign of Peter the Great...<br>
They include the southern borders and the common economic space for which<br>
many generations have spilled much blood." Stroyev's view of Moldova as<br>
Russia's southern border by right of conquest is shared by Russian<br>
nationalists, Communists and Transdniester leaders but is not usually voiced<br>
by responsible officials. It must have set alarm bells ringing in Kiev,<br>
since it implies Russian reabsorption of Ukraine, which lies between Russia<br>
proper and its "southern border" in Moldova. <br>
	In Belarus, Moscow does not need not to use pressure to secure political<br>
influence and military reentry. President Aleksandr Lukashenko seeks in his<br>
own original fashion to return Belarus to Russia's political and military<br>
orbit by presidential fiat, preparatory to outright unification. Lukashenko<br>
needs discretionary powers in order to overcome resistance to his project.<br>
He has drafted a new constitution which would give him those powers and<br>
called a referendum to get his draft approved. His moves, which violate the<br>
constitution currently in force, are being resisted by parliament and the<br>
Constitutional Court. <br>
	The Constitutional Court has the power to stop the issue going to a<br>
referendum. This past fortnight, Lukashenko has threatened to dissolve both<br>
parliament and the Constitutional Court if they continue to resist his<br>
plans. The president controls the state administration, security services<br>
and mass media, and exudes confidence that the referendum will go his way.<br>
He also has the support of various levels of the Russian government from<br>
Yeltsin down. Even as he opened what seems to be the final stage of his<br>
confrontation with the legislature and the Court, Lukashenko was received by<br>
the top Russian leaders amid heavy media exposure. Official Russia needs and<br>
uses Lukashenko not just in Belarus but as a catalyst of integration in the<br>
CIS. Moscow holds up the Yeltsin-Lukashenko treaty creating a Russia-Belarus<br>
Community as an example for other CIS countries to follow, and threatens<br>
military countermeasures in Belarus as a means of discouraging NATO enlargement.<br>
	At the same time, influential elements in the Russian government have<br>
recently signaled their alarm at the heavy economic cost political<br>
unification with Belarus would impose on Russia. Moscow is also<br>
uncomfortable about some of Lukashenko's tactics and has tried to convince<br>
him that a merger of Belarus and Russia will be counterproductive if it is<br>
seen as undemocratic and imposed from above, or if it provokes serious<br>
social divisions. Official Moscow therefore wants Lukashenko to bring the<br>
legislature or at least a substantial part of it on board before he pursues<br>
his policy of "integration" with Russia. The Kremlin has accordingly advised<br>
Lukashenko to defuse the confrontation, offer parliament token concessions,<br>
and obtain the consent of the legislature before proceeding with his<br>
constitutional referendum.<br>
	Meanwhile, Lukashenko and his military officials have intensified contacts<br>
with their Russian counterparts on unifying air defense and border troops,<br>
preparatory to a possible military alliance that would entail stationing<br>
Russian troops in Belarus. Such a development would have far-reaching<br>
security implications for Belarus' neighbors. It would turn Poland into a<br>
front-line state, envelop the flanks of Latvia and Lithuania, and leapfrog<br>
Ukraine. Ukraine could find itself with Russian forces in Crimea to the<br>
east, in Transdniester to the south, and in Belarus to the west. <br>
	Lukashenko's main political opponent, Chairman of Parliament Syamyon<br>
Sharetsky, has warned that dictatorship is on the march in his country. But<br>
the stakes in Belarus transcend that country and carry implications for the<br>
post-Soviet balance of power in the heart of Europe.<br>
________________________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
"The Fortnight in Review" is prepared by Senior Analysts Elizabeth Teague<br>
(Russia), Stephen Foye (Security and Foreign Policy), and Vladimir Socor<br>
(Non-Russia republics), and Analyst Igor Rotar.<br>
