THE JAMESTOWN FOUNDATION<br>
PRISM<br>
A MONTHLY ON THE POST-SOVIET STATES<br>
<p>
Vol.II      October 1996       Part 2 <br>
________________________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
ISLAM IN THE NORTHERN CAUCASUS<br>
By Aleksei Malashenko<br>
<p>
	The significance of Islam in the social and political life of the Northern<br>
Caucasus, which was still being debated by politicians and scholars as late<br>
as the early 1990s, is no longer in doubt today. The war in Chechnya, which<br>
the local separatists declared a jihad, and the partial introduction of the<br>
Shariat laws in the Chechen Republic in August 1996, dotted the final "i."<br>
But the influence of the "Islamic factor" is far from limited to Chechnya<br>
alone. It is quite noticeable in other North Caucasus republics as well,<br>
above all, in Dagestan...<br>
	The Northern Caucasus is one of the two main regions in the Russian<br>
Federation where Muslims are compactly settled. (The other, as is<br>
well-known, is the Volga region.) There are about 4 million Muslims here,<br>
and from 15 to 22 million in Russia as a whole, depending on which count you<br>
use.<br>
	Islam did not penetrate into the Northern Caucasus all at once. In the<br>
southern part of Dagestan, where it was introduced by the Arabs, Islam began<br>
to take root in the 7th century. By the 15th century, it was established in<br>
most of Dagestan, and only by the 15th-19th centuries did it penetrate<br>
further -- into the central and western regions of the Northern Caucasus --<br>
present-day Chechnya, Ossetia, Kabardino-Balkaria, Karachai, and Cherkessia.<br>
	The establishment of Islam as the leading faith in the region was not<br>
always painless. In many cases, including in certain regions of Chechnya,<br>
Islam was established by force. One of Chechnya's most venerated heroes,<br>
Sheik Mansur, is known for his success at this type of "Islamization."<br>
	Sunni Islam is widespread in the Northern Caucasus, and its two most<br>
liberal branches, Hanifism and Shafiism, are represented in various regions<br>
of Dagestan.<br>
	At the beginning of the last century, the biggest Sufi brotherhoods --<br>
Nakshbandiya and Kadiriya -- took root in the Northern Caucasus, and<br>
continue to be influential to this day.<br>
	It is worth noting that Islam in the Northern Caucasus is of a syncretic<br>
character, assimilating elements of the [pre-Islamic] local religions, and<br>
the cult of the saints, while the Shariat coexists with the pre-Islamic<br>
local traditions and customary law, or Adat.<br>
	During the years of Soviet rule, although the influence of Islam on the<br>
lives of the peoples of the Northern Caucasus weakened, it continued to be<br>
noticeable on an everyday level, especially in rural areas. The authorities<br>
had an ambivalent attitude towards Islam and the Muslim clergy. On one hand,<br>
they waged atheist propaganda campaigns, closed the overwhelming majority of<br>
the mosques (in Dagestan, for example, out of the 2,060 mosques which had<br>
existed before the revolution, only 28 were left in 1980), and persecuted<br>
the clergy. On the other hand, especially in the 1920s, there were attempts<br>
to "adapt" Islam to the new political system, and even to its ideology.<br>
Conformist members of the clergy, in turn, gave pro-Soviet sermons,<br>
attempted to combine secular law with the norms of the Shariat, etc.<br>
	In Chechnya, there were pockets of armed resistance to Soviet rule (whose<br>
leaders interpreted their fight as a "holy war"), right up to the beginning<br>
of World War II.<br>
	In the postwar years, religious life was regulated by the Spiritual<br>
Administration [dukhovnoe upravlenie] of the Muslims of the Northern<br>
Caucasus, whose leaders were completely dependent on the center and<br>
fulfilled its instructions. At the same time, in mountain areas, Muslim<br>
communities lived in relative autonomy from the official religious<br>
structures. "Informal" religious authorities preserved the traditions of<br>
classical Islam, and succeeded in hiding from the godless authorities some<br>
of the Arabic-language religious literature which had reached the Northern<br>
Caucasus in the last century. It is interesting that the official clergy and<br>
the secular authorities, both of whom knew of the existence of this<br>
"parallel Islam," did not try to take measures against its adherents.<br>
	From the beginning of perestroika, as Soviet society liberalized, and<br>
continuing through the consequent disintegration of the Soviet Union, the<br>
role of Islam in the social and political lives of the peoples of the<br>
Northern Caucasus increased. This found concrete expression in two closely<br>
linked processes: the religious revival and the politicization of Islam.<br>
	One representative indicator of this Islamic revival is the opening of<br>
mosques previously closed by the Soviet authorities, and the building of new<br>
mosques. In Dagestan in 1995, there were, according to one count, 1,500<br>
mosques, and by another, over 5,000. In Kabardino-Balkaria, which is not<br>
known for its religious fervor, the number of mosques grew from two to nine.<br>
In 1994, a mosque was built in Adygeia, where all the mosques had been<br>
destroyed in the 1930s. Hundreds of mosques were in operation in Chechnya on<br>
the eve of the war.<br>
	But the number of mosques, which for many specialists and politicians is<br>
the most persuasive indicator of the religious revival, is, in a certain<br>
sense, only its consequence. If, at first, the opening of new mosques<br>
stimulated the growth in the religious activity of the faithful, later, the<br>
opening of new mosques, in turn, was made necessary by the needs of the<br>
Muslim communities. (Now, there is a well-known "surplus" of mosques,<br>
especially since more and more prosperous people are starting to have the<br>
desire to build "their own" mosque. Local inhabitants and specialists note<br>
that many mosques in the Northern Caucasus are not all that well-attended.)<br>
	In our view, a more weighty indicator of "re-Islamization" is the creation<br>
of a broad network of Muslim seminaries [medrese] and educational<br>
institutions. In Dagestan in 1995, there were more than 20 Islamic high<br>
schools and two Islamic universities. Religious primary schools exist<br>
everywhere. An authoritative Islamic institute has opened in Grozny.<br>
	In addition to local teachers, students are taught by people coming from<br>
other Muslim countries. Thousands of young people have received, and are<br>
still receiving, education in Turkey, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Kuwait, Jordan,<br>
and Pakistan. A young educated generation of Muslim clergy is being formed<br>
relatively quickly, which will soon be ready to occupy important positions<br>
in public and religious life in the Northern Caucasus, and is already<br>
beginning to do so.<br>
	Each North Caucasus republic has its own religious newspapers and other<br>
periodical publications. (The first and most influential newspaper of this<br>
type is "Islamskie novosti," which first came out in 1990 in Makhachkala.)<br>
Quite a bit of religious literature is coming in from abroad, including many<br>
books by authors expressing radical, or even fundamentalist, views.<br>
	In the Northern Caucasus, one notices, ever more clearly, the tendency to<br>
transform the former Soviet (or quasi-Soviet) identity into another, in<br>
which its religious, Islamic affiliation becomes the dominating factor. (By<br>
the way, this process is taking place on a more limited scale in Tatarstan<br>
as well.)<br>
	But the resurgence of the Islamic mentality does not at all mean that the<br>
level of ethnic consciousness is diminishing. The sense of belonging to the<br>
same religion coincides with a recognition of one's own ethnicity. Islam, in<br>
spite of the presence of tendencies toward Islamic solidarity, is split, as<br>
it were, into ethno-national camps. The split of the single Spiritual<br>
Administration of Muslims of the Northern Caucasus into separate branches<br>
for each republic, and especially, the formation of four "spiritual<br>
administrations" in Dagestan, along ethnic lines, is evidence of this.<br>
	The politicization of Islam, as shown by the secular authorities' appealing<br>
to Islam, and most of all, in the activity of Islamic parties and<br>
organizations, has become a factor in the Islamic revival in the Northern<br>
Caucasus, just as it has in all other Muslim countries and regions of the<br>
former USSR. Since in Islam, unlike other world religions, there is no<br>
strict distinction between spiritual and secular, and its adherents see it<br>
as a way of life, one may say that it is "legitimate" to appeal to Islam in<br>
one's social and political activity.<br>
	An appeal to Islam by the administration of an avowedly secular state, in a<br>
certain sense, is motivated by its desire to obtain additional legitimacy<br>
and authority in the eyes of the population. And, looking at it from a<br>
simple, "common sense" point of view, any ruler in a Muslim country,<br>
especially if he is a Muslim himself, is obliged, from time to time, to<br>
demonstrate his adherence to the common faith. (It is well-known that even<br>
under Soviet rule, many leaders, in situations where it was convenient and<br>
safe to their career, demonstrated their faithfulness to Muslim tradition.<br>
We may note that Islam provides for "takiya," -- concealing one's true views<br>
in the interests of the Muslim community, which could always serve for the<br>
local Communist rulers, who came from a Muslim environment, as a<br>
justification for their apostasy.)<br>
	For secular leaders, appealing to Islam has a rather multi-faceted<br>
character, ranging from introducing the Shariat in the Chechen insurgents'<br>
military units (which will be discussed later) to the financing of mosques<br>
from local government budgets, the organization of pilgrimages [hajj] to<br>
holy places, and the inclusion of "religious instruction" in school curricula.<br>
	In the 1990s, Islamic parties and organizations began to appear in the<br>
Northern Caucasus. The first of these was the all-Union Islamic Revival<br>
party [IRP], established in June 1990, which first took root in the region<br>
among the Avar ethnic group in Dagestan. Akhmed-kadi Akhtaev, a doctor by<br>
education, was elected the first Amir (leader) of the IRP. Soon after it was<br>
formed, the IRP's activity spread into many republics and regions. After the<br>
breakup of the USSR, the IRP's branches in Tajikistan and Uzbekistan were<br>
reformed into independent national parties. In the Caucasus, in spite of the<br>
efforts of Akhtaev and his supporters, especially the brothers Bagauddin and<br>
Ilias Kebedov, the party's influence was limited to northern and central<br>
Dagestan, where it had about 5,000 members. We may note that the IRP, a<br>
religious political organization, was registered by the republic's Ministry<br>
of Justice, in violation of Russian law, which requires the separation of<br>
church and state.<br>
	In 1991, the Organizational Committee of the IRP was registered in Moscow.<br>
The party managed to hold a series of regional conferences, to put out<br>
several issues of the newspaper Vakhdat, (which was soon renamed Edinstvo<br>
[Unity]); its leaders systematically spoke out in the central press...<br>
Nevertheless, the IRP never succeeded in becoming the basis for an<br>
all-Union, or all-Russian, Muslim movement. In 1994, the party "disappeared"<br>
from the all-Russian political arena. Its activists tried to shift its focus<br>
to Dagestan, but were no longer in any condition to exert any substantial<br>
influence on the situation in the republic.<br>
	In 1990, the Islamic Democratic party [IDP] was formed in Dagestan, which<br>
tried, in its ideology and practice, to unite the ideas of Islamic revival<br>
and the democratic reorganization of Russia. The IDP's chairman, Abrashit<br>
Saidov (like Akhtaev, a doctor by profession) criticized communism in its<br>
newspaper, Dagestan, and emphasized its incompatibility with Islam and<br>
democracy. In the early 90s, the IDP supported Boris Yeltsin in every way it<br>
could. Saidov himself ran for deputy of the USSR Supreme Soviet against<br>
Ramazan Abdulatipov, a prominent politician who later became chairman of the<br>
Supreme Soviet's Council of Nationalities.<br>
	In 1993, the IDP split: a group of parties, led by former athlete Surakat<br>
Asiyatilov, demanded that the IDP develop more of an Islamic "accent" in its<br>
ideology, and simultaneously, that it demonstrate more support for<br>
Dagestan's leadership. Saidov was removed from his post and became a<br>
political commentator. After his departure, the IDP was renamed the Islamic<br>
party.<br>
	Everywhere in the Northern Caucasus, small groups are forming, at times<br>
claiming to speak for all of Dagestan, or all of the Northern Caucasus, but<br>
whose activity is actually limited to a single ethnic group, local region,<br>
or even a small village. In their programs (if they have programs at all),<br>
calls for an Islamic revival and appeals to ethno-cultural identity both<br>
take a prominent place, which at times are seen as one and the same thing by<br>
these parties and circles. The "Islamic Way" party, which appeared in<br>
Chechnya in 1990, which is headed by one of Chechen separatist leader Djohar<br>
Dudaev's former allies, and later, his opponent, Bislan Gantamirov, is an<br>
organization of this sort.<br>
	With the intensification of the conflict in Chechnya, the role of Islam as<br>
a political factor in the Northern Caucasus began to grow. This was made<br>
possible by a number of circumstances:<br>
<p>
* the Chechen separatists' desire to present their action as a jihad against<br>
Russia;<br>
* their appeal to the idea of Islamic solidarity;<br>
* the aid (albeit limited) which they received from several Muslim countries;<br>
* and finally, the attempt of a number of politicians, both in Russia and in<br>
Chechnya, to present this conflict as part of a broader confrontation<br>
between Christians and Muslims.<br>
<p>
	Of course, one must not exaggerate the significance of the "Islamic factor"<br>
in this conflict, but it is also dangerous to ignore it completely.<br>
	It is clear that even Djohar Dudaev did not, at first, try to politicize<br>
Islam. He was constantly changing his mind on the significance of religion,<br>
and had been leaning towards the view that a secular form of government<br>
would be established in a future independent Chechen state. In one of his<br>
interviews, he said that "Russia forced us into Islam."<br>
	Nevertheless, the logic of resistance, and the rebel leaders' search for<br>
the optimal ideology more or less forced them to appeal to Islam. One of the<br>
main tenets of this ideology is the assertion that Russia's war against<br>
Chechnya is part of a broader Islamic-Christian conflict -- an idea which,<br>
as one may easily guess, is shared by the "hawks" in Moscow. Of course, it<br>
would be incorrect to reduce the whole ideology of the Chechen resistance to<br>
Islam alone, but all the same, its "religious accent" is becoming more<br>
pronounced.<br>
	The introduction of Shariat courts in Chechnya, which, so far, are limited<br>
to military formations, also leads us to this conclusion. This measure was,<br>
to a significant degree, forced: the Chechen leaders think that this was the<br>
reason why they were able to make their fighters and field commanders more<br>
law-abiding and governable. At the same time, the legitimization [of the<br>
Shariat] has been met with a significant amount of protest in society. There<br>
are known cases where relatives of fighters who have been punished by these<br>
courts have promised to take revenge on the judges and the executioners.<br>
	The influence of Islam on the social and political situation in the<br>
Northern Caucasus is now already well-established. Society is gradually<br>
"re-identifying" itself and the Soviet mentality is gradually being replaced<br>
by an ethno-religious mentality. All of this was fostered both by the<br>
historical fate of the region, which, from the religious point of view,<br>
belongs to the Muslim world, and by the rather tense present situation,<br>
linked to the war in Chechnya, which, to a greater or lesser extent, is<br>
attracting the attention of the Muslim world.<br>
<p>
Translated by Mark Eckert<br>
<p>
Alexei Malashenko is associated with the Moscow center of the Carnegie<br>
Endowment for International Peace.<br>
________________________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
ONE WOMAN'S CHOICE<br>
by Yelena Dikun<br>
<p>
	Ella Pamfilova entered politics on the crest of the first democratic wave<br>
in 1989, when she was elected a deputy of the USSR Supreme Soviet. In the<br>
country's highest legislative body, she was remembered for her clear voice,<br>
her sincerity, and her high ideals. The young charming woman waged a<br>
constant battle against the special privileges enjoyed by the party elite. <br>
	In 1991, she was appointed minister of social security of the population in<br>
the "government of reformers" headed by Yegor Gaidar. For three years,<br>
Pamfilova tried to solve the most difficult Russian problem -- the social<br>
problem.<br>
	But in 1994, Ella Aleksandrovna left the government "of her own volition,"<br>
slamming the door behind her on the way out. At the time, she publicly<br>
declared that all Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin's assertions that the<br>
economy had become "socially-oriented" were nothing but pure window-dressing.<br>
	After her resignation, Ella Pamfilova returned to her post as deputy, and<br>
in the State Duma, continued to work on social problems. The need is<br>
certainly there. There are 2.7 million unemployed in Russia today. In the<br>
half of 1996, the average monthly income of a worker was 714,000 rubles, and<br>
the average pensioner received 271,000 rubles a month. The minimum<br>
subsistence level was 364,000 rubles per person per month. Thus, 34.9<br>
million people, i.e., 24 percent of the population, have incomes below the<br>
minimum subsistence level.<br>
	Ella Pamfilova knows how hard it is for ordinary people to make ends meet<br>
-- and not just from the statistics. Although two and a half years have<br>
passed since she left her post as minister of social security, and became an<br>
ordinary deputy, she gets dozens of letters a day in which people describe<br>
their sorrows and misfortunes. <br>
	Here are just a few of them:<br>
<p>
	* "I am 67 years old, I am very sick, I can't walk, and I live alone. My<br>
husband died two years ago. My pension is 135,000 rubles a month. How is it<br>
possible to live on this money? 35,000 goes to rent, electricity, and the<br>
telephone bill. I can't afford to eat anything but bread. I have worked for<br>
43 years, I'm a certified veteran of labor, and what do I have to show for<br>
it? Not even a garden plot to call my own. The government promised that they<br>
would increase the pensions of people who worked during the war and had<br>
medals. But they haven't done it. When will the people at the top understand<br>
that people are starving and dying every day? Please, I beg you, show my<br>
letter to Chernomyrdin. Perhaps he'll take pity on me. I deserve better."<br>
Anna Vasilieva, Syzran, Samara oblast.<br>
<p>
	* "I am a retired woman, born in 1932, without much in the way of property.<br>
My pension is 127,000 rubles a month. I am a certified veteran of labor. I<br>
have worked for 29 years. I was an engineer-economist, and now it has turned<br>
out that I have only earned enough for bread and kasha. Meat is now only a<br>
distant memory. Even the smell of the neighbors' food coming through the<br>
window is almost too rich for me now. I am in constant need of medication --<br>
I suffer from an irregular heartbeat, and my feet hurt -- but I don't have<br>
the money for it. I can't say that things were good before -- even then, we<br>
had to count every kopek -- but then, at least, we were warmed by the hope<br>
that we would see a 'radiant future' in our lifetimes. I don't blame<br>
anybody, I don't blame the government for it, but I can't hang on like this<br>
for long. Please, I beg of you, help me if you can." Lidia Subbotina, Essentuki.<br>
<p>
	* "We are retired weavers from the mills of Ivanovo, where there are many<br>
people unemployed and poor. If you only knew how unbearable it is to live in<br>
poverty. Just as during the war, we can't get enough to eat. We're sick of<br>
seeing that the store shelves are full -- but not for someone whose<br>
pocketbook is as empty as ours: our pensions are only 100-150,000 rubles a<br>
month. Our clothes are all threadbare, but we never buy new clothes; the<br>
prices are outrageous, and our pensions are only enough for bread, milk,<br>
potatoes, and rent and utilities. The new 'Bogorodskoye' cemetery filled up<br>
in just a year and a half, and those fields were enormous. People are dying<br>
like flies, since only one out of 100 can buy medicine at 30,-50,000 a pack.<br>
They've taken everything away from retired people: our food, our friends (we<br>
have nothing to serve them when they come to visit), the movies, the<br>
bathhouse, the beauty parlor.  To be frank, we no longer believe in anyone<br>
or anything, and we'll die before things get any better. We won't even have<br>
enough for our funerals. For ten years, I salted away 'funeral money.' Now<br>
the money I've saved wouldn't buy anything more than half a kilo of the<br>
cheapest variety of sausage." Nina Smirnova, Ivanovo.<br>
<p>
	* "I am just 20 years old, but my life is already over. At the age of 18, I<br>
got called up and went to serve in the army. I served 400 days and was badly<br>
wounded 'while performing my soldierly duty.' Now, I am a first-class<br>
invalid. I can't roll over without help. I can't even lift a spoon to my<br>
mouth, and now I use my head to help my hand write this letter. I have not<br>
received any compensation for my ruined health. All I was given was a<br>
miserable pension. The government turned me, a healthy young man, into a<br>
helpless freak. I disgust even myself. But I could have been a miner or an<br>
engineer, a banker or a driver. If the government doesn't want to help those<br>
who have suffered through its own fault, then it would have been better if<br>
they had just put us to sleep, like stray dogs. Consider this letter to be<br>
my official request for euthanasia." Vladimir Kalyuzhny, Donetsk-3, Rostov<br>
oblast.<br>
	<br>
	"If people put their hopes and expectations in me, then I am simply obliged<br>
to do my best to live up to them," says Ella Pamfilova. "But the door to the<br>
executive branch structures is barred to me now: in the first place, I don't<br>
expect anything good from the present government, and second, I have broken<br>
relations with them for good. But that actually makes it easier for me. I<br>
can do and say whatever I think necessary."<br>
	Ella Pamfilova really does have unique experience in social problems. She<br>
passed through the "school of hard knocks" at the factory to which she was<br>
assigned after graduating from the Moscow Energy Institute. She worked there<br>
as a foreman, and developed a new procedure for repairing equipment for the<br>
electrical power plants in Moscow and the Moscow oblast. She headed a shop<br>
of 120 employees: some of whom had prison records. But these "tough" men<br>
elected this "weak" woman to be chairman of the factory trade union<br>
committee. And after that, at the Congress of Energy and Electrical Workers,<br>
she was nominated to run for deputy of the USSR Supreme Soviet. There were<br>
eleven other candidates on the list, all of them men, but Pamfilova once<br>
again prevailed.<br>
	Not long ago, I asked Ella Pamfilova why she doesn't take up the fight<br>
against privileges again, the fight in which she "made her name" when she<br>
was a deputy of the USSR Supreme Soviet. She answered: "Because the nature<br>
of these privileges has changed. We are no longer talking about special<br>
rations or special stores, but of abuse of power, and the settling of<br>
personal accounts and the building up of spheres of influence under the<br>
guise of 'fighting corruption.' A cynical redistribution of property is<br>
taking place. In a word, the character of the ruling elite has not changed.<br>
It's the same old corrupt, elitist, nomenklatura-bureaucratic swamp, in<br>
which everything worthwhile sinks and drowns."<br>
	Pamfilova says that when she was appointed minister of social security of<br>
the population, she naively thought that if she did something good, no one<br>
would oppose it.<br>
	Now, looking back on her time in Yegor Gaidar's government, Pamfilova<br>
admits that she had no clear conception of that government's political<br>
course. That government had its "intellectual wing" -- Yegor Gaidar,<br>
Aleksandr Shokhin, Petr Aven, Anatoly Chubais, and she had a secondary role.<br>
	But soon she understood that it was impossible for her to work like that.<br>
The problems kept snowballing: the collapse of the social security system,<br>
the liberalization of prices, delays in the payment of salaries and<br>
pensions. Then, in Ella Pamfilova's words, she began to think about cause<br>
and effect.<br>
	Ella Aleksandrovna does not deny that she probably made mistakes in her<br>
ministerial post, out of inexperience or romanticism, but, at times, she is<br>
blamed for too much. For example, some people think that she was the one who<br>
was behind the subordination of the pension fund to the government (it had<br>
been subordinated to the Supreme Soviet,) and that this, in the final<br>
analysis, was what made it run out of money. In fact, things happened a<br>
little differently. It came to Pamfilova's attention that money from the<br>
pension fund, (which was controlled by Ruslan Khasbulatov at the time) was<br>
being spent on arms for Chechnya. She reported this information to the<br>
president, and asked him to do something about it. An enormous sum of money<br>
had been concentrated in the pension fund and she saw her task as being to<br>
establish strict control over this money and to spend it rationally. This<br>
was to be the role of government. The fact that the government used to<br>
fulfill its obligations and make its payments to the fund on time, and now<br>
"liquidates" its pension debts the same way it does its payroll debts, i.e.,<br>
by delaying them for months, is another matter entirely...<br>
	Ella Pamfilova handed in her resignation from her ministerial post twice.<br>
The first time was after Yegor Gaidar was forced out of the government in<br>
late 1992. <br>
At that time, Yeltsin was able to persuade her to stay.<br>
	When Pamfilova submitted her resignation for the second time in 1994, she<br>
had a clearer reason: the reforms weren't moving forward, what went under<br>
the name of "reform" was nothing but a travesty. The raw-material producers<br>
were cynically and ignorantly tearing the country apart.<br>
	At that time, she submitted her resignation several times, but the papers<br>
always managed to get lost. Finally, however, the president gave in, but<br>
only under the condition that she would continue to work on social problems.<br>
A Council on Social Policy was formed under the presidential administration,<br>
and Pamfilova was appointed to head it. She and her small staff worked all<br>
summer and prepared an effective anti-poverty program. This was not just a<br>
statement of principles but a plan to reform wage and employment policies,<br>
tying them to investment and modernization. But when the Council presented<br>
its proposal to the government, it was told in no uncertain terms that they<br>
had no need of it.<br>
	Later, in November 1994, when the first provocation had taken place in<br>
Chechnya, Pamfilova set off for Grozny with three other Duma deputies. When<br>
they came back, Ella Pamfilova spoke quite sharply on television, on the<br>
"Podrobnosti" [Details] program, saying that the Security Council had become<br>
a collective maniac committing senseless murders, and that she hoped that<br>
the president would have nightmares about the children who were dying in the<br>
bombing raids. After that statement, the Council on Social Policy was<br>
quietly dissolved. Ella Aleksandrovna read about it in the press...<br>
	Ella Pamfilova had always been a loyal and devoted supporter of Yegor Gaidar<br>
but at the end of 1994, Pamfilova left Gaidar's faction. She explained her<br>
decision by saying that Russia's Choice had adopted a policy of appeasement<br>
towards the government. The straw which broke the camel's back was Anatoly<br>
Chubais' behavior when he agreed to take the job of first vice-premier<br>
without consulting with the faction first. "How can I understand a<br>
situation," asked Pamfilova, "in which democrats are leaving the government<br>
because it is impossible for them to work there, and reforms are being<br>
rolled back, and after all this, Chubais goes and" [enters it.]<br>
	There have been several times in Ella Pamfilova's political career in which<br>
she has tried to "build bridges" between rival male democratic leaders. For<br>
example, at the very beginning of the presidential campaign, she tried to<br>
convene a forum of democratic forces to nominate a single candidate for<br>
president. Pamfilova then held a series of negotiations with Yegor Gaidar,<br>
Grigory Yavlinsky, Boris Fedorov and others. They all warmly supported the<br>
idea in words, but, as is well-known, nothing came of it.<br>
	In spite of the fact that Pamfilova's efforts have often met with a wall of<br>
misunderstanding and indifference, she still maintains, if not romanticism,<br>
then a certain  optimism. This optimism is based on the conviction that<br>
Russians are a clever and unusually talented people. "Yes, things are bad<br>
for people. Their salaries are not being paid on time, there's corruption<br>
all around, crime is rampant, but people understand that now, at least, they<br>
have a chance to do something on their own. Quietly, more and more people<br>
are squeezing the slave out of their souls, bit by bit. Once you have enough<br>
of such people, they will no longer allow the government to behave so<br>
high-handedly," Ella Pamfilova believes.<br>
<p>
Translated by Aleksandr Kondorsky and Mark Eckert<br>
<p>
Yelena Dikun is a political columnist for Obshchaya gazeta.<br>
<p>
