MONITOR - A DAILY BRIEFING ON THE POST-SOVIET STATES<br>
<p>
IN THIS ISSUE:<br>
<p>
* Russia's government threatens tax dodgers<br>
* Chernomyrdin exhorts secret police to stay out of politics<br>
* Rybkin meets with Zavgaev, but Moscow's influence in Chechnya is eroding<br>
* Bill Clinton's remarks on NATO get a cool reception in Moscow<br>
* Russia's foreign minister outlines the Kremlin's diplomatic goals<br>
* Despite earlier portends, an agreement is reached on Black Sea Fleet...<br>
* ...But a Russian Duma bill could still impede the fleet's partition<br>
* Three Ukrainian naval commanders resign; a link to the fleet talks is seen<br>
<p>
NEWS:<br>
<p>
RUSSIA'S FINANCE MINISTER SAYS BUDGET IN TROUBLE. Finance Minister Aleksandr<br>
Livshits told the Russian Duma yesterday that falling revenues will leave<br>
the federal budget 25 percent underfinanced for the coming year despite the<br>
government's best efforts to raise tax collection and tighten spending.<br>
(UPI, October 23 See Perspective item below) His underlying message was that<br>
the government cannot meet parliament's demand to rework the 1997 federal<br>
budget. Last week, the Duma rejected the draft, demanding that the<br>
government increase planned social spending and industrial investment.<br>
<p>
IMF RUMORED TO BE CONSIDERING WITHHOLDING LATEST TRANCHE OF LOAN TO RUSSIA.<br>
Unconfirmed reports from Moscow say that the IMF is on the verge of<br>
abandoning negotiations with the Russian government and withholding the<br>
latest monthly tranche of its $10.1 billion extended Fund facility. A team<br>
of IMF experts now in Moscow is said to be unimpressed by the government's<br>
efforts to increase tax collection. (BBC World Service, October 24) The IMF<br>
withheld the tranche in July for the same reason. <br>
<p>
KULIKOV DOCUMENTS HIS ALLEGATIONS AGAINST LEBED. Russian interior minister<br>
Anatoly Kulikov has submitted to the Procurator General documents to support<br>
his allegations that Aleksandr Lebed had been building a private army and a<br>
parallel General Staff. (RTR, October 23) Kulikov's charge that Lebed was<br>
planning to seize power in a coup d'etat led to Lebed's dismissal as<br>
Security Council secretary. At the time, Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin<br>
said there was some truth to the allegations concerning the formation of a<br>
"Russian legion," but dismissed the possibility of a coup.<br>
<p>
YELTSIN TO NAME NO NATIONAL SECURITY ADVISER. Boris Yeltsin's press<br>
secretary reported on October 22 that the Russian president had decided<br>
against naming a new national security advisor to replace the departed<br>
Aleksandr Lebed. Yeltsin reportedly said that new Security Council secretary<br>
Ivan Rybkin would fulfill that role in the course of his normal activities<br>
as a "member of the presidential team." (Interfax, October 22)<br>
<p>
RUSSIA AND INDIA CLOSE TO ARMS DEAL; SIGN DEFENSE AGREEMENT. Quoting<br>
informed sources in the Indian Defense Ministry, a Russian news agency<br>
reported on October 21 that the government in New Delhi has approved a deal<br>
to buy 40 Russian Su-30 fighters for $1.8 billion. Russian defense minister<br>
Igor Rodionov is currently in New Delhi and yesterday signed an agreement<br>
with his Indian counterpart that provides for wide-ranging cooperation<br>
between the militaries of the two countries. (Itar-Tass, October 21; October 23)<br>
<p>
CHINA LOOKS TO BUY MORE SU-27S. China might buy 55 more Sukhoi Su-27 jet<br>
fighters, according to a "well-informed source" at the Seoul, Korea air<br>
show. The Chinese Air Force already has 48 of the modern jets, and has a<br>
license to build the plane itself. But Chinese production will not begin<br>
until after the turn of the century. (Itar-Tass, October 23)<br>
<p>
LUKASHENKO-GAZPROM ENTENTE CORDIALE. Construction work began yesterday on<br>
the Belarus stretch of the giant Yamal-Hamburg pipeline, which will carry 68<br>
billion cubic meters of Siberian gas annually to West European consumers.<br>
Speaking at the inaugural ceremony, Belarus president Aleksandr Lukashenko<br>
and Gazprom chairman Rem Vyakhirev both stressed that the Belarus stretch<br>
has the additional significance of providing a political link between<br>
Belarus and Russia. Vyakhirev praised Lukashenko as "the leading integrator<br>
in the CIS." Belarus has piled up almost $300 million in debts to Gazprom<br>
this year. (Interfax, October 23)<br>
<p>
UN URGES POSTPONEMENT OF ABKHAZ ELECTION. The UN Security Council has<br>
adopted a statement asking Abkhazia to call off the parliamentary election<br>
scheduled for next month. Elections can not be legitimately held until<br>
Abkhazia has a political status consistent with Georgia's sovereignty and<br>
territorial integrity. The Council called on both sides, "particularly the<br>
Abkhaz side," to resume negotiations and to achieve significant progress on<br>
a comprehensive political settlement. (Western agencies, October 22 and 23)<br>
The statement follows strong Georgian complaints over UN passivity and, most<br>
recently, pro-Abkhaz signals inconsistent with its mediating role.<br>
<p>
PERSPECTIVE:<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN FEDERATION<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN GOVERNMENT GETS TOUGH WITH TAX LAGGARDS. Russia's new commission for<br>
enforcing tax discipline has launched a high-profile campaign aimed at<br>
frightening Russian companies into paying overdue taxes. Following the<br>
commission's first meeting on October 22, Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin<br>
warned four of the country's largest companies that they will face<br>
bankruptcy proceedings if they do not pay their tax arrears within 24 hours.<br>
The hit-list included the Krasnodar oil refinery, the Moskvich auto company,<br>
the KamAZ truck plant and the Achinsk aluminum plant. Each is said to have<br>
paid less than ten percent of its taxes. Two of the companies are contesting<br>
the ultimatum: KamAZ says it was granted a tax break by presidential decree,<br>
while the Krasnodar oil refinery says taxes on its industry are unbearably<br>
high. (Itar-Tass, Reuters, AP, October 22; BBC World Service October 23)<br>
<p>
There is widespread agreement that the four companies have been picked on in<br>
an effort to frighten other companies into paying up. Chubais claimed that<br>
17 companies were on the original hit-list and that the four remaining are<br>
hard-core nonpayers. But the press has pointed out that other persistent tax<br>
laggards have escaped attention because of their political connections.<br>
Conspicuously absent are Norilsk Nickel, which was acquired by Oneksimbank<br>
last year at a time when First Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir Potanin was<br>
president of the bank, and the auto giant AvtoVAZ, which owes more in back<br>
taxes than any other Russian company but which also has influential<br>
government patrons. (Nezavisimaya gazeta, Kommersant-daily, October 16)<br>
<p>
Chernomyrdin said urgent measures must be taken to improve tax collection.<br>
First deputy chairman of the commission, Anatoly Chubais, who is believed to<br>
be the originator of the present campaign, said only 45 percent of planned<br>
budget revenues had been collected so far this month. Chubais has always<br>
been seen as tough on tax issues and his ouster from the government in<br>
January was interpreted by many companies at the time as a sign that they<br>
could stop paying. But while the slump in tax payments in the first six<br>
months of this year was attributed to the approach of the presidential<br>
election, the government has been dismayed to find that payments have not<br>
improved in the election's aftermath. The government urgently needs revenue<br>
to pay wage arrears and to ward off strikes. A nationwide day of protest is<br>
set for November 5.<br>
<p>
JITTERS IN THE KREMLIN AS YELTSIN'S ACTIVITIES DECLINE. Russian media have<br>
begun to speculate over an October 23 visit by Prime Minister Viktor<br>
Chernomyrdin and Presidential Chief of Staff Anatoly Chubais to the<br>
headquarters of the Federal Security Service on Moscow's Lubyanka Square.<br>
This was Chernomyrdin's first visit to former KGB headquarters and followed<br>
the decision by Russia's ailing President Yeltsin to transfer oversight of<br>
the "power ministries" to his prime minister. The media are interpreting the<br>
visit as a sign of Kremlin jitters that the secret police might exploit<br>
Yeltsin's increasing inactivity and absence from the political scene to<br>
intervene in the political process. The little that was officially reported<br>
of Chernomyrdin's discussions seems to bear out that interpretation. "Some<br>
individuals and groups are exploiting the processes of democratization and<br>
transformation to create extremist, armed, or terrorist formations<br>
representing a threat to society and the state," Chernomyrdin was quoted as<br>
saying. He was not just talking about Chechnya, the media concluded, for he<br>
went on to speak of the seductive temptation of "superficially easy<br>
solutions, such as 'the iron hand,' to resolve complex problems." (RTR,<br>
October 23)<br>
<p>
RYBKIN'S MEETING WITH ZAVGAEV MAY SIGNAL HARDENING OF RUSSIAN POSITION.<br>
Newly-appointed Security Council secretary Ivan Rybkin met yesterday with<br>
the head of the pro-Moscow Chechen government, Doku Zavgaev. (Interfax,<br>
October 23) Rybkin's predecessor, Aleksandr Lebed, pointedly avoided all<br>
contact with Zavgaev, and the fact that Zavgaev was not even invited to<br>
negotiations on the Chechen crisis indicated that Lebed's low view of<br>
Zavgaev's usefulness was shared by others in the Kremlin. Since Lebed's<br>
ouster, however, the Kremlin has begun again to recognize Chechnya's puppet<br>
leader. <br>
<p>
Rybkin and Zavgaev discussed the need to carry out the agreements reached<br>
between the federal side and the Chechen opposition, particularly those<br>
dealing with the rebels handing over their arms and disbanding their<br>
"illegal armed formations." They also discussed the coalition government<br>
formed by the opposition. They emphasized that all political forces in the<br>
republic -- and not just the opposition -- should be part of this government.<br>
<p>
In essence, Rybkin agreed, although not openly, with Zavgaev's criticism of<br>
Lebed's peacemaking activity. Zavgaev, for his part, found the new Security<br>
Council secretary "well-informed about the situation in the republic and the<br>
forces behind the conflict." (Interfax, October 23) This apparently<br>
insignificant phrase takes on added meaning in light of Zavgaev's earlier<br>
complaints that Lebed was poorly-informed and did not understand the nature<br>
of the conflict. <br>
<p>
It is unlikely, however, that any hardening of the Kremlin's position will<br>
seriously influence developments in the republic. On October 23 the last<br>
unit of the 104th Airborne Division left Chechnya. Only the 205th Motorized<br>
Infantry Division and scattered units from the North Caucasus Military<br>
District remain. (Interfax, October 23) Chechnya is now almost completely<br>
controlled by the forces of the Chechen resistance.<br>
<p>
MOSCOW REACTS COOLLY TO CLINTON REMARKS ON NATO. U.S. president Bill<br>
Clinton's call this week for the NATO alliance to admit new members by 1999<br>
drew a measured response from Moscow yesterday. Russian foreign minister<br>
Yevgeny Primakov refused to comment at length on Clinton's October 22<br>
speech, saying only that Moscow continues to oppose enlargement and that the<br>
Kremlin would await further developments. (Interfax, October 23; see<br>
Monitor, October 23) Clinton had said that "no country outside of NATO will<br>
have a veto" on the admission of new members, a clear reference to Moscow. <br>
<p>
Reactions to Clinton's speech in Brussels were reported to have been<br>
positive, as NATO officials suggested that White House backing for<br>
enlargement would give the alliance's plans a boost. Poland's ambassador to<br>
NATO welcomed Clinton's target date of 1999 for new members and said that<br>
"U.S. leadership in NATO has been and will be an indispensable element of<br>
European security." Alliance leaders also lauded Clinton's reaffirmation<br>
that NATO's doors will remain open to additional new members after the first<br>
group of inductees-to-be is chosen. That policy, they hope, will ease the<br>
anxieties of those emerging democracies not chosen initially. (Reuter,<br>
October 23) NATO is scheduled to hold a meeting of foreign ministers in<br>
December at which potential new members will be evaluated and the timetable<br>
for expansion discussed. <br>
<p>
THE WORLD AS SEEN FROM THE KREMLIN. In a long article published by a Russian<br>
daily, Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov provides a glimpse of the Kremlin's<br>
official world view and sets out the contours of Russia's foreign and<br>
security policies. Primakov organizes his arguments in a conceptual<br>
framework based on the familiar notion that, in the post-Cold War era,<br>
international relations are in transition from a bi-polar to a multi-polar<br>
world. He would have us believe that his prescriptions are intended to<br>
facilitate that transition. Not surprisingly, Primakov depicts NATO<br>
enlargement as "a retreat back to blocs and coalitions" and an impediment to<br>
progress toward that multi-polar world and what he describes as "a<br>
democratic world order." The practice of those in the West to divide the<br>
world into post-Cold War winners and losers also impedes this transition,<br>
Primakov argues, because it promotes a counter-tendency toward the creation<br>
of a "uni-polar world" -- i.e., led by the U.S. -- that he says is rejected<br>
by a predominant part of the world community.<br>
<p>
As the foregoing suggests, Primakov employs his elaborate framework to<br>
introduce a familiar litany of Moscow's foreign policy goals and complaints.<br>
Among them are a call for renouncing the use of economic means to achieve<br>
geopolitical goals -- despite Moscow's own heavy-handed use of such means to<br>
force CIS integration -- which includes criticism of economic sanctions<br>
imposed on Libya and Iraq and objections to anti-dumping measures allegedly<br>
employed by the West against Russian exports. Primakov speaks of the world's<br>
progress in resolving regional conflicts, but equates the international<br>
peacekeeping efforts in the former Yugoslavia and the Middle East peace<br>
process with Moscow's own military interventions in such CIS hotspots as the<br>
Dniester region and Abkhazia. Primakov also grants the CIS equal standing<br>
with established international organizations like the OSCE, the Council of<br>
Europe, and NATO, and raises the issue of international human rights to<br>
criticize the Baltic countries for what he alleges is their mistreatment of<br>
Russian-speakers. (Nezavisimaya gazeta, October 22)<br>
<p>
THE WESTERN REGION<br>
<p>
AGREEMENT REACHED ON BLACK SEA FLEET. It was announced in Moscow today that<br>
presidents Boris Yeltsin and Leonid Kuchma had reached full agreement during<br>
talks on the Black Sea Fleet, including on nettlesome basing and financial<br>
issues. Russian prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin will reportedly travel to<br>
Kiev next month to sign a final agreement on the division of the fleet.<br>
(BBC, October 24) Details of the agreement will be forthcoming.<br>
<p>
Russian deputy prime minister Valery Serov and naval commander in chief Adm.<br>
Feliks Gromov had conferred yesterday in Kiev with their Ukrainian<br>
counterparts to prepare for today's Moscow meeting of the two presidents.<br>
The Ukrainian president also met with the Russian delegation, and his<br>
Security Council secretary, Volodymyr Horbulin, insisted afterward that the<br>
sides were "closer than ever" to finalizing a package of three draft<br>
agreements. Yeltsin's foreign policy adviser Dmitry Ryurikov had disagreed,<br>
however, and the fine print of Horbulin's own remarks seemed to belie his<br>
optimism. Horbulin had indicated that, while the draft dealing with the<br>
Russian fleet's status on Ukrainian territory was "almost" ready for<br>
initialing, the draft on the terms for the fleet's partition required<br>
further negotiations, particularly on the apportionment of Sevastopol's<br>
bays. The third draft, on the lease of bases in Ukraine to Russia, "must<br>
absolutely stipulate a time frame for the lease" and the cost assessment<br>
methods, he said. (Interfax-Ukraine, UNIAN, October 23)<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN DUMA ENACTS BLACK SEA FLEET BILL. Today's fleet agreement<br>
notwithstanding, the Russian Duma yesterday adopted by a vote of 334 to 1<br>
the bill on the Black Sea Fleet whose approval on first-reading last week<br>
caused an outcry in Ukraine. (see Monitor, October 17, 18, and 22) The bill<br>
prohibits any "unilateral" reduction of the fleet's forces and manpower and<br>
defines Sevastopol as the fleet's base. It also instructs the Russian<br>
government to ensure the base's military effectiveness, along with that of<br>
the fleet. It halts the fleet's partition with Ukraine, and bans any<br>
transfer of ships or coastal forces and facilities to Ukraine until "after<br>
the entry into force of treaties which would regulate the whole range of<br>
Russian-Ukrainian relations." (Itar-Tass, October 23)<br>
<p>
In effect, the bill treats the still-undivided bulk of the ex-Soviet fleet<br>
as a Russian possession and attempts to freeze this situation indefinitely<br>
by linking its resolution to a host of political issues. The bill also<br>
affords the Duma an opportunity to shape or torpedo that resolution through<br>
the ratification process. The bill now goes to the Federation Council. <br>
<p>
UKRAINIAN ADMIRALS RESIGN. Ukrainian navy commander Adm. Volodymyr<br>
Bezkorovaynyy and two of his top aides have turned in their resignations .<br>
They have been accepted by the defense minister and forwarded to President<br>
Leonid Kuchma for final approval. Two of the three cited health grounds in<br>
their applications, but sources in the Defense Ministry speculated that the<br>
resignations could be related to the ongoing discussions with Russia over<br>
the division of the former Soviet Black Sea Fleet. On October 9 an unnamed<br>
Ukrainian official had listed in detail what he described as dangerous<br>
concessions being made to Russia in the latest drafts of the agreements on<br>
the Black Sea Fleet. Another, or additional motive, might be the obvious<br>
unhappiness in the Defense Ministry with the way the navy is being run. One<br>
report said that the ministry plans to hold an "ad hoc" meeting in the navy<br>
headquarters later this month, and that it is assigning 15 officers from the<br>
ministry to naval headquarters. (Interfax-Ukraine, October 23)<br>
<p>
CORRECTION: A meeting between the Russian and Ukrainian Presidents is<br>
expected to take place in Moscow today, and not yesterday, as the Monitor<br>
mistakenly reported on October 23. <br>
