MONITOR - A DAILY BRIEFING ON THE POST-SOVIET STATES<br>
<p>
IN THIS ISSUE:<br>
<p>
* Boris Yeltsin proposes the creation of a new "consultative council" <br>
* Regional election results leave Kremlin leaders dismayed <br>
* Chechnya's president says the peace process will continue... <br>
* ...But Yandarbiev insists on elections and compensation <br>
* Russia's paratroopers are to be subordinated to the Ground Forces <br>
* "Rightists" emerging victorious in Lithuanian parliamentary election <br>
* Criticism mounts in Ukraine over a Russian bill on the Black Sea Fleet and<br>
Sevastopol <br>
* Pakistan and Uzbekistan move toward common ground on a political<br>
settlement in Afghanistan <br>
* Turkic summit avoids politics; focuses on economic and trade issues<br>
<p>
NEWS:<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN MILITARY PRESENCE IN MOLDOVA TO BE LEGALIZED BY DUMA. Russia's Duma<br>
is about to consider a bill, submitted by deputies of the Narodovlastie and<br>
Zhirinovsky factions, that would confer on the Russian Operational Group of<br>
Forces in Moldova (the former 14th Army) an official status as forces<br>
permanently stationed abroad. The bill states that the region is one of<br>
"Russian strategic interests." Transdniester leader Igor Smirnov attended<br>
the committee meeting which finalized the bill. Russian prime minister<br>
Viktor Chernomyrdin broke precedent by officially acknowledging that he<br>
received Smirnov yesterday. (Interfax, Flux, October 21)<br>
<p>
LUZHKOV REITERATES RUSSIA'S CLAIM TO SEVASTOPOL. On the eve of an expected<br>
visit to Moscow by Ukrainian president Leonid Kuchma, Moscow mayor Yuri<br>
Luzhkov has repeated his assertion that the strategically important port of<br>
Sevastopol remained subordinate to Moscow and part of the Russian republic<br>
when the rest of Crimea when transferred to Ukraine by Nikita Khrushchev in<br>
1954. Sevastopol, he said, remains part of Russia to this day. (ORT, October<br>
21. See "Perspective" item below)<br>
<p>
MOSCOW TO PROPOSE FREE TRADE WITH U.S. Russia's foreign trade minister said<br>
yesterday that Moscow intends formally to propose a liberalization of trade<br>
relations between the U.S. and Russia with the ultimate goal of "lifting all<br>
trade and economic barriers and creating a single market." Oleg Davydov said<br>
that Moscow will make the proposals during the next session of the<br>
Gore-Chernomyrdin commission, scheduled for December or January. (Itar-Tass,<br>
October 21)<br>
<p>
COLUMBIA TO BUY RUSSIAN MILITARY HELICOPTERS. The Columbian army is to<br>
purchase 10 Mil-17 military helicopters in what has been described as a<br>
Russian "breakthrough" into the Latin American arms market. Earlier this<br>
year the two countries signed a military cooperation agreement. Peru has<br>
also purchased Soviet/Russian arms in the past. (Itar-Tass, October 18 1996)<br>
<p>
PERSPECTIVE:<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN FEDERATION<br>
<p>
YELTSIN PROPOSES NEW POLICY BODY. Russian president Boris Yeltsin dropped a<br>
bombshell yesterday when he met with the speaker of the lower house of the<br>
Russian parliament, Gennady Seleznev. Yeltsin proposed the creation of a<br>
"consultative council" made up of the heads of the top four organs of state<br>
power: himself as president, Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, and the<br>
speakers of the two houses of the Russian parliament, the Duma and the<br>
Federation Council. "There should be a permanent, so to speak, foursome,"<br>
Yeltsin said. The council should meet not less than once every two weeks to<br>
discuss "the most acute and important state problems." Yeltsin added that,<br>
as long as he himself remains in the sanitarium awaiting heart surgery, the<br>
president would be represented by his chief-of-staff, Anatoly Chubais. (RTR,<br>
Interfax, October 21)<br>
<p>
Yeltsin normally meets every Tuesday with his prime minister, and this week<br>
is no exception. It appears that Yeltsin has floated his idea for the new<br>
body without consulting Chernomyrdin, who will be presented with a fait<br>
accompli at today's meeting with the president. <br>
<p>
There is no obvious constitutional need for a new body. The Russian<br>
constitution is imperfect in many ways, but it does set up a machinery of<br>
government that is adequate to run the state even while the president is<br>
temporarily indisposed. Yeltsin has already transferred some of his powers<br>
to Chernomyrdin for the duration of his sickness, and he has (grudgingly)<br>
undertaken to sign all his powers over to the prime minister while he is<br>
undergoing surgery. It therefore appears that the new body is yet another<br>
manifestation of the ongoing power struggle in the Kremlin. From Chubais'<br>
point of view, it gives the president's chief-of-staff a body on which he<br>
will sit in the same capacity and on the same level as the prime minister.<br>
<i>&gt;From Yeltsin's point of view, the body will serve the useful function of</i><br>
putting Chubais and Chernomyrdin at loggerheads and preventing the two from<br>
ganging up against -- or together trying to oust -- Yeltsin while he is<br>
hospitalized. What the two Communist leaders of the two houses of parliament<br>
expect to get out of the arrangement is so far a mystery.<br>
<p>
Yeltsin has acted wholly in character. He has a propensity for setting up<br>
extra-constitutional bodies to perform functions that constitutional bodies<br>
are failing to fulfill to his liking. At the end of 1993, he set up a<br>
hand-picked assembly to draft a new constitution after he had firebombed the<br>
Supreme Soviet, whose job this would normally have been. Earlier this year<br>
he created the president's Political Consultative Council -- an unelected<br>
body made up of those parties that failed to win election to the Duma.<br>
<p>
KREMLIN DISMAY AT REGIONAL ELECTION RESULTS. There was dismay in pro-Russian<br>
government circles at the outcome of the six elections for regional<br>
governors held on October 20. The chief source of anguish was the<br>
overwhelming victory of nationalist Aleksandr Rutskoi in Kursk oblast.<br>
Despite desperate efforts by local officials to keep him off the ballot,<br>
Rutskoi won just under 79 percent of the vote. Also worrying for the Kremlin<br>
was a victory for the candidate of the Communist/nationalist coalition in<br>
Kirov oblast. Former Yeltsin aide Sergei Filatov called the results in Kursk<br>
and Kirov "a serious defeat for the democratic forces." The re-election of<br>
Kremlin-friendly incumbents in Kaliningrad and Sakhalin oblasts and the<br>
Jewish Autonomous oblast seemed little consolation. The Kremlin also took<br>
little solace in the indeterminate result reached in Pskov oblast, where a<br>
runoff will have to be fought in two weeks between the incumbent governor<br>
and the candidate supported by Vladimir Zhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic<br>
party. (RTR, ORT Interfax, October 21)<br>
<p>
CHECHEN PRESIDENT CONFIDENT PEACE PROCESS WILL CONTINUE... In a wide-ranging<br>
interview broadcast on Russian television last night, Chechen president<br>
Zelimkhan Yandarbiev said he regretted that ousted security supremo<br>
Aleksandr Lebed had not been allowed to finish the job he had begun, but<br>
stressed that the Chechen leadership "does not tie the outcome of<br>
negotiations to personalities." (NTV, October 21) The presence of Prime<br>
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin's signature on the joint documents signed<br>
earlier this month in Moscow signifies that the peace process will continue,<br>
Yandarbiev said. <br>
<p>
Chechen resistance leaders have never been of one mind regarding which<br>
political forces in Russia to support. During Russia's December 1995<br>
parliamentary elections, the council of commanders of the Chechen resistance<br>
forces called for a halt to raids on Russian territory in the hope that a<br>
Communist victory might lead to a cessation of hostilities on Chechen<br>
territory. But a number of influential field commanders disagreed. "There is<br>
no political force in Russia with whom it makes any sense for us to<br>
negotiate," Shamil Basayev told the Monitor at the time. Basayev seems to<br>
have been skeptical about Lebed's peacemaking activities too, since he has<br>
pointedly distanced himself from the negotiations. In last night's<br>
interview, Yandarbiev admitted that the Chechen leadership has always had to<br>
restrain uncompromising field commanders such as Shamil Basayev and Ruslan<br>
Gelayev.<br>
<p>
...INSISTS ON ELECTIONS AND COMPENSATION. Yandarbiev identified two<br>
immediate problems that need to be resolved. One is the withdrawal of<br>
Russian troops from the republic "to the last soldier." At present, several<br>
thousand Russian troops remain in Chechnya, though nearly 70 percent of<br>
Russian army units and 40 percent of Interior Ministry troops have already<br>
left, according to military sources. (Interfax, October 19) The other is<br>
Yandarbiev's insistence that Russia must compensate Chechnya for the<br>
material, social and moral damage done by Russia's military operations.<br>
Preliminary estimates of the damage amount to $150 billion, Yandarbiev said.<br>
<p>
Yandarbiev insisted that his leadership intends to hold parliamentary and<br>
presidential elections in Chechnya in January 1997, and that the new<br>
president will be sworn in as the president of the independent republic of<br>
Chechnya-Ichkeria. From Moscow's point of view, the Khasavyurt agreements<br>
call for the question of Chechnya's status to be postponed until 2001.<br>
Moscow therefore sees these elections as a violation of the accords. In<br>
Yandarbiev's opinion, there is no such contradiction: "Chechnya is an<br>
independent state and the Khasavyurt accords say only that the question of<br>
relations with the Russian Federation has to be resolved by 2001," he told<br>
Russian television last night.<br>
<p>
AIRBORNE FORCES UNDER SIEGE. Unnamed military sources report that the<br>
Airborne Forces will soon be subordinated to the main command of Russia's<br>
Ground Forces. The change reflects a lowering of the elite paratroopers'<br>
status; they are currently subordinated directly to the defense minister and<br>
General Staff chief, and serve as a reserve force under the Russia's supreme<br>
commander-in-chief, the president. (Interfax, October 19) The change also<br>
reflects a victory for Russia's Ground Forces. Almost since the creation of<br>
the Russian army in 1992 the Ground Forces command has been engaged in a<br>
seemingly losing battle with the Airborne Forces over which service would<br>
become the basis of Russia's mobile forces -- seen as the core of a<br>
restructured military machine. But the mobile forces never got off the<br>
ground, and the ousters of former defense minister Pavel Grachev and former<br>
Security Council secretary Aleksandr Lebed -- political rivals but each a<br>
former paratrooper -- appears to have worked in favor of the Ground Forces<br>
command. A General Staff deputy chief said on October 20 that, following<br>
reductions, the Airborne Forces would retain 2-3 divisions and one or two<br>
brigades. Defense Minister Igor Rodionov put the number of surviving<br>
airborne divisions at two, which in his proposed total of only 12 active<br>
divisions is a significant number. They will remain as a special and<br>
distinctive arm of service, he said. (ORT, October 20; RTV, October 19 and 20)<br>
<p>
On October 17 Russia's Defense Ministry leadership sacked an Airborne Forces<br>
general who had conducted a press conference on a day earlier, during which<br>
he made public the negative reaction of the Airborne Forces leadership to<br>
plans for the speedy disbandment of two of the elite service's current five<br>
divisions. Maj. Gen. Vladimir Kazantsev was dismissed for "violations of<br>
ethical norms" and for "discrediting the top leadership of the Defense<br>
Ministry." (Itar-Tass, October 17. See Monitor, October 16-17) Lebed was<br>
involved in the meeting that led to the press conference, and the dismissal<br>
of Kazantsev was probably aimed at least in part at punishing those who had<br>
associated themselves too publicly with the renegade security chief. <br>
<p>
THE BALTIC STATES<br>
<p>
LITHUANIAN "RIGHTISTS" WINNING ELECTION. Incomplete returns from the first<br>
round of Lithuania's parliamentary election, held on October 20, show the<br>
Fatherland Union/Conservatives capturing a plurality of the votes in the<br>
contest for the 70 parliamentary seats adjudicated by party lists. The FU/C<br>
is followed by the allied Christian Democrats and the governing,<br>
left-of-center Democratic Labor party. Another 71 seats are at stake in<br>
single-mandate constituencies, where FU/C and CD candidates have already won<br>
some seats and lead in many other localities ahead of the November 10<br>
runoff. The two parties, with some smaller allied groups and possibly also<br>
the Center Union, are set to form the new government. FU/C leaders Vytautas<br>
Landsbergis and Gediminas Vagnorius officially announced yesterday that they<br>
expect to become chairman of parliament and prime minister, respectively.<br>
(ELTA, BNS, October 21)<br>
<p>
THE WESTERN REGION<br>
<p>
OUTCRY MOUNTS IN UKRAINE OVER RUSSIAN DUMA'S FLEET BILL. Ukrainian president<br>
Leonid Kuchma yesterday telephoned Russian president Boris Yeltsin to<br>
request a meeting, tentatively scheduled for October 24, that will almost<br>
certainly be devoted to discussion of a Russian Duma bill that would halt<br>
the partition of the Black Sea Fleet and declare Sevastopol an exclusive<br>
base of the  Russian fleet. (see Monitor, October 18) With Kuchma present,<br>
the Ukrainian parliament overwhelmingly adopted a resolution warning that it<br>
would demand the immediate withdrawal of the Russian Black Sea Fleet from<br>
Ukrainian territory if the Duma's bill becomes law. The parliament described<br>
the Duma's bill as "openly anti-Ukrainian," as "reaffirming territorial<br>
claims" vis-a-vis Russian jurisdiction over Sevastopol, and as destabilizing<br>
for regional and international security. In a demonstration of national<br>
consensus, Aleksandr Moroz -- the parliament's Socialist chairman and a<br>
political rival of Kuchma -- shepherded the resolution and was publicly<br>
thanked by Kuchma. <br>
<p>
Foreign Minister Hennady Udovenko, meanwhile, said in a Russian press<br>
interview that Kiev is "constantly concerned by Russian attempts to question<br>
Ukraine's sovereignty and integrity. There will be no return  to the past."<br>
Justice Minister Serhy Holovaty saw the Duma's bill as a first step toward<br>
conferring on the Black Sea Fleet official status as a Russian force<br>
deployed abroad (see also Moldova item in News section above); and he<br>
cautioned that Yeltsin may be politically or physically unable to veto it.<br>
(UNIAN, Interfax-Ukraine, October 18-21)<br>
<p>
Russian prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said last week that he "hopes" to<br>
visit Kiev shortly to sign an agreement on the fleet's partition based on<br>
terms set "in principle" by the two presidents. That would relegate<br>
agreements on the Russian fleet's legal status in Ukraine and on related<br>
leasing conditions to a later time. But Kiev has all along insisted on a<br>
"package solution" that would include agreements on legal and leasing<br>
issues, rightly anticipating that it would be even more difficult to obtain<br>
recognition of Ukrainian sovereign jurisdiction over Russian naval bases<br>
after the fleet has been divided. <br>
<p>
CENTRAL ASIA<br>
<p>
UZBEKISTAN, PAKISTAN RECONCILING POSITIONS ON AFGHANISTAN. Following three<br>
days of talks in Tashkent, Uzbek president Islam Karimov and his Pakistani<br>
counterpart, Faruk Ahmad-khan Leghari, agreed that a resolution of the<br>
conflict in Afghanistan requires a representative government there comprised<br>
of all ethnic, regional, and religious forces. That government should be<br>
formed, they agreed, through direct negotiations among all those forces<br>
under the aegis of the United Nations and the Islamic Conference. The two<br>
presidents called for an immediate termination of hostilities and the<br>
commencement of talks to form a national conciliation government. Leghari<br>
officially endorsed Karimov's proposal for an international embargo on arms<br>
deliveries to Afghanistan. Karimov and Leghari also agreed on the need to<br>
prevent the inter-Afghan conflict from damaging Uzbek-Pakistani relations.<br>
Pakistan underwrites the Taliban, the Islamic movement that last month<br>
captured Kabul. <br>
<p>
The two presidents also discussed in detail proposed oil and gas pipelines<br>
and a transit corridor from Central Asia via Afghanistan to Pakistan's coast<br>
on the Indian Ocean. A possible route considered at the meeting would run<br>
from Termez in Uzbekistan to Mazar-i-Sharif in the ethnic Uzbek area of<br>
Afghanistan, and across Taliban-controlled territory to Pakistan and its<br>
port city Karachi. (Interfax, Western agencies, October 18 through 21)<br>
Turkmenistan is already on board the Pakistan-promoted project and has<br>
normal relations with the Taliban.<br>
<p>
Uzbekistan has strong cards to play in the region. It wields influence in<br>
the ethnic Uzbek areas of Afghanistan and Tajikistan and supports Ahmad<br>
Rashid Dostum's troops. Still not involved in the fighting, they are the<br>
strongest anti-Taliban force in Afghanistan. Uzbekistan's reaction to the<br>
successes of the Taliban has been alarmist, unintentionally playing into the<br>
hands of Russian diplomacy and potentially undermining Karimov's own effort<br>
to maximize Uzbekistan's independence from Russia. An Uzbek-Pakistani<br>
consensus, such as that apparently emerging from the Karimov-Leghari talks,<br>
with the added incentive of the Pakistan-promoted trans-Afghan transit<br>
corridor, could play an important role in pacifying the region and reducing<br>
the openings for Russia's reentry. <br>
<p>
TURKIC SUMMIT FOCUSES ON REGIONAL ECONOMICS. The presidents of Turkey,<br>
Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan, and Uzbekistan met in the<br>
Uzbek capital Tashkent on October 20-21 for the annual summit of the Turkic<br>
countries. The presidents reaffirmed their countries' commitment to market<br>
economics and discussed measures to expand regional economic links through<br>
commercial and customs facilities, telecommunications, and overland routes<br>
and pipelines to export Central Asian commodities to international markets.<br>
They also endorsed the plans of the Transcaucasus countries and Pakistan to<br>
create internationally-financed transit corridors that would provide Central<br>
Asia with export outlets to the Mediterranean Sea and the Indian Ocean. <br>
<p>
The conferees on the whole avoided discussion of political issues, and<br>
claimed that they did not discuss the situation in Afghanistan and<br>
Tajikistan. They issued a general condemnation of "the phenomenon of<br>
separatism and terrorism" and called for international cooperation to resist<br>
it. Timed to Uzbekistan's celebration of the 660th anniversary of the birth<br>
of Tamerlane, the summit also discussed joint observances of anniversaries<br>
of historic figures and events common to Turkic peoples. (Interfax, Western<br>
agencies, October 20 and 21)<br>
<p>
This was the fourth Turkic summit, and the next one is scheduled for 1997 in<br>
Kazakhstan. Initial omens that such summits would become a vehicle for an<br>
assertive Turkish role in Central Asia have not been borne out. The summits<br>
have increasingly eschewed political, let alone security issues, focusing on<br>
economics and culture -- the latter seen through a decidedly lay prism<br>
consistent with these countries' secular orientation. The countries'<br>
emphasis on individual state-building has precluded pan-Turkism.<br>
_____________________________________________________________________<br>
