THE FORTNIGHT IN REVIEW -- A BI-WEEKLY ON THE POST-SOVIET STATES<br>
<p>
<p>
The past two weeks have seen high drama in Moscow, culminating in President<br>
Boris Yeltsin's dismissal of Aleksandr Lebed just months after his<br>
appointment as national security adviser. There was relief when, rather than<br>
resorting to force, Lebed vowed to continue the struggle by constitutional<br>
means. But recent developments in Armenia, Belarus and Moldova, where<br>
elected presidents are using undemocratic methods to cling to power,<br>
underline the fact that other parts of the former Soviet empire also remain<br>
as enigmatic and unpredictable as ever.<br>
<p>
Lebed Latest Casualty of Kremlin Infighting <br>
	Feuding erupted in the Moscow when Russian Interior Minister Anatoly<br>
Kulikov accused his rival, national security chief Aleksandr Lebed, of<br>
plotting to seize power in a coup d'etat. Kulikov had earlier accused Lebed<br>
of betraying Russia's interests and capitulating to the Chechen opposition<br>
by brokering an August cease-fire. Now Kulikov claimed that Lebed was<br>
mustering a secret force and plotting political assassinations with the help<br>
of Chechen gunmen. Dismissing the charges, Lebed demanded a meeting with<br>
ailing President Boris Yeltsin. And, for the third time in two months, Lebed<br>
threatened to resign.<br>
	Yeltsin was at pains to show that he was still in control of events.<br>
Appearing on Russian television on October 17, the frail-looking president<br>
announced that he was sacking Lebed as Security Council secretary. Yeltsin<br>
said he could no longer tolerate Lebed's "mistakes," his quarreling with<br>
government ministers, and his habit of taking of decisions without proper<br>
authority. Yeltsin made it clear, too, that he was irritated by Lebed's<br>
presidential ambitions.<br>
	Yeltsin made no reference to the coup allegations that sparked the crisis,<br>
confirming suspicions that Kulikov's charges were a pretext to remove Lebed<br>
from office. The clash between the two security chiefs seemed to spring from<br>
more than mere personal rivalry and to mark a power struggle between rival<br>
Kremlin clans, jockeying to fill the vacuum created by Yeltsin's prolonged<br>
hospitalization. There were as a result widespread expectations that that<br>
fresh splits would soon appear and that other sackings were likely to follow.<br>
<p>
Ouster Casts Cloud Over Chechnya Peace Process <br>
	There was confusion in Moscow over what Lebed's ouster would mean for the<br>
Chechen peace process. Lebed warned it could lead to disaster. Chechen<br>
opposition leaders also reacted with alarm to signs that the Kremlin "war<br>
party" was in the ascendant. What happens in Chechnya may prove as important<br>
as the state of Yeltsin's health in determining future developments in<br>
Moscow. If Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin manages to assert control, he<br>
will be under strong pressure to continue the peace process as a means of<br>
boosting his own presidential prospects. But if Kulikov and the war party<br>
gain control of Moscow's policy toward Chechnya, renewed bloodshed seems the<br>
unhappy probability and popular sympathy for Lebed will grow.<br>
<p>
Chechens Press on Regardless <br>
	While Russia's leaders exchanged threats and accusations, Chechen<br>
opposition leaders pressed ahead with the construction of state institutions<br>
in the breakaway republic. The final touches were being put to a provisional<br>
coalition government, to be led by Aslan Maskhadov. Opposition leaders also<br>
announced that presidential and parliamentary elections would be held in<br>
late January. Moscow officials, taken aback, objected that January was too<br>
soon and that Chechen leaders had no right to take unilateral decisions on<br>
such important matters. Given the lack of consensus in Moscow, however,<br>
there seemed little Moscow could do to prevent the Chechen leadership from<br>
carrying out their plans.<br>
<p>
Skirmishing Over Military Reform<br>
Russia's military reform lurched uncertainly into gear in early October, but<br>
the accompanying Kremlin intrigue suggested that personalities and politics<br>
remained more important than policies in the Russian defense establishment.<br>
Developments were keyed by the first meeting of Russia's recently-created<br>
Defense Council on October 4, at which government leaders and chiefs of<br>
Russia's armed forces and security structures examined proposals for reform.<br>
Reports of the closed-door meeting indicated that participants approved a<br>
Defense Ministry proposal to cut the size of the regular armed forces from<br>
1.5 to 1.2 million men while liquidating scores of low-readiness or<br>
poorly-manned units. The transition to an all-volunteer force, which<br>
President Yeltsin pledged during his campaign would be completed by the year<br>
2000, will instead be delayed until the year 2005. Reports also suggested<br>
that military spending will rise next year to cover current funding arrears<br>
and to pay for the proposed reductions, but the longer-term goal was said to<br>
be a smaller military that would be cheaper to maintain.<br>
	Politically, the October 4 meeting highlighted the potential importance of<br>
the Defense Council as a counterweight to Aleksandr Lebed's Security<br>
Council. Indeed, Lebed chose pointedly not to attend the meeting, which was<br>
presided over by Prime Minister Chernomyrdin. Lebed's absence was also at<br>
least in part a result of Yeltsin's decision a week earlier to name Defense<br>
Council secretary Yury Baturin -- not Lebed -- as head of a presidential<br>
commission overseeing appointments to top defense posts. Baturin's<br>
appointment at last cleared the way for Defense Minister Igor Rodionov to<br>
begin consolidating his position within the military bureaucracy. On October<br>
4 it was announced that Rodionov had been promoted to Army General and that<br>
six top commanders -- all said to be opponents of the announced defense cuts<br>
-- had been dismissed. Russian commentators suggested that Lebed's influence<br>
within the defense establishment had been weakened by his failure to win<br>
control over top appointments, and that adroit maneuvering by his opponents<br>
might also have weakened ties between Lebed and Rodionov.<br>
	Lebed returned the fray on October 16, lambasting a General Staff directive<br>
that ordered reductions in Russia's elite Airborne forces. Those cuts had<br>
been anticipated following the October 4 meeting and, indeed, the outspoken<br>
commander of the Airborne troops had been among the six generals dismissed<br>
on that day. Lebed characterized the directive as a product of Kremlin<br>
intrigues that, he claimed, were really aimed at destroying the Airborne<br>
Forces altogether. The retired general (and former Airborne commander)<br>
alleged that the directive was part of a mistaken and dangerous effort to<br>
decentralize the government and the army, and warned that its implementation<br>
could ignite a social explosion and further inflame dissatisfaction with the<br>
armed forces.<br>
<p>
Lebed Puzzles NATO <br>
	During and after a visit to NATO headquarters in Brussels on October 6-8<br>
(his first visit to the West), Aleksandr Lebed surprised audiences by<br>
depicting the West as "civilized" and the alliance as an organization with<br>
which Russia could do business. Although he reiterated Russian objections to<br>
NATO's enlargement, Lebed deplored the confrontational policy toward NATO<br>
that Russia has pursued to date, and said that Moscow was foolish not to<br>
participate more actively in the Partnership for Peace program. Lebed's<br>
accommodating words drew fire from the Russian Duma, which demanded that he<br>
appear before them later this month. His remarks also left the Foreign<br>
Ministry scrambling to restate its categorical opposition to enlargement and<br>
its demand that any political agreement with NATO must grant Moscow a voice<br>
in the alliance's affairs. Lebed had criticized the alliance on several<br>
occasions before traveling to Brussels, and his behavior on that occasion<br>
may have been aimed at appearing "presidential" in his first appearance on<br>
the world stage. Informed sources told the Jamestown Foundation, too, that<br>
high-ranking NATO officials were left in confusion by the way in which Lebed<br>
switched in Brussels from one line in one meeting to an apparently<br>
contradictory one in the next. In their public reactions, therefore, Western<br>
leaders welcomed Lebed's constructive remarks; privately, they expressed<br>
uncertainty whether Lebed's statements represented a real departure from the<br>
Kremlin's official hard line. <br>
<p>
Russia Judged World's Most Dangerous Emerging Market <br>
	Financial markets were briefly unsettled by the fireworks between Kulikov<br>
and Lebed, but quickly returned to normal as investors concluded that<br>
allegations of private armies and coups d'etats were made for political<br>
effect. Many investors seem now to have decided that the potential rewards<br>
of investing in Russia outweigh the risks. Earlier this month, U.S. and<br>
European credit-rating agencies awarded Russia its first long-term credit<br>
rating since the 1917 Revolution. Russia's BB grading was higher than<br>
expected, and put it on a level with Hungary, Mexico, India and Slovakia. A<br>
different picture emerged, however, from a study of political risk in<br>
emerging markets conducted by the Merchant International Group (MIG). On the<br>
basis of personal interviews with 2,500 western business people, MIG<br>
concluded that corruption, fraud and bureaucratic delays make Russia a<br>
riskier place to do business than Mexico, Venezuela, Brazil or Indonesia --<br>
though less than Nigeria.<br>
	The slow progress of Russia's application to join the World Trade<br>
Organization (WTO) also underlined the gap between Moscow's aspirations and<br>
achievements. A high-level Russian delegation was in Geneva on October 15-16<br>
for a further, inconclusive round of negotiations on Russia's application.<br>
Russia still has to convince the WTO that its trading practices are in line<br>
with world standards. Doubt centers on the lack of predictability and<br>
transparency in Russia's trade reforms. There has been a considerable<br>
liberalization of Russian trade, including the establishment of<br>
current-account ruble convertibility and abandonment of almost all direct<br>
administrative controls on exports and imports. But domestic price controls<br>
on oil have not been completely removed; subsidies to coal, steel and other<br>
producers are understood to continue; and there has recently been some<br>
tendency to raise protective import duties. Beyond those specific issues,<br>
there is a widespread perception that Russian economic policy-making remains<br>
unstable. That includes the making of foreign economic policy, where changes<br>
in tariffs, the granting to government cronies of exemptions from the<br>
payment of duties, and abrupt and sometimes retroactive changes in the tax<br>
regime facing foreign companies in Russia have all drawn adverse comment.<br>
The credibility of the Russian government as a partner in the development of<br>
world trading policies still remains rather low. A period of stable and<br>
consistent conduct of trade policy in Moscow is probably needed before<br>
Russia is likely to be treated more warmly in international organizations<br>
such as the WTO.<br>
<p>
ELSEWHERE IN THE CIS, DEMOCRACY TAKES A TUMBLE <br>
<p>
	Old habits die hard. Still taking their cue from Moscow and following in<br>
Yeltsin's footsteps, the presidents of Belarus, Armenia and Moldova have<br>
redoubled their efforts to concentrate state power in their own hands. The<br>
three presidents vary in personality and temperament and their countries<br>
differ in many important aspects. All three presidents have nonetheless<br>
embarked on the road to personal and authoritarian rule, seeking to control<br>
and manipulate the democratic institutions that emerged during the last days<br>
of the USSR and the first years of independent statehood. Each of the<br>
presidents is now attempting to use elections (or a referendum) in an effort<br>
to beat national parliaments into submission and to eliminate political<br>
opposition to presidential fiat.<br>
	The three countries' international orientation, their choice of alliances<br>
and their alignments constitute the ultimate stake in these internal<br>
conflicts. Nevertheless, the West has yet to clarify its interests in any of<br>
the three countries or to act to further those interests.<br>
<p>
Belarus: President and Parliament Battle it out<br>
	In Belarus, President Aleksandr Lukashenko has drafted a new constitution<br>
that confers sweeping powers on the president while emasculating the<br>
parliament and the Constitutional Court. Lukashenko has scheduled a November<br>
referendum to have his constitution adopted and pave the way for dissolving<br>
parliament and dismissing the Court. The president has ordered the Finance<br>
Ministry to fund the referendum (allegedly from "working people's"<br>
donations) and instructed local state bodies to administer the referendum.<br>
The exercise contravenes the existing constitution and other legislation,<br>
which state that only parliament may call a referendum and only the Central<br>
Election Commission may administer it. Exercising its prerogative,<br>
parliament has scheduled a counter-referendum for later in the month, in<br>
which voters will be asked to choose between competing constitutional<br>
drafts. One draft is that sanctioned by the president and the other, which<br>
would abolish the presidency and transform Belarus into a purely<br>
parliamentary republic, is sponsored by parliament. The president has<br>
responded by forbidding the state authorities to finance or cooperate in any<br>
way with parliament's referendum. He has ignored not only the law and<br>
parliamentary decisions but also the Constitutional Court, which has found<br>
no fewer than sixteen presidential decrees to be in violation of the<br>
constitution.<br>
	A large number of parliamentarians, as well as the Constitutional Court and<br>
the Central Election Commission, are resisting Lukashenko's bid for power.<br>
They are supported by a coalition of 24 parliamentary and extraparliamentary<br>
parties and groups spanning the two poles of what may be termed the<br>
constitutional front. Given the unexpected strength of the resistance,<br>
Moscow and top Russian Communists have urged Lukashenko to secure at least<br>
some measure of parliamentary support for his policy of "reintegration" with<br>
Russia.<br>
	The president has accordingly set about splitting the two largest<br>
parliamentary groups, the Agrarians and the Communists. Most of these<br>
deputies double as directors of factories, state and collective farms or<br>
government bodies. Simultaneously, therefore, they act as links in the<br>
"vertical administrative mechanism" created and headed by Lukashenko. This<br>
makes them vulnerable to both threats and financial inducements doled out by<br>
the president and government. The president has, moreover, promised that<br>
obedient deputies will be employed in the new -- and powerless -- parliament<br>
he proposes to create.<br>
	Lukashenko has scheduled his referendum on November 7. Parliament may go<br>
ahead with its own referendum on November 24. The stage seems set for<br>
continuing confrontation.<br>
<p>
Armenia: International Organizations Criticize Presidential Election<br>
	In Armenia, fallout continues from a fraudulent presidential election.<br>
Following the first round, held on September 22, the authorities took a<br>
whole week to count the votes and declare that incumbent president Levon<br>
Ter-Petrosian had won 51.75 percent of the vote, against 41.3 percent for<br>
Vazgen Manukian, candidate of the opposition National Accord bloc. Official<br>
returns suggested that, even if electoral fraud was not as systematic as the<br>
opposition claimed, it was enough to tip Ter-Petrosian over the 50 percent<br>
mark and avoid the necessity of a runoff. Mass protests, which degenerated<br>
into a mob attempt to overrun the parliament and Central Election Commission<br>
offices, were answered by the authorities with a crackdown on the opposition<br>
as a whole. Police closed down the offices of opposition parties and<br>
arrested several prominent opposition figures. The better known were<br>
eventually released, but not before criminal proceedings had been instituted<br>
against them. Eight opposition deputies were stripped of parliamentary<br>
immunity and expelled from the chamber, almost entirely eliminating the<br>
opposition's parliamentary representation.<br>
	Armenia's post-election crackdown capped a process that was already<br>
discernible during the 1995 parliamentary elections. Those elections were<br>
also marred by government-perpetrated fraud, and saw the suspension of the<br>
main opposition party -- the Armenian Revolutionary Federation,<br>
Dashnaksutiun. Western countries and international organizations tended to<br>
treat these early warnings with relative indifference. They seem thereby<br>
unintentionally to have invited more serious transgressions, as the recent<br>
presidential election and ensuing repression suggest. <br>
	The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), which<br>
observed Armenia's presidential election, issued a strongly worded<br>
assessment of the ballot. OSCE monitors observed "numerous irregularities,"<br>
including unlawful police presence at voting stations, ballot-stuffing, and<br>
refusal by electoral officials to consider opposition complaints. The report<br>
pointed out that more than 22,000 votes could not be traced to any<br>
registered voter, while a further 21,000 ballots were missing and<br>
unaccounted for. Since Ter-Petrosian scraped the 50 percent threshold by a<br>
mere 22,000 votes, the OSCE concluded that these disparities alone were<br>
enough to cast doubt on the results. Both the OSCE and the Washington-based<br>
International Foundation for Electoral Systems called on the authorities to<br>
investigate the violations and review the election returns. They stopped<br>
short, however, of recommending that the election should be invalidated. <br>
	In the circumstances, any official review of the returns looks highly<br>
unlikely. International pressure is lacking, and the authorities have the<br>
internal situation well in hand. The three "power" ministers are personal<br>
and political supporters of the president, and the defense minister stated<br>
on national television that the security ministries would not accept an<br>
opposition victory, "even if they won 100 percent of the vote."<br>
	Local elections will be held in Armenia on November 11. Opposition parties<br>
say they are unable to campaign freely, their press is gagged, and their<br>
leaders are facing the threat of criminal prosecution. In other words, the<br>
stage in Armenia is set, like that in Belarus, for an exercise in<br>
undemocratic elections.<br>
<p>
Moldova: Institutionalizing Presidential Rule <br>
	Democratic elections may soon be an endangered species in Moldova, too.<br>
President Mircea Snegur has cemented an opportunistic alliance with the<br>
ultranationalist Popular Front which he hopes will enable him to win<br>
reelection. The Popular Front wants to unite Moldova with Romania, and it is<br>
not squeamish about authoritarian methods. Now Snegur and the Front are<br>
campaigning to change the constitution, dissolve parliament and dismiss the<br>
government through a combination of presidential fiat and social agitation<br>
against reforms. The president is blaming the social costs of the reforms --<br>
which he himself launched -- on the governing Agrarian Democratic party and<br>
on his challengers for the presidency, Prime Minister Andrei Sangheli and<br>
parliamentary Speaker Petru Lucinschi. <br>
	To advance his quest for personal rule, the president has launched a front<br>
organization called the "Pro-Snegur Movement." Moldova is a multiethnic<br>
country, but this is a monoethnic organization. The president is also<br>
seeking to create instruments of force under his personal control. He has<br>
assumed "direct command" over the armed forces even though the law empowers<br>
the president to do so only in a state of national emergency and with<br>
parliamentary approval; he also unilaterally placed the service for the<br>
protection of the president, government and parliament under exclusive<br>
presidential subordination, declining to account for most of its activities<br>
and vetoing parliamentary legislation which envisaged parliamentary and<br>
governmental control over that service. The Constitutional Court, showing<br>
far less courage than its counterpart in Belarus, is emitting uncertain<br>
signals which may discourage the parliament and government from running the<br>
risk of appealing to the Court. Democracy may as a result be in danger of a<br>
serious setback. <br>
<p>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
The Fortnight in Review" is prepared by Senior Analysts Elizabeth Teague<br>
(Russia), Stephen Foye (Security and Foreign Policy), and Vladimir Socor<br>
(Non-Russian republics). <br>
