<title>The Monitor: A Publication of the Jamestown Foundation: 14 October 1996 - Monitor Vol. II, No. 191</title>
<h1>14 October 1996 - Monitor Vol. II, No. 191</h1>
Jamestown Foundation (<i>brdcast@jamestown.org</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Oct 1996 09:07:57 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#16">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#16">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#16">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#16">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Jamestown Foundation: "15 October 1996 - Monitor Vol. II, No. 192"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0015.html">Jamestown Foundation: "11 October 1996 -- Monitor Vol. II, No. 190"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
MONITOR  -  A DAILY BRIEFING ON THE POST-SOVIET STATES<br>
<p>
IN THIS ISSUE:<br>
<p>
* Lebed says he's supporting Russia's former presidential security chief <br>
* Yeltsin sets up emergency tax commission <br>
* New agency seen as Chubais' creation <br>
* Moscow emits uncertain signals on relations with NATO <br>
* The Baltic states intensify their efforts to meet NATO membership criteria <br>
* Ukraine expresses alarm as Lebed openly lays claim to Sevastopol <br>
* U.S. defense secretary nixes Minsk visit amid concerns over SS-25 redeployment<br>
<p>
NEWS:<br>
<p>
LATVIA'S GUESTS ABUSE HOSPITALITY. Hundreds of Russian war veterans held an<br>
unauthorized rally in central Riga yesterday to mark the anniversary of the<br>
1944 Soviet "liberation" of the Latvian capital. Participants called for the<br>
restoration of the USSR and the release of Baltic Communist leaders<br>
sentenced for their participation in the 1991 Soviet crackdown and putsch.<br>
(Itar-Tass, Interfax, October 13) The Baltic states have been under pressure<br>
to accept thousands of Soviet Army veterans as permanent residents and even<br>
to co-finance their social benefits, rather than having them repatriated to<br>
Russia.<br>
<p>
OFFICERS FLEEING THE FLEET? According to a Russian television report,<br>
Russia's Pacific Fleet faces a potentially debilitating loss of officers<br>
next year, when the contracts for many of them come up for renewal. Of some<br>
600 officers, 70 percent reportedly do not intend to extend their term of<br>
service, and 182 have already filed for demobilization. (Russian TV, October<br>
11) <br>
<p>
BELLONA REPS BARRED FROM ST. PETERSBURG. On orders from Russia's Foreign<br>
Ministry, two representatives of the Oslo-based environmental organization<br>
Bellona have been denied visas to visit St. Petersburg, the group announced<br>
on October 10. The representatives reportedly had intended to bring<br>
information needed for the defense of Aleksandr Nikitin, the retired Russian<br>
naval officer charged with treason for work done in collaboration with<br>
Bellona. Norway's Foreign Ministry is expected to raise the issue with<br>
Moscow. (Bellona press release, October 10)<br>
<p>
KUZYUK: "ELITE" ARMS COMPANIES TO GROW INTO TRANSNATIONAL GIANTS. Boris<br>
Kuzyk, President Boris Yeltsin's advisor on arms cooperation with foreign<br>
countries, said yesterday that several of Russia's successful arms combines<br>
would grow into transnational corporations. He said serious proposals had<br>
already been received from prospective partners in Belarus, Ukraine, and<br>
Kazakhstan. Kuzyk pointed to the Moscow Aircraft Production Association<br>
(MAPO) and the St. Petersburg Morskaya Tekhnika financial-industrial group<br>
as examples. (Interfax October 12, 13 1996)<br>
<p>
YEMANIS WANT HIDE OF RUSSIAN ARMS DEALER. A Russian arms dealer has been<br>
holed up in the Russian consulate in Aden for 4 months after Yemen demanded<br>
his arrest for failing to deliver $4 million worth of arms it had ordered<br>
and paid for. Sergei Spassky had headed a company called Bonex when he made<br>
the deal with Yemen in 1994. Now vice-president of another company, he made<br>
the mistake of returning to Aden in May. (Reuters, 12 October 1996)<br>
<p>
SOUTH KOREA SHOWS INTEREST IN RUSSIAN JET. The commander of the South Korean<br>
Air Force told a group of visiting Russian parliamentarians that his service<br>
would consider the Russian-built Su-35 fighter along with U.S. and West<br>
European planes when it upgrades its fleet. Gen. Lee Kwang Hak added that<br>
the new acquisitions would not begin until 2002. (ITAR-TASS, October 9 1996)<br>
<p>
PERSPECTIVE:<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN FEDERATION<br>
<p>
LEBED SAYS HE'S SUPPORTING KORZHAKOV. Russian security chief Aleksandr Lebed<br>
says he will support former Presidential Security Service head Aleksandr<br>
Korzhakov in his bid for the parliamentary seat Lebed gave up when he moved<br>
to the Kremlin in June. (NTV, October 13) A by-election for the Tula<br>
constituency will be held next February. Lebed and Korzhakov were in Tula --<br>
a major center of defense production south of Moscow -- for celebrations<br>
marking the city's 850th anniversary. There had been rumors that Lebed would<br>
strike a deal with Korzhakov, who lost his post as Yeltsin's chief bodyguard<br>
in June, in order to get access to Korzhakov's unique insider information<br>
and sources of funding. Commentators warn that association with Korzhakov,<br>
who is under investigation for alleged extortion, could sully Lebed's image<br>
as a crusader against corruption. But Korzhakov told a press conference in<br>
Moscow on October 11 that he is the victim of a campaign to discredit him<br>
because he has compromising material "up here in my head" on top Kremlin<br>
insiders. (Interfax, October 11) Lebed has made a number of incongruous<br>
alliances on his way to the top. Generally, he has not kept his allies long.<br>
In the words of journalist Yefim Bershin, who took part in Lebed's election<br>
campaign, Lebed is a loner who bases his success on personal charisma rather<br>
than teamwork. (Vek, No. 39, October 4-10, 1996)<br>
<p>
YELTSIN SETS UP EMERGENCY TAX COMMISSION. Trying to convince the nation that<br>
he is still running the country, President Boris Yeltsin gave his second<br>
nationwide radio address on October 11. Yeltsin blamed tax dodgers for the<br>
destitute state of Russia's pensioners, teachers and soldiers, and announced<br>
that he was setting up a special temporary commission to crack down on tax<br>
evasion and ensure that state wages and pensions are paid. Officially, the<br>
commission is headed by Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. But, zooming in<br>
on the fact that the commission is "subordinate to the president" and that<br>
Yeltsin's chief-of-staff, Anatoly Chubais, was appointed first deputy head,<br>
the media immediately dubbed it "Chubais' Cheka." (The Cheka was Lenin's<br>
secret police.) The commission includes high-ranking representatives of the<br>
economic ministries, the security services, and the prosecutor's office,<br>
although the Security Council is represented only by Aleksandr Lebed's<br>
deputy. Chubais promised that the commission would start work within a week<br>
and be fully operational within a fortnight. (Interfax, Kommersant-daily,<br>
Segodnya, October 12)<br>
<p>
The government's failure to collect taxes is a real problem and Russia is<br>
under heavy IMF pressure to improve procedures. Recent revelations that the<br>
gas giant, Gazprom, owes the state some $2.5 billion in unpaid taxes<br>
reflects the magnitude of the problem. (BBC World Service, October 2 and 13)<br>
The government had hoped that tax collection would improve after the<br>
presidential election, but this has not happened. In the first nine months<br>
of the year the government collected only 75 percent of planned taxes, and<br>
September's haul was but 45 percent of the target and a 29 percent reduction<br>
compared to August. (Delovoi mir, October 9)<br>
<p>
NEW COMMISSION SEEN AS CHUBAIS' CREATION. Anatoly Chubais' new post will<br>
further inflame his critics. Aleksandr Korzhakov, himself seen as a<br>
latter-day Rasputin until his recent ouster, accused Chubais in his press<br>
conference last week of forcing Yeltsin to go through with the presidential<br>
election in a calculated effort to undermine the president's health and<br>
usurp his powers. (Interfax, October 11) <br>
<p>
The business newspaper Kommersant-daily, which calls Chubais "acting<br>
president," sees the commission as the fruit of an artful campaign to wrench<br>
the control of taxation away from Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin.<br>
Kommersant-daily argues that Chubais used an ill-fated 18 August<br>
presidential decree on income tax -- which provoked such protest in business<br>
circles and the media that it had to be rescinded a month later -- to get<br>
the State Tax Service withdrawn from Chernomyrdin's jurisdiction and<br>
resubordinated to the president (read, his chief-of-staff). But while the<br>
newspaper sees the commission as essentially a pawn in the Kremlin power<br>
struggle, it laments the fact that Russia is still ruled by means of<br>
backstairs intrigue and "emergency measures." (Kommersant-daily, October 12)<br>
<p>
MIXED SIGNALS FROM MOSCOW ON NATO? Russia's Foreign Ministry appeared to<br>
scramble late last week to reassert Moscow's hard-line stance on relations<br>
with NATO in the wake of security chief Aleksandr Lebed's earlier,<br>
unexpectedly accommodating remarks on that subject during a visit to<br>
Brussels. Addressing a meeting of Russian diplomats in Moscow on October 10,<br>
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov reiterated Moscow's long-standing demand<br>
that a political agreement with NATO is possible only if it confers upon<br>
Russia a real voice in NATO affairs. "Agreement is not an aim in itself," he<br>
said. "We want a document that reflects our concerns and establishes a<br>
system that guarantees our security." (UPI, October 10) In remarks to<br>
reporters that same day, Foreign Ministry press spokesman Gennady Tarasov<br>
said that Moscow remains "resolutely opposed to NATO's planned enlargement,"<br>
which he described as inconsistent with Russia's military-strategic,<br>
political, and economic interests. (Interfax, October 10) The Foreign<br>
Ministry's reaction suggested a possible rift between it and Lebed's<br>
Security Council on the subject of relations with NATO. It also hinted at an<br>
emerging competition between the two bodies -- and between Primakov and<br>
Lebed personally -- for control of Russia's foreign policy agenda. <br>
<p>
For all of that, it is difficult to determine whether Lebed really has<br>
strayed from the Kremlin's line on NATO. Two Polish leaders suggested in<br>
Brussels on October 11 that Moscow had indeed finally resigned itself to<br>
NATO's enlargement and that it is now bargaining simply to "to get<br>
concessions in other areas." They also said that Lebed had come to NATO<br>
headquarters "like a tiger and left like a pussycat." (Reuter, October 11)<br>
But U.S. officials are described as only cautiously encouraged by Lebed's<br>
conciliatory public posture in Brussels. Their optimism is reportedly<br>
tempered by what they describe as the harder edge that Lebed displayed in<br>
his private meetings with NATO officials. They say that those private<br>
exchanges suggested no real shift in Russia's position. (The New York Times,<br>
October 10)<br>
<p>
Nor has Lebed been entirely consistent since his return from Brussels. In<br>
remarks on October 12 he again called for Russia to play a more active role<br>
in NATO's Partnership for Peace program and to fashion a political agreement<br>
whereby Moscow can interact constructively with the Western alliance.<br>
(Reuter, October 12) But only two days earlier a Lebed aide had cautioned<br>
that Lebed's remarks in Brussels meant neither that Moscow had shed all its<br>
apprehensions about NATO's enlargement nor that it had finally resigned<br>
itself to expansion. In his own remarks to a conference in Moscow that same<br>
day, Lebed was reported to have mentioned "NATO's expansion to the East,<br>
towards our borders, to the Baltic republics" as one of a series of<br>
potential threats to Russian security. (Itar-Tass, October 10)<br>
<p>
THE BALTIC STATES<br>
<p>
BALTIC DEFENSE MINISTERS ANNOUNCE JOINT PROGRAMS. Meeting in Riga on October<br>
12, the defense ministers of the three Baltic states resolved to create a<br>
joint commission to coordinate weapons procurement. The action was aimed at<br>
ensuring that the arsenals of the three states are compatible with each<br>
other and with those of NATO countries. The three ministers also announced<br>
that the joint Baltic Battalion (BaltBat) and the planned joint naval<br>
squadron of the Baltic states will be made available for international<br>
peacekeeping operations in 1997 and beyond. In addition, the ministers<br>
requested support for the creation of a common Baltic airspace control<br>
system, and announced that they would appeal for help on this score from<br>
U.S. defense secretary William Perry personally. (Interfax, Radio Riga,<br>
October 13) <br>
<p>
The steps demonstrate the Baltic states' resolve to upgrade their defense<br>
capabilities after some officials of NATO countries -- particularly Perry --<br>
cited insufficient military preparedness as a reason for postponing<br>
consideration of the Baltic states' accession to NATO. To finance the<br>
upgrading the Baltic political leaderships last week confirmed plans to<br>
increase defense spending to the NATO benchmark level of 2 percent of the<br>
national GDP.<br>
<p>
THE WESTERN REGION<br>
<p>
LEBED DEMANDS SEVASTOPOL FROM UKRAINE. Russia's chief security official,<br>
Aleksandr Lebed, has unambiguously claimed Sevastopol for Russia in an open<br>
letter published in the Russian Black Sea Fleet's newspaper and a Crimean<br>
Russian nationalist newspaper. "We must assert that a territorial dispute<br>
exists, support Russia's right to Sevastopol with historical, legal, and<br>
ethnic arguments, and take into account the will of Sevastopol's<br>
population," Lebed wrote. He called for raising the issue of Sevastopol's<br>
status in Russian-Ukrainian political negotiations and for the legislative<br>
branch to support the executive branch in obligating the Russian delegation<br>
at the Black Sea Fleet negotiations to insist on exclusive Russian basing<br>
rights in Sevastopol. Lebed reiterated the familiar argument that Sevastopol<br>
never lost its "Russian status" because it was not specifically mentioned in<br>
the USSR Supreme Soviet's 1954 decision to transfer Crimea to Ukraine. (Flag<br>
Rodiny, October 5, and Krymskaya pravda, October 10, cited by UNIAN, October<br>
11.)<br>
<p>
Ukraine's Foreign Ministry, in a declaration issued over the weekend,<br>
deplored the "increasingly frequent and open anti-Ukrainian sallies by<br>
Russian officials." While "presuming that President Boris Yeltsin and the<br>
Russian Foreign Ministry have not changed their position," Kiev "sees with<br>
extreme concern that those sallies emanate from senior government officials,<br>
including those responsible for national security." Russian territorial<br>
claims on Ukraine "seriously complicate bilateral relations and destabilize<br>
the situation," and also run counter to Russia's commitments to Ukraine and<br>
the norms of international law, Kiev's statement said. (Interfax-Ukraine,<br>
October 12)<br>
<p>
Lebed laid claim to Sevastopol less directly last month by calling for<br>
informal discussions between Moscow and Kiev and for international<br>
arbitration. He also announced last month that his Security Council would<br>
henceforth take control of Moscow's policy on the Black Sea Fleet and the<br>
Sevastopol issue. Russian prime minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and the Foreign<br>
Ministry seem thus far to have ignored Lebed's attempt to grab that issue<br>
from them. However, the Duma is now drafting a resolution that is expected<br>
to reassert its earlier claims to Sevastopol in stronger terms. Common<br>
ground on the issues of Sevastopol and the Black Sea Fleet may enable Lebed<br>
and the Duma to overcome their conflict over Lebed's policy in Chechnya. <br>
<p>
Lebed's latest foray may also be in part an attempt to prove that he is<br>
every bit as patriotic as Moscow mayor Yury Luzhkov, who has made the status<br>
of Sevastopol -- where the Moscow municipality has significant financial<br>
interests -- into a trademark political issue. Kiev understands this, but<br>
the increased salience of the Crimean issue on the Russian agenda may<br>
encourage hopes among Crimea's pro-Russian parties that a future Russian<br>
leader will adopt their cause.<br>
<p>
U.S. WORRIED BELARUS MIGHT NOT GIVE UP NUCLEAR MISSILES. U.S. defense<br>
secretary William Perry has decided to drop Minsk from the schedule of his<br>
upcoming trip to Russia . The move comes as American concerns mount that<br>
mercurial Belarus president Alexander Lukashenko might renege on the<br>
country's previous pledge to return the last Soviet SS-25 mobile<br>
intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs) to Russia by the end of the<br>
year. There are two regiments of Russian Strategic Rocket Troops in Belarus,<br>
fielding 18 single-warhead SS-25 missiles. In addition, they maintain two or<br>
three spare warheads.<br>
<p>
In September 1993 the Belarus and Russian prime ministers signed an<br>
agreement in Moscow calling for all the Soviet missiles to be repatriated to<br>
Russia by the end of 1996, prompting U.S. secretary of state Warren<br>
Christopher to call Belarus "a shining example to states around the region."<br>
(The New York Times, October 27, 1993). But Lukashenko, elected in 1994, had<br>
other ideas. He halted the missile transfer in mid-1995 and charged that the<br>
withdrawal agreement had been a big political mistake. Lukashenko also<br>
apparently had money in mind. He was envious of a deal reached between<br>
Russia and Ukraine whereby Russia credited Ukraine for the nuclear material<br>
in the Soviet warheads once deployed on its territory. In February 1996<br>
Lukashenko announced that Russia had agreed to pay Belarus for the plutonium<br>
in its SS-25 warheads. (Interfax, February 27 1996) Then, in July, an aide<br>
to Lukashenko reported that Minsk had once again suspended the withdrawal<br>
because Russia was not making any payments. He insisted, however, that they<br>
would all be gone by the end of the year. <br>
<p>
Lukashenko has also not been above suggesting that Belarus might hang on to<br>
the missiles should NATO expand into Eastern Europe -- despite Minsk's<br>
accession to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) as a non-nuclear<br>
weapons state. (Belarus Radio, April 5 1996) <br>
<p>
Among all the successor states of the Soviet Union, Russia and Belarus have<br>
the closest military relationship, and the Russians have tried to dispel the<br>
notion that there is an impasse over the missiles. Clearly, Russia's<br>
Strategic Rocket Forces -- which would like to finish the redeployments --<br>
have been annoyed. Yet both sides continue to act as if things will work<br>
out. Aleksandr Lebed visited Minsk a month ago and following consultations<br>
with his Belarusian counterpart announced that, while a number of "technical<br>
problems" still needed to be resolved, the two had agreed that the<br>
withdrawal schedule would be met. (Itar-Tass, September 13 1996) As the days<br>
pass, Washington does not seem to be so sure. <br>
<p>
