<title>The Monitor: A Publication of the Jamestown Foundation: 4 October 1996 Fortnight in Review - Vol I, No. 7</title>
<h1>4 October 1996 Fortnight in Review - Vol I, No. 7</h1>
Jamestown Foundation (<i>brdcast@jamestown.org</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Oct 1996 15:13:47 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#10">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#10">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#10">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#10">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Jamestown Foundation: "7 October 1996 Monitor-Vol II, No. 186"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Jamestown Foundation: "4 October 1996 Monitor - Vol. II, No. 185"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
THE FORTNIGHT IN REVIEW -- A BI-WEEKLY ON THE POST-SOVIET STATES<br>
<p>
Chechnya: Russian Government Moves to Consolidate Peace at Last <br>
	The Chechen peace process took a major step forward on October 3 when the<br>
leader of the Chechen opposition, Zelimkhan Yandarbiev, traveled to Moscow<br>
for long awaited talks with the Russian government. He and Prime Minister<br>
Viktor Chernomyrdin signed an agreement setting up the Joint Commission<br>
envisioned in the August 31 Khasavyurt accords, which brought the 21-month<br>
conflict to an end. The commission will oversee the withdrawal of Russian<br>
troops and the reconstruction of housing, health and other public services<br>
in the war-ravaged republic. The meeting took place just one day after<br>
Security Council Secretary Aleksandr Lebed, who brokered the Khasavyurt<br>
accords, was fiercely criticized by Russian parliamentarians for his efforts<br>
to resolve the conflict. But the fact that Chernomyrdin signed the October 3<br>
agreement meant that Moscow for the first time officially recognized the<br>
validity of the Khasavyurt accords. Until then, the Russian government had<br>
refused to express a clear opinion and the legal status of the peace<br>
settlement had been in doubt. <br>
<p>
Tensions Erupt Between Yeltsin and Lebed <br>
	Also on October 3, President Boris Yeltsin expressed unequivocal approval<br>
for the first time of Lebed's peace efforts. Yeltsin was making the first of<br>
a series of radio addresses intended to reassure the Russian public that he<br>
is not a lame duck president, even though he will have to recuperate for at<br>
least two months after his impending heart operation and may be away from<br>
the Kremlin until the new year. "My aide Aleksandr Lebed," the president<br>
said in an apparent effort to claim the credit, "has carried out my<br>
instructions and put an end to the bloodshed." Earlier in the day, Yeltsin<br>
and Lebed had held their first face-to-face meeting since mid-August, when<br>
Yeltsin first gave Lebed responsibility for ending the Chechen war. Their<br>
latest meeting was stormy and at one point Lebed threatened to resign.<br>
Yeltsin's response was to reprimand Lebed on national television, telling<br>
him publicly to get in line and stop quarreling with the government. Lebed<br>
did nothing of the kind: on October 4, he snubbed his colleagues by<br>
pointedly refusing to turn up for the first meeting of the Defense Council,<br>
newly created by Yeltsin to oversee military reform and counterbalance<br>
Lebed's own Security Council.<br>
<p>
Wrangling Over NATO <br>
	The issue of NATO enlargement dominated East-West diplomacy in the past two<br>
weeks, as alliance leaders insisted they would stay the course while Moscow<br>
sandwiched slivers of resigned acceptance between chunks of customary<br>
truculence. Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Defense Minister Igor<br>
Rodionov insisted that Moscow would not allow enlargement to threaten<br>
cooperation between Russia and the West. But their grudging nods to<br>
pragmatism did not prevent a bevy of Russian leaders -- Primakov and<br>
Rodionov among them -- from reiterating strong objections to NATO's plans<br>
and, in some cases, threatening various kinds of reprisal.<br>
	The search for accommodation on NATO enlargement was complicated by<br>
Russia's quickening domestic political struggle. With President Yeltsin, the<br>
country seemed to be moving toward a situation reminiscent of that which<br>
prevailed during the presidential campaign earlier in the year. Nationalist<br>
posturing was the order of the day then, which meant that diplomacy often<br>
had to take a back seat to domestic politicking. A power-hungry Aleksandr<br>
Lebed, suddenly obdurate on NATO enlargement, may emerge as the wild card in<br>
Moscow's pack. While a planned trip on October 7 to NATO's Brussels<br>
headquarters may provide a more positive picture of the former general's<br>
views on NATO expansion, his recent comments have given Western leaders<br>
little ground for optimism.<br>
<p>
Helsinki To New York <br>
	Criss-crossing the Atlantic on the weekend of September 21-22, Primakov and<br>
U.S. defense secretary William Perry emerged as the leading players in the<br>
latest jousting over enlargement. Perry told reporters on the plane to<br>
Finland that Moscow's slow progress in destroying its tactical nuclear<br>
weapons could force the West to renege on earlier, informal assurances to<br>
Russia that NATO would not station nuclear weapons in newly-admitted Eastern<br>
European member-states. In Helsinki, Perry balanced strong reaffirmation of<br>
Washington's commitment to enlargement with proposals to give Moscow a<br>
significant voice in NATO affairs, including possible participation in<br>
various NATO committees. But his references to the conclusion of a "charter"<br>
between Russia and NATO made it clear that Moscow would not receive voting<br>
rights.<br>
	Primakov mentioned neither the proposed charter nor Washington's call for<br>
an expanded Partnership for Peace program during a speech to the OSCE in<br>
Vienna on September 20. Instead, he restated Moscow's objections to<br>
enlargement and its desire to see the OSCE become Europe's central security<br>
structure. But in the remarks made in New York on September 23 the Russian<br>
foreign minister made it clear that, despite its objections to enlargement,<br>
Moscow sought both to reach an accommodation on the issue and to "avoid<br>
serious collisions in relations with the West" over it. That spirit of<br>
modest cooperation carried over into bilateral talks in New York between<br>
Washington and Moscow. Although the two sides failed to resolve differences<br>
on Iraq and the former Yugoslavia, Primakov and U.S. secretary of state<br>
Warren Christopher did announce an important missile defense agreement. They<br>
also found common ground on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and on<br>
continued Russian participation in the Bosnian peacekeeping force. Following<br>
a meeting with U.S. president Bill Clinton on September 28, Primakov<br>
described Washington's policy toward Russia as "balanced" and said it was<br>
based on equality and mutual advantage.<br>
<p>
Talking Tough<br>
	During talks with NATO defense chiefs in Norway on September 26, Russian<br>
defense minister Igor Rodionov crafted his response to enlargement much as<br>
Primakov had done in New York: Rodionov underscored Moscow's continued<br>
opposition to enlargement while declaring that the alliance's plans would<br>
not prevent Russia from cooperating with it in Bosnia and elsewhere. In<br>
Moscow, however, anti-enlargement rhetoric had already displayed a much<br>
harder edge. On September 24, Aleksandr Lebed was quoted by a British<br>
newspaper as saying that Russia would slap economic sanctions on U.S. and<br>
German companies if NATO expanded. He was particularly scathing about<br>
Germany, comparing Bonn's post-unification policies to the construction of a<br>
"Fourth Reich" and accusing Germany of wanting to dominate all of Central<br>
and Eastern Europe. A day later, Lebed took on the U.S., intimating that<br>
Washington was considering missile attacks against Russia and warning<br>
bombastically that Moscow did not fear a full-scale war with the U.S. Later,<br>
on September 28, President Yeltsin demanded that NATO conclude a political<br>
treaty with Russia before expanding, a proposal that was endorsed by<br>
Rodionov in remarks on October 1. Rodionov also issued a strong warning that<br>
NATO expansion might cause Moscow to reconsider its adherence to the<br>
Conventional Forces in Europe Treaty.<br>
<p>
Russia's Army: Anticipating a "Hot October?" <br>
	The highly politicized battle over NATO enlargement was paralleled inside<br>
Russia by a deepening conflict over Russia's armed forces. Mounting salary<br>
and payments arrears in the armed forces -- as in other sectors of the<br>
Russian economy -- had over several months increased resentments among<br>
uniformed and civilian employees of Russia's Defense Ministry. Civilian<br>
employees launched a protest in Moscow on September 19, and there were<br>
concerns that regular military personnel might follow them into the streets.<br>
Defense Minister Rodionov, already engaged in a bitter battle with the<br>
government over the draft 1997 budget, complained repeatedly about the<br>
army's financial woes and threw his support behind the civilian protest. But<br>
Lebed raised the political stakes higher still. On September 25, he alleged<br>
that Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin was deliberately holding back<br>
funding earmarked for the military in order to weaken the armed forces and<br>
undermine Rodionov (a Lebed ally). Lebed also charged that underfinancing<br>
had humiliated the army to the point where an "armed mutiny" was an<br>
immediate possibility. Lebed's remarks bordered on the incendiary and<br>
appeared, in Russia's current context, to reflect political aspirations<br>
beyond those of simply ensuring the welfare of military personnel.<br>
<p>
TWO POST-IMPERIAL REARGUARD ACTIONS<br>
<p>
The smoldering struggle over the spoils of empire entered an active phase at<br>
opposite ends of what used to be the Soviet Union. And while Russia was<br>
handed a success in its political competition with the West for influence in<br>
the Baltic region, it suffered a setback in the military and, in a broader<br>
sense, cultural conflict with local forces on the fringe of Central Asia. <br>
<p>
NATO Expansion off Course in Baltics<br>
	In the Baltic region, it befell NATO's leading power to announce and defend<br>
a decision to postpone sine die the start of procedures to admit Estonia,<br>
Latvia and Lithuania to the alliance. Surprisingly, it was the Pentagon that<br>
bore the brunt of what was essentially a political decision. U.S. defense<br>
secretary William Perry and other Defense Department officials argued<br>
publicly  that the Baltic states were "not yet" eligible for admission<br>
mainly because they were militarily unable to come to the aid of NATO<br>
members if necessary, and because they had "disputes with Russia" over the<br>
treatment of ethnic Russians within their borders. The same officials were<br>
quoted as arguing that the Baltic states had little reason to worry about<br>
being consigned to a "gray" security area," since Sweden and Finland seemed<br>
not to be unduly worried that they too belonged to a gray area outside NATO.<br>
The State Department, apparently content to take a back seat on this issue,<br>
nevertheless referred to the problem of ethnic Russians as a potential<br>
"crisis" in a policy address by the Secretary of State, prompting the OSCE<br>
envoy to Estonia to disagree publicly and point out that the human rights of<br>
that population were not being violated. <br>
	The State Department presaged the decision to postpone the Baltic accession<br>
to NATO by offering in early September a Baltic Action Plan credited to<br>
Deputy Secretary Strobe Talbott. It suggested some economic, political and<br>
public relations measures as apparent substitutes for security guarantees in<br>
the Baltic region, and offered no commitments or schedules regarding Baltic<br>
accession to the alliance. The Baltic states politely waved BAP off. <br>
	To be sure, the shelving of Baltic accession to NATO in late September was<br>
accompanied by promises to assist the Baltic states in their efforts to<br>
qualify for membership. The omens that preceded the decision somewhat<br>
amortized its shock effect on the Baltic states. However, the reasons cited<br>
in support of the decision were received in the Baltic states and beyond<br>
even more critically than the decision itself. Rebuttals pointed out that<br>
NATO's enlargement, proceeding from the principle of indivisible security,<br>
must take into account not only the countries' level of readiness but also<br>
their security needs; that the countries' immediate military readiness had<br>
not been a requirement for admission when NATO was founded; and that member<br>
countries achieved such readiness as a result of being admitted to the<br>
alliance. Baltic officials also pointed out that the central European<br>
countries slated to become members of the alliance do not currently meet<br>
Perry's readiness criterion either. <br>
	The second rationale, referring to disputes between the Baltic states and<br>
Russia, not only ignored the findings of international organizations which<br>
have found no human rights problems in connection with the treatment of<br>
Russians in the Baltic states. It unwittingly gave Moscow a reason to go on<br>
heating up ethnic and border issues, just as Moscow has in its efforts to<br>
discourage NATO enlargement in the Baltic region. The timing of the<br>
announcement, on the morrow of Perry's talks with Russian defense minister<br>
Rodionov, was also awkward. It did not even placate official Moscow, where<br>
the announcement was apparently seen as vindicating Moscow's stonewalling<br>
and bluffing. Within days, the deputy director of the USA Institute,<br>
Moscow's leading foreign policy think-tank, warned that Russia might occupy<br>
the Baltic states militarily if NATO admitted them to the alliance.<br>
	The Baltic states reacted with a solemn statement in which their three<br>
presidents jointly reiterated that only early accession to NATO could<br>
guarantee their freedom and requested the alliance to take "the clearest<br>
possible stand" on Baltic security. The presidents pledged their countries<br>
to intensify efforts to canvas support for their accession to NATO, develop<br>
bilateral security cooperation with NATO countries, and make "the sacrifices<br>
necessary" to upgrade their own forces. These eloquently expressed<br>
intentions could not obscure the fact that NATO's enlargement had veered off<br>
course in the Baltic region.<br>
<p>
Russia's Grip Over Tajikistan Threatened<br>
	Ensuring that other powers do not step in to fill the power vacuum left by<br>
the USSR has been a fundamental aim of Russian foreign policy since 1991. In<br>
Tajikistan, these efforts have begun to unravel recently. In mid-September,<br>
the Tajik opposition routed superior but clearly unmotivated government<br>
forces in Garm, the narrow middle section of Tajikistan which connects the<br>
western and eastern parts of the country. The operation was credited to<br>
field commanders Mirzohoja, Ahmadbek and Muhammadruzi, who prevailed not<br>
only against Tajik government commanders but also against Russian forces.<br>
The insurgents established a compact territorial base in part of Garm,<br>
drawing closer to their goal of cutting Dushanbe, in the west of the<br>
country, off from the opposition's eastern strongholds. A provisional truce<br>
with the government enshrined the opposition's gains. United Tajik<br>
Opposition (UTO) leader Saidabdullo Nuri announced that the opposition had<br>
no intention of introducing legal changes -- an apparent reference to<br>
Islamic Shariat law -- in its first "liberated area." That announcement was<br>
meant to banish the specter of "Islamic extremism" which Moscow and Dushanbe<br>
conjure up to justify their war effort. <br>
	To offset the reverses in Garm and regain the initiative in other areas,<br>
the Russian military command in Tajikistan and the government in Moscow<br>
pressed into service what passed for the Afghan government in Kabul.<br>
Comprised mainly of Afghan Tajiks, embattled in its own capital and<br>
controlling only a small part of the country, the Kabul government had been<br>
drifting for some time toward an alliance with Russia as its only chance of<br>
remaining in office and containing the offensive of the Taliban movement.<br>
During the month of September, senior Russian military and diplomatic<br>
officials agreed with Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani and prime<br>
minister Gulbuddin Hekmatyar on military cooperation against the UTO. The<br>
UTO had long used sanctuaries in Afghanistan's ethnic Tajik areas along the<br>
border with Tajikistan, tolerated by the Kabul leaders who had neither the<br>
intention nor the means to challenge them. It is still unclear what changed<br>
their mind, other than Moscow's increasing support and possible promises of<br>
military and financial assistance. Given their record of resistance to the<br>
Soviet army in the name of Islam, it may have been a difficult decision for<br>
the Kabul leaders to side with the immediate successor to that army against<br>
the Islamic resistance movement of their Tajik kinsmen on the border.<br>
	Pacts signed in mid-September by Russian generals with Kabul's commanders<br>
provided for a 25-kilometer-wide "security zone" on the Afghan side of the<br>
Afghan-Tajik border. Coordinating with Russian border troops, Kabul's forces<br>
were to interdict the passage of UTO detachments from Afghanistan into<br>
Tajikistan and catch them in the crossfire. Moreover, Kabul's troops were to<br>
attack UTO sanctuaries in that zone. In other words, the Afghan government<br>
was to stab Tajikistan's opposition in the back. Russian officials in<br>
Tajikistan and Moscow made optimistic public statements about the military<br>
benefits of their new alliance with the Rabbani-Hekmatyar group.<br>
	The Moscow-Kabul alliance with its implicit anti-Taliban edge signified the<br>
beginning of Moscow's return to Afghanistan in its old role as a<br>
power-broker. It appeared to stem from a decision in Moscow to switch to a<br>
forward defense of Tajikistan by establishing a defense line inside<br>
Afghanistan, enlisting one Afghan party to help hold that line, and<br>
supporting that Afghan party against its rival. Considered in retrospect,<br>
the decision appeared to reflect an intelligence fiasco of the kind that<br>
plagued Russian forces in the Chechnya war. The decision grossly<br>
underestimated the force of the Taliban, a mere fortnight before they<br>
captured Kabul; overestimated the Kabul leaders' capacity to resist, let<br>
alone to deliver on their commitments to Russia; and may even have been<br>
counterproductive to Kabul itself by forcing it to divert precious military<br>
resources to the Tajik border instead of staking everything on holding onto<br>
Kabul. In any event, the one-time resistance leaders did mount several<br>
attacks on the UTO in the security zone, to public accolades in Moscow and<br>
Dushanbe, before being routed from the capital on September 27 by the<br>
victorious Taliban.<br>
	This development is forcing Russia to recast its strategy in the region.<br>
With its options in Tajikistan narrowing, Moscow may at last get serious<br>
about pressuring its Kulyab clan allies into a power-sharing arrangement<br>
with the opposition first, and with the Soviet-era ruling clans in Leninabad<br>
region second.  As regards Afghanistan, the policy debate in Moscow has<br>
barely begun, but two conflicting options seem to be emerging. One option,<br>
championed by National Security Chief Aleksandr Lebed, argues that the<br>
Taliban will continue their northward thrust into ex-Soviet Central Asia,<br>
and recommends drawing a line of forward defense deep in northern<br>
Afghanistan, in alliance with the remaining Rabbani-Hekmatyar forces under<br>
Afghan Tajik commander Ahmad Shah-Masood and with the Afghan Uzbek forces of<br>
Gen. Abdul Rashid Dostum. The other option, espoused by Foreign Minister<br>
Yevgeny Primakov and apparently the majority view at the moment, discounts<br>
the prospect of a Taliban advance into Central Asia and recommends exploring<br>
a modus vivendi with the Taliban and its main supporter, Pakistan. <br>
	The newly independent states of Central Asia will undoubtedly express their<br>
views in the next few days. Among these countries, the one with the<br>
strongest cards to play is Uzbekistan which has influence in sizable areas<br>
of Tajikistan and Afghanistan, a large if obsolete military arsenal, and<br>
links with Dostum. Uzbek and other leaders may well reach consensus on a<br>
core agenda. They seek both to secure their countries' secular orientation<br>
and to deny Moscow an opportunity to reestablish regional hegemony under the<br>
guise of combating "Islamic fundamentalism." The way to accomplish both<br>
purposes can be found only in regional solidarity. <br>
	Such solidarity must include Pakistan. That country holds the key to Afghan<br>
peace and is pivotal to the planned multi-billion dollar UNOCAL-Delta gas<br>
pipeline from Central Asia via Afghanistan to the Indian Ocean, which would<br>
significantly weaken Russia's stranglehold on Central Asian mineral exports. <br>
<p>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
"The Fortnight in Review" is prepared by Senior Analysts Elizabeth Teague<br>
(Russia), Stephen Foye (Security and Foreign Policy), and Vladimir Socor<br>
(Non-Russian republics). <br>
