<title>The Monitor: A Publication of the Jamestown Foundation: 25 September 1996 Monitor -- Vol. II, No. 178</title>
<h1>25 September 1996 Monitor -- Vol. II, No. 178</h1>
Jamestown Foundation (<i>brdcast@jamestown.org</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 25 Sep 1996 09:34:04 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#2">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#2">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#2">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#2">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Jamestown Foundation: "26 September 1996 Monitor - Vol II, No. 179"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Jamestown Foundation: "24 September 1996 Monitor - Vol.II, No.177"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
MONITOR - A DAILY BRIEFING ON THE POST-SOVIET STATES<br>
<p>
IN THIS ISSUE: <br>
<p>
* Moscow and Washington reach missile defense agreement but stumble on NATO<br>
enlargement <br>
* Aleksandr Lebed says Moscow will counter NATO enlargement with economic<br>
sanctions<br>
* More mixed signals come from Moscow on Boris Yeltsin's health <br>
* The reinstatement of Vladivostok's mayor could safeguard other popularly<br>
elected officials <br>
* Experts evidence little optimism about short-term Russian economic prospects<br>
* The latest Security Council appointment aims at balancing the influence of<br>
a Lebed ally <br>
* Unpaid wages are increasing resentment in Russia's armed forces <br>
* Moldova reminds Moscow in vain of their unfulfilled troop withdrawal agreement<br>
<p>
NEWS:<br>
<p>
CALL FOR CHECHEN AMNESTY. President Ruslan Aushev of the Republic of<br>
Ingushetia, which borders on Chechnya, has called on the Russian parliament<br>
to declare a general amnesty for all those who fought in the Chechen<br>
opposition forces, including field commanders Shamil Basayev and Salman<br>
Raduyev. (Interfax, September 24) Aushev is a member of the upper house of<br>
the Russian parliament.<br>
<p>
CHECHEN OPPOSITION COMPLETES LIST OF COALITION GOVERNMENT. Chechen<br>
resistance leaders have agreed to a list of fourteen candidates for an<br>
interim coalition government to be headed by Zelimkhan Yandarbiev. The full<br>
list will be revealed when Yandarbiev visits Moscow; his visit is<br>
provisionally scheduled for September 30. (Interfax, September 24)<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN ADMIRAL ASSAILS WEST. The First Deputy Commander of Russia's Navy<br>
charged on September 23 that the West continues to contemplate the use of<br>
force against Russia. Admiral Igor Kasatonov cited as evidence naval<br>
reconnaissance operations being conducted against Russia and the West's<br>
continuing naval build-up. (Interfax, September 23) Kasatonov's remarks<br>
follow recent accusations that two British ships were spying on the<br>
activities of Russia's Northern Fleet. (See Monitor, September 18)<br>
<p>
START II A "BETRAYAL" OF RUSSIAN INTERESTS. The chairman of the Russian<br>
Duma's defense committee is reported to have told Itar-Tass that legislators<br>
are "unlikely" to ratify the START II Treaty because of NATO plans to expand<br>
eastward and the possibility that the alliance will deploy nuclear weapons<br>
on the territory of new member states. Gen. Lev Rokhlin said that<br>
implementation of START II would be a "betrayal of Russia's national<br>
interests." (Itar-Tass, September 21) <br>
<p>
AEROFLOT-BOEING DEAL TO COME UNDER PRESSURE? A Russian daily reports that<br>
Russian aircraft builders are joining with regional political interests in a<br>
coalition to protect beleaguered domestic aircraft manufacturers. Formation<br>
of the new coalition, which also is said to enjoy a strong presence in<br>
Russia's upper house of parliament, has been energized by Aeroflot's recent<br>
decision to purchase 10 American-made Boeing 737 airliners. (See Monitor,<br>
September 11) The newspaper suggests that Aeroflot may be pressured to nix<br>
the Boeing deal. (Kommersant-daily, September 24)<br>
<p>
CONTROVERSY OVER POLAND-RUSSIAN GAS DEAL. A 25-year agreement on the<br>
delivery of Russian gas to Poland, scheduled to be signed today, has<br>
provoked criticism from some Polish opposition parties on the grounds that<br>
it could make Warsaw energy-dependent on Russia. The gas, to come from the<br>
Russian Yemal peninsula via a 2,500 mile pipeline, will cross Belarus and<br>
Poland on its way to Germany and Western Europe. Defenders of the deal argue<br>
that Russia could not blackmail Poland because that would mean also cutting<br>
gas deliveries to Germany and Western Europe. (UPI, September 24)<br>
<p>
PERSPECTIVE:<br>
<p>
RUSSIAN FEDERATION<br>
<p>
MISSILE DEFENSE AGREEMENT HIGHLIGHTS PRIMAKOV-CHRISTOPHER TALKS. The U.S.<br>
and Russia announced on September 23 that they had concluded the first part<br>
of a new agreement on missile defense systems, and that negotiations on a<br>
second part would begin next month. Announcement of the accord, which was<br>
described as a "milestone" by U.S. secretary of state Warren Christopher,<br>
came following several hours of intensive talks in New York between<br>
Christopher and Russian foreign minister Yevgeny Primakov. The September 23<br>
agreement pertains to theater missile defenses and covers so-called<br>
low-velocity systems, while the second part of the agreement will deal with<br>
higher-velocity systems. Conclusion of a final agreement is important<br>
because it would, in Primakov's words, "signify the line of demarcation<br>
between strategic and theater anti-ballistic missiles." Establishing that<br>
demarcation could allow the U.S. to continue developing missile defense<br>
systems without violating the 1972 ABM Treaty. Primakov suggested that the<br>
agreement might also have a positive impact on Russia's parliamentary debate<br>
over ratification of the START II Treaty. The U.S. Congress has ratified<br>
START II, but opposition to the treaty in Russia -- based in part on a fear<br>
that the U.S. intends to violate the ABM Treaty -- has delayed efforts to<br>
bring it to a vote. (The New York Times, Reuter, UPI, September 24)<br>
<p>
Along with the missile defense accord, the talks in New York highlighted<br>
several other areas of cooperation between the U.S. and Russia, including<br>
agreement on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and on continued Russian<br>
participation in the Bosnian peacekeeping force. But the talks also revealed<br>
enduring disagreements between the two sides -- NATO enlargement foremost<br>
among them. Primakov restated Moscow's opposition to NATO's plans, and<br>
categorized as "exaggerated" claims by U.S. officials that Moscow is now<br>
deeply engaged in negotiations that link Russian acquiescence to enlargement<br>
with a "charter" agreement between Moscow and the alliance. The two sides<br>
also failed to resolve their differences on Iraq and the former Yugoslavia.<br>
Moscow spearheaded world criticism of the recent U.S. air attacks on Iraq<br>
and more recently has clashed with Washington over the latter's wish to<br>
delay the lifting of UN sanctions on Belgrade. (The Washington Post, Reuter,<br>
September 24)<br>
<p>
LEBED THREATENS SANCTIONS TO COUNTER NATO ENLARGEMENT. Russian Security<br>
Council secretary Aleksandr Lebed, formerly a moderate on the issue of NATO<br>
enlargement, threatened in a September 24 newspaper interview that Moscow<br>
would slap economic sanctions on U.S. and German companies as a response to<br>
the alliance's expansion. "Let there be no mistake," Lebed was quoted as<br>
saying. "German and American industrial interests in Russia will suffer<br>
directly as a result of enlargement plans." Lebed leveled some of his<br>
sharpest criticism at Bonn, whose post-unification policies he compared<br>
acidly to the construction of a "Fourth Reich." Vowing that Russia would not<br>
fall into Germany's sphere of influence, Lebed suggested a link between NATO<br>
enlargement and an alleged policy of German expansionism in Eastern Europe.<br>
"The German Defense Ministry, clearly determined to expand Germany's sphere<br>
of influence to the East, has driven the expansion policy," Lebed was quoted<br>
as saying. "With the enlargement of NATO and of the European Union, the<br>
whole of central and eastern Europe will come under German economic and<br>
political domination." (AP, September 24)<br>
<p>
Lebed's remarks, reported in Britain by yesterday's Daily Telegraph, came on<br>
the eve of today's meeting in Norway of NATO defense ministers. Russian<br>
defense chief Igor Rodionov, a political ally of Lebed's, is to take part in<br>
that meeting. Although various Russian political leaders have threatened a<br>
number of possible counter-measures to NATO's enlargement, Lebed's talk of<br>
economic sanctions would seem to be a first from a major government figure.<br>
However, Lebed's threat was discounted later in the day by First Deputy<br>
Prime Minister Aleksei Bolshakov, who said that the possibility of using<br>
sanctions against Western countries involved in NATO's expansion has not<br>
been raised in the Russian government. In fact, he said, Moscow seeks a<br>
further liberalization of its foreign trade relations. (Itar-Tass, September 24)<br>
<p>
UNCERTAINTY OVER HEALTH OF RUSSIAN PRESIDENT. Mixed signals continued to<br>
come from Moscow yesterday as the Kremlin insisted that President Boris<br>
Yeltsin was in charge of the government even as his doctors said Russia's<br>
ailing leader might not be well enough to undergo heart bypass surgery.<br>
Yeltsin met yesterday for forty minutes with Prime Minister Viktor<br>
Chernomyrdin, after which Chernomyrdin insisted that Yeltsin was well enough<br>
to stay in office and should not step down. (Interfax, September 24) The<br>
doctors treating the president were to decide today whether and when to<br>
operate. Communist party leader Gennady Zyuganov has already said that<br>
Yeltsin should step down and that fresh elections should be held in three<br>
months if the operation does not take place. (Interfax, September 23) <br>
<p>
The Russian stock market has reacted sharply to the apparent seriousness of<br>
Yeltsin's illness. But although stocks in Russian companies fell five<br>
percent in busy trading, short-term government treasury bills, which make up<br>
most of the Russian government's internal debt, registered little reaction.<br>
(Interfax, September 24) The explanation may lie in the fact while the stock<br>
market contains a good deal of foreign money, the treasury bill market is<br>
dominated by domestic funds. Many Russian investors are more skeptical than<br>
their western counterparts about the importance of political developments,<br>
taking the view that high-level politics are of little relevance to the<br>
economy. <br>
<p>
MAYOR OF VLADIVOSTOK REINSTATED. President Boris Yeltsin has signed a decree<br>
reinstating the mayor of Vladivostok, Viktor Cherepkov, to the post from<br>
which Yeltsin dismissed him two years ago. (Interfax, September 24)<br>
Cherepkov was democratically elected in 1992 after winning more votes than<br>
all eighteen of his rivals put together. While in office he campaigned<br>
against bribery and corruption among high-ranking city officials, but was<br>
dismissed by presidential decree in 1994, following allegations that he had<br>
himself taken bribes. Cherepkov never ceased to protest his innocence,<br>
however, and this year an investigation by the newspaper Izvestiya concluded<br>
that he had been framed by Yevgeny Nazdratenko, governor of Primorsky krai,<br>
of which Vladivostok is the capital. Last month, a Moscow court found in<br>
Cherepkov's favor, ruling that Yeltsin had overstepped his powers in sacking<br>
Cherepkov. <br>
<p>
The Cherepkov case could safeguard the posts of other democratically elected<br>
officials. On June 6 of this year, Yeltsin signed a controversial decree in<br>
which he granted himself the right to dismiss popularly elected regional<br>
governors. Although the constitutionality of this decree has yet to be<br>
challenged, the Cherepkov case suggests that Yeltsin might find himself on<br>
shaky ground if he tried to employ the June 6 decree.<br>
<p>
PESSIMISM ABOUT RUSSIAN ECONOMIC PROSPECTS. Participants in a seminar in<br>
Helsinki on September 23-24 took a gloomy view of Russia's short-term<br>
economic prospects and were not much more enthusiastic about likely<br>
medium-term developments. Many speakers said the long-awaited growth in<br>
Russian output is unlikely to come before 1998 and that the economic climate<br>
remains inhospitable to foreign investment. Russian deputy economics<br>
minister Andrei Svinarenko said his ministry's best-case forecast for 1997<br>
is zero growth, followed by a recovery in output only in 1998. Other<br>
speakers were equally downbeat. Aleksei Mastepanov of Russia's fuel and<br>
energy ministry noted that Russian oil production has fallen by 47 percent<br>
from its 1980s peak, coal by 34 percent, and gas by 7 percent. His<br>
ministry's projections for the year 2000 suggest a further decline -- to<br>
between 88 and 100 percent of last year's level. Mastepanov described<br>
ambitious plans for energy conservation and a revival of energy production,<br>
but acknowledged that large investments are required and may not be<br>
forthcoming. <br>
<p>
Much of the discussion revolved around the issue of whether or not standard<br>
free market reform prescriptions are working in Russia. Several senior<br>
Russian economists deplored Russia's "deindustrialization" and described it<br>
as the main effect of the reforms. Simon Clarke of Britain's University of<br>
Warwick argued that formal privatization has not changed the behavior of<br>
Russia's former state enterprises. Instead of collapsing and releasing labor<br>
and capital for new, market- oriented firms, former state enterprises are<br>
being kept alive by Soviet-era managers in ways that western experts and<br>
advisers did not foresee. The result, according to Clarke, is continued<br>
stagnation. Alan Gelb of the World Bank compared Russia with other<br>
transition economies. He offered some grounds for hope that Russia will at<br>
some point follow the pattern of output recovery after financial<br>
stabilization that has been seen in Poland, Estonia, the Czech Republic, and<br>
others. But he cautioned that in Russia this process has been delayed by the<br>
incoherence of Russian reforms, the low credibility of the Russian<br>
government, and exceptionally high rates of crime. (A Monitor correspondent<br>
participated in the seminar)<br>
<p>
LIVSHITS' NEW ROLE. The September 19 appointment of Aleksandr Livshits to<br>
the Russian Security Council puts the finance minister in a delicate<br>
position. The appointment follows mounting criticism from the Russian<br>
defense ministry over projected defense spending in next year's federal<br>
budget and comes amid complaints that the regular army is being shortchanged<br>
in relation to other "power structures" in the release of government funds<br>
this year. (See below, and Monitor, September 19) Against this background,<br>
the appointment of Livshits has been interpreted in the Russian press as a<br>
sign that Yeltsin's former economics adviser remains in favor with the<br>
president and is being given the role of counterweight within the powerful<br>
Security Council to Aleksandr Lebed's pet economist, Sergei Glazyev.<br>
(Kommersant-daily, September 20) Asked to assess his role on the Security<br>
Council, Livshits said he was there to ensure that grandiose plans for<br>
ensuring Russia's military security were kept in line with the country's<br>
economic capabilities. (NTV, September 19) <br>
<p>
WAGE PROTESTS AND DISSATISFACTION IN THE RUSSIAN ARMY. A Russian newspaper<br>
reported on September 19 that information on the government's mounting wage<br>
debt to civilian employees of the Defense Ministry had been suppressed<br>
deliberately by former defense minister Pavel Grachev. Sources within the<br>
ministry suggested that Grachev had acted on the orders of government<br>
leaders, who feared that publication of the wage arrears figures would hurt<br>
Boris Yeltsin's reelection chances. According to the same report, current<br>
Russian defense minister Igor Rodionov is behind the decision to make those<br>
figures public. Rodionov is reportedly motivated by his sympathy for the<br>
ministry's civilian employees, who are owed more than 6 trillion rubles,<br>
and, probably of greater importance, by a decision to launch a<br>
no-holds-barred battle within the government for greater defense funding.<br>
(Nezavisimaya gazeta, September 19)<br>
<p>
The revelations about wage arrears come amid rumors of growing<br>
disgruntlement in the ranks of Russia's regular armed forces. Indeed, a<br>
German newspaper claims to have obtained a Russian Defense Ministry report<br>
indicating that opposition to President Boris Yeltsin and his government is<br>
increasing among Russian servicemen. According to Der Tagesspiegel, military<br>
leaders also claim in the report that they can no longer guarantee the<br>
loyalty of their troops. (AP, September 22) A similar conclusion was voiced<br>
last week by Segodnya's respected military analyst Pavel Felgengauer, who<br>
suggested that a failure by the government to solve the problem of defense<br>
financing might "lead to a social protest that could transform into a mutiny<br>
and eventually even challenge civilian rule in Russia." (AP, September 19)<br>
<p>
THE WESTERN REGION<br>
<p>
WHATEVER HAPPENED TO THE RUSSIAN-MOLDOVAN TROOP WTHDRAWAL AGREEMENT?<br>
Moldovan foreign minister Mihai Popov, meeting on September 23 with his<br>
Russian counterpart Yevgeny Primakov in New York, urged the "soonest<br>
possible ratification by the Duma" of the agreement to withdraw Russian<br>
troops from Moldova and of the Russian-Moldovan political treaty.<br>
Ratification would "strengthen confidence" between the two countries, Popov<br>
said. Primakov, who says he has made relations with CIS countries a "top<br>
priority," has yet to respond to Chisinau's invitation to visit Moldova.<br>
(Flux, Basapress, September 23)<br>
<p>
The troop withdrawal agreement, signed by Prime Ministers Viktor<br>
Chernomyrdin and Andrei Sangheli in October 1994, was turned into a dead<br>
letter by the Russian side when it claimed immediately afterward that the<br>
document required parliamentary ratification. The agreement itself contained<br>
no such provision and was obviously not going to be ratified in a Russian<br>
Duma dominated by nationalists and Communists. The Kremlin, moreover, has<br>
made no attempt to obtain ratification. Moldovan president Mircea Snegur has<br>
himself practically dropped the issue since embarking more than a year ago<br>
on an uphill effort to win reelection. In order to achieve that goal Snegur<br>
feels he needs, at the least, Moscow's benign acceptance. <br>
<p>
The bilateral political treaty, signed by Presidents Boris Yeltsin and<br>
Snegur back in 1990 before their countries had become subjects of<br>
international law, contains as its centerpiece an unqualified mutual<br>
recognition of the two countries' independence and territorial integrity. In<br>
February 1995, Snegur accepted and initialed a "supplementary protocol,"<br>
proposed to him by Yeltsin as an attachment to the political treaty and as a<br>
condition for the Kremlin's support in winning the treaty's ratification.<br>
The protocol provided for joint Russian-Moldovan actions, including military<br>
measures, to defend regional peace and security if either side considers<br>
that a threat to peace has arisen. Leaders of the governing Agrarian<br>
Democratic party extricated Chisinau from the trap by refusing to discuss<br>
the protocol prior to the withdrawal of Russian troops from Moldova.<br>
Meanwhile the deadlock persists, and the issue of Russian troops unlawfully<br>
stationed in an independent European state against its will seems to be<br>
fading from international attention. <br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
