<td><h1> Transcaucasian Press about Human Rights 10/25-31
</h1></td>
</table>
<p>
TRANSCAUCASIAN PRESS ABOUT HUMAN RIGHTS <br>
October 25-31, 1996<br>
Compiled by the Caucasian Institute for Peace, Democracy and 
Development (CIPDD) <br>
in collaboration with the VERTIC-IWPR Media 
Resource
Centre in Tbilisi
<p>     
     
     
<h2>Armenia</h2>
     <p>
<b>Hope Given to Kim Balaian</b><br>
Report from the press-conference of Kim Balayan's lawyer Rouben 
Sahakian. One of the leaders of the Dashnaktsutiun party Kim 
Balayan was arrested on September 26. Though a month passed from 
the day of his arrest, the staff of the investigation group was 
not presented to Kim Balayan. When being the Head of the 
Juridical Commission of Armenian Parliament (in 1990-1995), he 
issued a document about dismissing the persons who are now 
investigating his case. Normally, they should have prejudice 
against him. According to the wife of Kim Balayan, he is kept in 
one cell with criminals, among whom are persons suffering from 
tuberculosis, paranoia, venereal diseases; also drug addicts. It 
is a clear violation of the law, his lawyer, Rouben Sahakian, 
says. The accusation was declared only on October 8. He is 
charged with high treason, participation in mass breaches of the 
peace and illegal weapon custody. The nature of the first two 
accusations, according to the lawyer, is hard to understand 
because they are 'too theoretical'. As to the third one, the 
search in Kim Balayan's flat was implemented with such flagrant 
violations that it has no perspectives.
"Lragir" (Herald), No. 129, October 29, p. 1.
     
     
     
<h2>Azerbaijan</h2>
     
<b>The Legislation on Conscription to the Army May Be Revised</b><br>
A special department of the Azerbaijani parliament is going to 
bring in a bill on amendments to the law on conscription to the 
army. According to a high-ranking official, one of the 
amendments provides for reduction of the term of military 
service to 18 or 24 months. The Defence Ministry, he says, is 
getting ready to demobilise in 1997 those who have served longer 
than that. Anyway, the ministry will also demobilise the 
servicemen conscripted before 1993.
"Muhalifat" No. 82, October 30, p. 1
     <p>
<b>It's Something Matter with Human Rights in Azerbaijan </b><br>
Commenting on maintaining human rights in Azerbaijan, Richard 
Kozlarich, Ambassador of the USA to Azerbaijan, says: "Not 
everything is well in this sphere". In his words, he has met 
more than once with the Procurator General and other high-
ranking officials to talk over the issue of religious minorities 
in Azerbaijan. "At these meetings I was emphasising the problem 
of registration of the Human Rights organisations in Azerbaijan. 
Existence of such organisations is necessary as they can affect 
positively the international image of the country", he  says. 
"Zerkalo" No. 43, October 26, p. 4
     <p>
<b>A New Candidate to Be a "Prisoner of Consciousness"? </b><br>
According to Natella Bairamova, a member of the Azerbaijani 
Society for Women's Rights, Kamal Talibov, an activist of the
Popular Front of Azerbaijan, arrested in the village of Siyagut, 
the Nakhichevan Autonomous Republic, is still in custody. Some 
of his countrymen surmise that K. Talibov was arrested for 
publishing his critical article about the living conditions in 
Nakhichevan in the "Muhalifat" ("The Opposition") newspaper on 
September 21. 'If Talibov is not released by November 3, i.e. 
after the maximal term of administrative detainment is expired, 
the Human Rights Centre of Azerbaijan will commence detailed 
monitoring of the case', Eldar Zeynalov, Director f the HRC, 
says. By the Amnesty International standards, Talibov may be 
considered a "prisoner of consciousness", as a prisoner confined 
for open defence of civil rights and freedoms via the press and 
for his peaceful political activities.
"Zerkalo" No. 43, October 26, p. 2
     <p>
<b>Four More POWs Discovered</b><br>
Ibrahim Husseinov, the head of the working group of the state 
commission for POWs and hostages, says officials of the ICRC 
have found out the names of four more Azeris, kept in captivity 
in Armenia. They are: Nazim Hafiz-oglu Mehtiyev, Salahaddin 
Perviz-oglu Kyazimzade, Elchin Farzali-oglu Jafarov and Faik 
Veysal-oglu Gadimov.
"Azadlig" No. 134, October 26, p. 2
     <p>
<b>Every 8 Hours a Policeman Dismissed?</b><br>
According to Ramil Usubov, Minister for Interior, 900 criminals, 
including 120 charged with the crimes against the state, have 
been extradited to Azerbaijan from the CIS countries by virtue 
of respective agreements between the law-enforcement bodies of 
Azerbaijan and the CIS states. He says more than 20 officials of 
the Azerbaijani interior ministry have been accused of various 
crimes and 2500 more policemen fired for neglect of  their 
duties.
"Ezhednevnie Novosti" No. 40, October 25, p. 2
     <p>
<b>M. Chehragani Left Iran</b><br>
Dr. Mahmudali Chehragani, one of the leaders of the National 
Movement of Azeris in Iran, and his family members have 
illegally emigrated from Iran. Facing political pressure, he was 
compelled to withdraw from the last parliamentary elections. A 
committee for Dr. Chehragani's rights was established in 
Azerbaijan. According to Piruz Dilenchi, Chairman of the North 
Committee of the National Liberating Movement of Southern 
Azerbaijan, the pressure on Dr. Chehragani has significantly 
increased lately: he was banned to meet his students; his car 
and house were confiscated. Out of 600 people arrested in recent 
times, 200 were his sympathisers. For Dr. Chehragani's safety 
sake, Mr. Dilenchi refused to reveal his present abode
"Yeni Mussavat" No. 55, October 25, p. 1
     <p>
<b>Austrian Consul Met Kenan Gurel</b><br>
Vekoslav Freisitzer, Consul General of Austria to Russia, has 
visited Baku for a short time to meet with Kenan Gurel, a 
citizen of Turkey and Austria, sentenced to 15 years' 
imprisonment for participation in the attempt at a coup d'etat 
of March, 1995. Having met with Gurel and learned his health 
conditions, Mr. Freisitzer said Austria  was trying to shorten 
the term of his imprisonment. Besides, an independent Austrian 
court, he said, was considering a possibility of the political 
asylum for Mahiz Javadov, one of the leaders of the unsuccessful 
coup d'etat.
"Azadlig" No. 133, October 25, p. 1
<p>          
<b>The Ruling Party Violating Law</b><br>
In accordance with the Law on Political Parties, no party or 
political organization has a right to found its local bodies at 
ministries, State departments, enterprises or educational 
institutions. Nevertheless, the ruling party "Yeni Azerbaijan" 
("New Azerbaijan") has set up its local committee (partcom) at 
the Administration of the State Railroad. The senior engineer 
and two deputy chairmen of the Administration have signed an 
appeal demanding for measures against interference of the party 
in the activities of the administration. According to the 
appeal, the partcom, following the worst Communist traditions, 
is endeavoring to promote party creatures to administrative 
positions.
"Azadlig" No. 133, October 25, p. 2
     
<h2>Georgia</h2>

<b>Find Killers of Our Sons!</b><br>
Account of two criminal cases. Just 6 years ago, Mrs. 
Veruleishvili saw her son murdered in a road accident. Although 
she, as well as the police, know well the personality of the 
driver, for all this time the law-enforcement  authorities have 
been claiming him to be dwelling in Russia. He cannot be 
extradited, they say, due to lack of finances for his 
transportation. As to the second case, Mrs. Kaladze's son was 
murdered at home by two killers three years ago (as it turned 
out later they murdered him by mistake). The law-enforcement 
authorities are telling the same story: the murderers are in 
Russian and there is no opportunity of their extradition. 
"Akhali Taoba" No. 178, October 30, pp. 1, 5
     <p>
<b>Nobody Can Be Tortured or Commit a Suicide in the Fifth 
Isolation Ward</b><br>
Report about a press-conference of Kakha Targamadze, Interior 
Minister, October 29. For the first 9 months of the year, he 
says, the law-enforcement authorities have registered 8912 
crimes altogether, 7563 of them (84.9%) are already revealed. In 
comparison with the last year, the crime has reduced by 27.8%, 
including murders by 42.1% and robbery by 50.5%.  The minister 
blames Mrs. Elena Tevdoradze, Chairman of the Parliamentary 
Subcommittee for Penitentiary Reforms, for violating the 
presumption of innocence when reporting about tortures by the 
police. He claims the isolation ward No. 5, where the most 
dangerous criminals are confined, to be under strict control, so 
that there can be neither tortures nor suicides of the 
prisoners.
"Akhali Taoba" No. 178, October 30, pp. 1, 2
     <p>
<b>Death Penalty Abolished?</b><br>
Interview with Elena Tevdoradze, Chairman of the Parliamentary 
Subcommittee on Penitentiary Reforms. The Constitution of 
Georgia, she says, provided for abolishment of death penalty in 
2 years. Besides, the death penalty is seriously impeding 
Georgia's entering the European Council. So, the parliament is 
to debate the issue in the near future. There are 50 sentenced 
to death prisoners in Georgia nowadays, she says. On the other 
hand, as Mrs. Tevdoradze claims, the penitentiary system of 
Georgia is not ready to substitute death penalty with a life- 
long imprisonment.
"Droni" No. 84, October 29 - November 1, p. 2
     <p>
<b>An Ombudsman Floating</b><br>
On October 28, the Bureau of the Georgian parliament crossed out 
debates over the nomination of Ombudsman of Georgia, scheduled 
for next week. Professor Rismag Gordeziani, the last candidate 
to occupy the post, had withdrawn due to his health conditions. 
The National Democratic Party offered Ms. Marika Baghdavadze of 
the Ilia Tchavtchavadze Society, but the other parliamentary 
factions rejected the candidate by reason of being unfamiliar 
with her personality. So the post remains vacant.
"Akhali Taoba" No. 177,  October 29, p. 1
     <p>
<b>First, a Gas-Mask Was Put on the Constrained Prisoner's Face and 
Then He Was Beaten by Truncheons</b><br>
Interview with Mrs. Elena Tevdoradze, Chairman of the 
Parliamentary Subcommittee for Penitentiary Reforms. She cites a 
letter of 21-year-old prisoner George Butikashvili, charged with 
illegal possession of a gun: he claims that he has found the gun 
on a road by chance, but the examination confirms that Kurdadze, 
the former Tbilisi procurator, was killed with just  this gun. 
Nowadays, Butikashvili, confined in the before-trial ward No. 5, 
suffers from asthma,  he also has a kidney removed after an 
operation. His letter says the law-enforcement officers regularly 
torture him: they put a gas-mask on his face to muffle his crying 
and wrap his wrists with newsprint when menacing him to hide the 
signs of the hand-cuffs.
"Alia" No. 133, October 28, pp. 1, 2
     <p>
<b>The Winner of a Trial in the Constitutional Court Arrested a Few 
Minutes Later</b><br>
Account of Tengiz Sudadze's trial in the Constitutional Court of 
Georgia, October 30. On August 9, Nugzar Nadaraia,  the mayor of 
Poti, banned the "Kolkh" company, headed by Mr. Sudadze, from 
building an oil terminal. The court declared Nadaraia's order 
contradicting the legislation: as the company signed the 
contract to build the terminal on October 18, 1995, and had 
already completed a part of the works by the time of the mayor's 
ban, it has the right to proceed with building. But just after 
living the court-room, Mr. Sudadze was arrested by the law- 
enforcement authorities. No official statement on the incident 
has been made yet. Commenting on the fact, Gia Meparishvili, 
Deputy Chairman of the Court, says he has no idea about the 
reasons of the arrest.
"Akhali Taoba" No. 179, October 31, pp. 1, 2
     <p>
<b>I Am Afraid of My Police:</b><br>
Not long since, Irakli Gongladze burglarised Major Ramaz 
Eloshvili's, an officer of the Anti-drug National Bureau, the 
Interior Ministry, apartment. Gongladze accused Eloshvili's 
friend Kakha Kurashvili of providing the information about the 
valuables in the apartment. Kurashvili was arrested, with 
breaching required procedures (the police did not proceed their 
papers and the arrest warrant, while the detainee was conveyed 
to the police station being almost naked), and his wife beaten 
by the policemen commanded by Eloshvili himself. The case was 
forwarded to the Procurator's Office and from this moment, 
according to law, the ministry has nothing to do with it. 
Nevertheless, some officers of the bureau keep on summoning 
Kurashvili's relatives. Niko Japaridze, Deputy Head of the 
Bureau, refused to comment on the case and banned his inferiors 
to do the same. 'Let's give up being zealous democrats:', he 
offers journalists.
"Alia" No. 135, October 31, pp. 1, 2
     <p>
<b>The Educational System Prefers the Pose of the Ostrich (and 
Becomes Well-Off?)</b><br>
Account of some problems of the educational system of Georgia. 
While Tamaz Kvachantiradze, the minister for education, assures 
that studies in the first 9 classes (out of 11) of the Georgian 
secondary schools are free of charge, the school directors 
compel parents to pay for their children's education. 'Those 
discontented can go away!', one of the school directors said to 
parents, adding that he would increase the payment unless they 
gave up complaining. Such a situation can be observed in almost 
all the schools. At the same time, Mr. Kvachantiradze keeps 
saying: 'These facts, if really taken place, must be considered 
a crime, but hitherto we have revealed none'.
"Alia" No. 135, October 31, pp. 1, 
  <p>
<hr>
<p>
