<head>
<title> Transcaucasian Press about Human Rights 10/18-24
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF">
<table border=0 cellpadding=6>
<tr>
<td><h1> Transcaucasian Press about Human Rights 10/18-24
</h1></td>
</table>
<p>
TRANSCAUCASIAN PRESS ABOUT HUMAN RIGHTS <br>
October 18-24, 1996<br>
Compiled by the Caucasian Institute for Peace, Democracy and 
Development (CIPDD) <br>
in collaboration with the VERTIC-IWPR Media 
Resource
Centre in Tbilisi
<p>     
     
<h2>Armenia</h2>
     <br>
<b>Searching for the Legislative Field for Dialogue</b><br>
Report from the meeting with journalists of human rights 
activists Armen Hovannisian, Aghasi Arshakian and Vova 
Hakhverdian. Protection of rights of those arrested was on the 
agenda. Armen Hovannisian criticised numerous human rights 
organisations in Armenia working on the base of grants, but doing 
nothing. Then they presented the list of 109 persons arrested 
after the September 25 events. Presence of many names with 
"information not available" shows that the work on the list was 
not properly done. However Armen Hovannisian noted that this list 
was prepared in conditions of almost total absence of official 
information. There are well known persons on the list - MPs, a 
Presidential candidate, political activists, who have been freed, 
that is why, the focus has to be on the persons, about whom the 
information was not available.
"Aravot" (Morning), No. 188, October 18, pp. 1, 3
     <p>
(The List of Persons Arrested on Political Reasons and Tortured 
after September 25 , not complete, was published in the "Aijm" 
("Now") newspaper (No. 38, October 18-24, 1996 p. 4-5.)
     <p>
<b>A Schoolboy Threw Himself from the Window of Dzerjinsky School. </b><br>
A woman called the newspaper, told about the event, and the 
reporter went to the school. According to the principal, two men 
from the military registration and enlistment office (voenkomat) 
came and asked to talk to one of the school-leaver, who was 18 
years old. As he saw them, the boy ran to the third floor, and 
then, seeing the approaching figures, threw himself out of the 
window. According to the military officer, he and his fellow did 
not do anything at all, the boy was so afraid that just jumped 
out of the window. The boy's aunt said the military men had come 
to their home at 6 in the morning. The boy is in hard conditions 
and will be operated on his head.
"Molorak" (Planet), No. 69, October 19, p. 1
     <p>
     
<h2>Azerbaijan</h2>
     <p>
<b>Islamists Will Face Hard Days</b><br>
The Azerbaijani law-enforcement authorities have concluded 
investigation of the activities of the Islamist Party of 
Azerbaijan. Namik Abbasov, Minister for State Security, says in 
accordance with the legislation the case will be brought to the 
Supreme Court in a month. The investigation, he claims, 
completely confirmed all the accusations against the party. 
However, neither the authorities nor the relatives of those 
detained can specify the articles of the Criminal Code the 
defendants are charged with. A lawyer, who prefers to keep his 
incognito, claims that the defendants will be charged, along 
with other articles, with high treason (article 57, providing 
for death penalty).
"7 Gun" No. 110, October 18, p. 1
     <p>
<b>International Conference on Refugees' Problems</b><br>
An international conference on the problems of refugees and 
deportees organised by the State Commission for the 
International Humanitarian Aid and Technical Assistance in 
collaboration with the Committee of the Asian Muslims and the 
Islamic organisation "Nijat" ("Aid") has taken place in the 
House of Government of Azerbaijan. Opening the conference, Izzet 
Rustamov, Vice-Premier, said delegations from Kuwait, Qatar, 
Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Syria,  the Sudan, etc. were participating 
in the forum. Representatives of the international organisations 
functioning in Azerbaijan and some ambassadors took part in the 
conference as well.
"Bakinsky Rabochy", October 18, p. 1
     <p>
<b>Students Are Determined to Defend the Building of a College</b><br>
On October 21, the Azim Azimzade Arts College was picketed by up 
to 100 of its students and professors. The authorities are going 
to lease the premises of the college (it has been occupying the 
building since 1930) to foreign companies. According to one of 
the students, if the picket fails, the action will be kept on in 
front of the president's office.
"7 Gun" No. 111, October 22, p. 1
     <p>
<b>Aid to the Schools in the Refugees' Settlements</b><br>
At a meeting with Lidya Rasulova, the minister for education, 
participants of the international conference on the problems of 
refugees and IDPs in Azerbaijan undertook to assist in providing 
the secondary schools in the settlements of refugees and IDPs 
with text-books and school-equipment, the press-centre of the 
Ministry of Education of Azerbaijan reports. The number of the 
schools to be aided is being calculated at present.
"Panorama" No. 187, October 22, p. 3
     <p>
<b>Lists of the Missed Detailing</b><br>
According to Pierre Dorbat (?), representative of the 
International Committee of the Red Cross in Baku, the ICRC 
offices in Baku and Yerevan are detailing the lists of those 
missed during the Karabakh war. Azerbaijan claims 1800 Azeris to 
be missed, while Armenia has provided the list of 250 its missed 
citizens. The ICRC will submit more accurate data to the 
leadership of the both countries. In the future, the ICRC is 
going to defend rights of the refugees after their repatriation. 
"Milliyet" No. 87, October 22, p. 3
     <p>
<b>The Head of Administration Beat a Village Teacher</b><br>
The information centre of the "Mussavat" party claims I. 
Gurbanov, the director of village school No. 5, the Imishlin 
district, to have been beaten by A. Mamedov, the head of the 
local administration, in the latter's office. Gurbanov had freed 
the pupils of his school from compulsory harvesting cotton for a 
day when a bus to carry the pupils did not come. Mamedov ordered 
to arrest and convey him to the police station. After the 
teachers of the school threatened to go on strike, Gurbanov was 
released, but Mamedov summoned him to the office and beat him 
severely. Gurbanov is reportedly a member of the Council of 
Veterans, Chairman of the Union of Intelligentsia and Deputy 
Chairman of the regional branch of the "Yeni Azerbaijan" party. 
"7 Gun" No. 112, October 24, p. 1
     <p>
<b>Refugees Returning Home</b><br>
Paolo Lembo, the UN Co-ordinator in Azerbaijan, has held a press- 
conference on occasion of  The UN Day (October 24). He said the 
basements of the cottages for refugees were to be set up in the 
liberated Agdam and Fizuli districts just that day. After the 
press-conference, Mr. Lembo and Vice-Premier Azad Sharifov
signed an agreement on "the first stage of reconstructing works 
on the liberated territories". The agreement provides for 
creation of a special agency to control the reconstruction. The 
UN Development Program and the World Bank have allocated 
$3,300,000 to this project, the first $500,000 will be received 
in a few days.
"7 Gun" No. 112, October 24, p. 3
     <p>
     
<h2>Georgia</h2>
     
<b>Tombs of the Party Leader's Parents Defiled</b><br>
On October 20, the Board of the Party for National Ideology made 
an official statement condemning defilement of the tombs of the 
party leader Zurab Gagnidze's parents. Mr. Gagnidze tells the 
newspaper that on October 19 he found his parents' tombs defiled. 
The board blames 'modern Vandals and fundamentalists' 
discontented with the party's new, pro-Shevardnadze course, for 
the incident, while Gagnidze claims some women, Zviad 
Gamsakhurdia's supporters, to be responsible for the defilement. 
"Akhali Taoba" No. 170, October 21, p. 2
     <p>
<b>Don't Blame the Law-Enforcement Authorities for Suppressive 
Methods</b><br>
Account of a press-conference of Kakha Targamadze, Minister of 
Interior, and Jamlet Babilashvili, Procurator General of 
Georgia, October 18. Nowadays, there are no political prisoners 
in Georgia, they say, all those claiming themselves to be are in 
fact criminals. In Mr. Targamadze's words, the police will keep 
breaking up protest actions by truncheons until every citizen 
obeys the law. The police, he says, are the very state 
authorities empowered to apply force in due course. As to the 
Georgian police, the minister claims them to be much more 
liberal compared with those in foreign countries.
"Dilis Gazeti" No. 185, October 19, p. 1
     <p>
<b>Will Refugees Take Part in the Coming Parliamentary Elections in 
Abkhazia?</b><br>
Interview with Kakha Chitaia, Chairman of the Parliamentary 
Foreign Committee. He disapproves of the refugees' participating 
in the coming parliamentary elections in Abkhazia even though 
the elections are held under the auspices of the UN (the Bosnian 
model). In his opinion, the results of such a scenario are 
completely unpredictable. For instance, the Abkhazian 
separatists may declare the elections outside Abkhazia to have 
been gerrymandered. Thus, it will be harder for the Georgian 
leadership to insist on the unlegitimacy of the Sukhumi 
authorities.
"Droni" No. 82, October 22-24, p. 3
     <p>
<b>Three Georgian Soldiers Have Hung Themselves</b><br>
Report about a press-conference of the organisation for 
protection of soldiers' rights, October 22. Among the problems 
of the army there is a rather low-caloric diet: 1500 calories 
instead of needed 4000. Worse still, the rate of mortality in 
the army has increased in recent times: 7 soldiers have been 
lost since the beginning of the year, 3 of them hanged 
themselves because of extremely hard conditions.
"Resonansi" No. 203, October 23, pp. 1. 3
     <p>
<b>Listen to Us or We Will Declare Mass Disobedience</b><br>
Report about a press-conference in Tbilisi State University, 
focused on the problem of the Black Sea International University 
(so-called Turkish University), October 22. Participants of the 
press-conference were rather negative towards the Turkish 
University. 'The more Georgians learn the Turkish language, the 
easier Turkey will complete its tasks in Georgia', Irina 
Gotsiridze, an expert on Turkey, claims. The participants 
declared their readiness for street protest actions ('we have 
appealed to the authorities ten times without any result') 
demanding to put off matriculation to the university. They also 
cite Demuri Mikadze, Chief of the Tbilisi Police, who had said 
to them (as they claim): 'I'm too against the university. You 
must stand firm and act just like your comrades acted defending 
the Georgian language' (in 1978, Georgian students launched a 
protest demonstration and compelled then government to turn down 
a project of the Communist Party to make Russian an official 
language of Georgia).
"Akhali Taoba" No. 172, October 23, pp. 1, 2
     <p>
<b>The Statistics Gives Rise to Particular and Common Questions The </b><br>
newspaper appeals to the Georgian  authorities for their 
comments on the following statistics: in the first 6 months of 
the year the law-enforcement authorities have registered 7222 
crimes; 344 of them were committed by the underage (by 59 cases 
more than in the last year). Besides, the number of underage 
beggars has increased dramatically in recent times: in October 
14-21, only in one of the districts of Tbilisi, the police have 
revealed 46 children-beggars.
"Dilis Gazeti" No. 187, October 23, p. 1
     <p>
<b>An Aid to Help Nobody</b><br>
Interview with Ms. Tsitso Bakuradze, Deputy Head of the 
Department for Living Standards, the Ministry of Labour and 
Social Protection. The precise number of the destitute in 
Georgia, she claims, will become clear after all the citizens 
formally appeal to the ministry for social protection. 'We 
expect the number to be more than 120 thousands', she says. The 
ministry has developed a project of social protection providing 
for three categories of the destitute: the first one embodies 
single pensioners (if their pension is the only source of their 
income); the second - the other pensioners and the students 
below 18 years of age; the third - the families residing in 
towns if all the members are unemployed.
"Dilis Gazeti" ("Morning Newspaper") No. 188, October 24, p. 2
     <p>
<b>A Delegation from Tsalka Complains of the Local Administration </b><br>
About 50 residents of the Tsalka district of Georgia (populated 
mostly by ethnic Azeris and Greeks) have been holding a protest 
action in front of the State Office since October 22. They are 
demanding to dismiss George Kvaliashvili, the head of the local 
administration. Embezzlement of the humanitarian aid; wrong 
policy in the land reform; sharp deficit of the electricity, 
despite regular payments: this is a brief list of the problems 
the locals complain about.
"Alia" No. 131, October 24-25, p. 3
<p>
<hr>
