<!-- body="start" -->
The following is the latest version of the monthly publication,<br>
"TransCaucasus: A Chronology."  This issue covers events in the region for<br>
the month of December, 1996.<br>
  For more information or to be added to the email distribution list,<br>
please contact the author, Richard Giragosian. The "TransCaucasus: A<br>
Chronology" is now entering its sixth year of monthly publication.<br>
<p>
Richard Giragosian<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
email: giragosi@essential.org<br>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
<p>
                        TransCaucasus<br>
                        A Chronology<br>
                       (E-Mail Version)*<br>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
Vol. VI                  January, 1997                         No.1<br>
<p>
<p>
The TransCaucasus: A Chronology is a chronological summary of the=20<br>
significant social, economic, and political events in the lower=20<br>
Caucasus, as reported by local and international media and selected=20<br>
sources in the region.  Full acknowledgement should be given to all=20<br>
material quoted from or based on this publication.<br>
<p>
Compiled and written by Richard Giragosian (giragosi@essential.org)<br>
Edited and designed by Christopher Hekimian<br>
<p>
ISSN 1078-3113<br>
<p>
A Publication Of The Armenian National Committee of America<br>
*******************************************************************<br>
<p>
Republic of=20<br>
Armenia<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
29,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than Maryland<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan (east) 566 km<br>
Nakhichevan (south) 221 km<br>
Georgia 164 km<br>
Iran 35 km<br>
Turkey 268 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
3.6 million<br>
68% urban<br>
110.5 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
93.3% Armenian<br>
1.5% Russian<br>
1.7% Kurdish<br>
3.5% Assyrian, Greek, other<br>
<p>
<p>
Leadership:  Levon Ter Petrosian, President; Hrant Bagratian, Prime=20<br>
Minister; Vahan Papazian, Foreign Minister.=20<br>
<p>
Independence:  Armenia re-established its independence on September=20<br>
23, 1991, after more than 70 years of Soviet rule.  The first=20<br>
Armenian Republic was established on May 28, 1918.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Armenia joined the CIS in March 1992 and=20<br>
CIS Defense Treaty in May 1992.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A constitution was adopted by national referendum on=20<br>
July 5, 1995.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Elections were held for Parliament July 5, 1995 and for=20<br>
President September 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to=20<br>
Armenia is Ambassador Peter Tomsen. The Armenian representative to=20<br>
the United States is Ambassador Rouben Shugarian.  The Armenian=20<br>
representative to the United Nations is Ambassador Alexander=20<br>
Arzoumanian.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
ARMENIA - Human Rights Watch World Report 1997<br>
<p>
The government's crackdown on the political opposition in September=20<br>
1996 cast a pall on human rights.  Given the 1995 ban on the=20<br>
Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF), Armenia's largest=20<br>
opposition party, and fraudulent 1995 parliamentary elections, the=20<br>
1996 crackdown accentuated the government's intolerance of any real=20<br>
political opposition.  This crushing of opposition forces bore out=20<br>
Defense Minister Vazgen Sarkissian's September 25 warning that=20<br>
"After [the September 25] events, even if they win 100 percent of=20<br>
the votes, neither the Army nor the National Security and Interior=20<br>
Ministry would recognize such political leaders."<br>
<p>
In April, the Ministry of Justice attempted to close Azg, the=20<br>
Ramkavar party daily, claiming that it needed to re-register under=20<br>
the auspices of the diaspora Ramkavar party, which is pro-Ter-<br>
Petrosian.<br>
<p>
The Ministry of Justice refused to register the Committee for the=20<br>
Defense of Political Prisoners, basing its decision on its view=20<br>
that since there were no political prisoners in Armenia, such an=20<br>
organization was unnecessary.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
2 December: A delegation of Armenian government officials led by=20<br>
parliamentary chairman Babken Ararktsian meet with Chinese=20<br>
parliamentary chairman Qiao Shi and other officials in Beijing. =20<br>
The meetings review bilateral relations and discuss the expansion=20<br>
of governmental cooperation in science, education and commerce. =20<br>
The relations between the two countries have steadily grown since=20<br>
China first extended diplomatic recognition in 1991.<br>
<p>
4 December: The Armenian government reveals plans to import 1.1=20<br>
billion cubic meters of natural gas in 1997 under the terms of the=20<br>
state social and economic developmental program recently ratified=20<br>
by the parliament.  The state plan also envisions utilizing foreign=20<br>
expertise to modernize the country's natural gas transport system. =20<br>
Armenian natural gas transport and supply facilities have remained=20<br>
idled since their closure in 1992 as a result of the full economic=20<br>
and transport blockade by Azerbaijan.  The Armenian government is=20<br>
also planning to privatize its state gas concern, Armgazprom, with=20<br>
assistance from the European Union.<br>
<p>
5 December: Armenian interior ministry police detain several=20<br>
leading members of the opposition National Progress party for=20<br>
questioning.  Although the incident remains unexplained, the=20<br>
detention is apparently the latest example of the government's=20<br>
campaign to intimidate and impede the country's political=20<br>
opposition parties.<br>
<p>
8 December: President Levon Ter Petrosian and National Security=20<br>
Minister Serge Sarkisian meet in Yerevan with Russian Border Troops=20<br>
Commander, General Andrei Nikolayev, to discuss the status of=20<br>
Russian military personnel in Armenia.  The border troops,=20<br>
stationed along the Armenian-Turkish border, are chronically short=20<br>
of adequate food supplies, as well as fuel and spare parts for=20<br>
their equipment.  The Russian troop presence is based on the terms=20<br>
of a 1992 renewable bilateral accord whereby both countries finance=20<br>
the troops' deployment and operational needs.=20<br>
<p>
9-10 December: Newly appointed Prime Minister Armen Sarkissian,=20<br>
during a visit to the United Kingdom, meets with several leading=20<br>
European companies to promote greater foreign investment in=20<br>
Armenia.  The prime minister also meets with several British=20<br>
government officials and parliamentarians.<br>
<p>
10 December: The Armenian Supreme Court issues sentences in the=20<br>
"Dro" trial, condemning three defendants to death on charges of=20<br>
terrorism, drug trafficking and crimes against the state.  The=20<br>
three defendants are Armen Munjoyan, Arsen Artsrouni and Armen=20<br>
Grigorian.  The Court also sentences the remaining eight defendants=20<br>
to terms ranging from three to fifteen years imprisonment and=20<br>
orders the state confiscation of all the defendants' property.  The=20<br>
defendants included Artavazd Manoukian who died while in custody=20<br>
from internal hemorrhaging and lack of medical attention.  ARF=20<br>
leader and defendant, Hrant Markarian, was found guilty of=20<br>
possessing multiple passports and an unregistered firearm, but was=20<br>
not found to have any connection to the "Dro" group, thus=20<br>
exonerating the ARF.  The prosecution had claimed that Markarian's=20<br>
participation with "Dro" proved the ARF's involvement as well.<br>
<p>
10 December: On his first formal visit to Moscow, newly appointed=20<br>
Armenian Foreign Minister Alexander Arzoumanian meets with Russian=20<br>
Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov.  The meeting reviews the=20<br>
conflicting positions regarding Nagorno Karabagh during the recent=20<br>
summit of the organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe=20<br>
(OSCE).  Although Moscow remains committed to guaranteeing the=20<br>
territorial integrity of Azerbaijan and providing a limited=20<br>
concession of autonomy for Nagorno Karabagh within Azerbaijan=20<br>
proper, the foreign minister promised to continue the constructive=20<br>
dialogue with all sides in their mediation attempt.<br>
<p>
10 December: The representative of the World Bank to Armenia,=20<br>
Vahram Nersissiants, announces that the multilateral lending=20<br>
organization is preparing to extend a new loans to the country. =20<br>
The World Bank assistance, providing credits for the development of=20<br>
Armenia's legislative and educational sectors, would bring the=20<br>
total level of World Bank aid to approximately $500 million.<br>
<p>
11 December: In response to the death sentences imposed the day=20<br>
before on three defendants in the "Dro" trial, the human rights=20<br>
organization Amnesty International issues a statement demanding=20<br>
that Armenian President Levon Ter Petrosian immediately commute the=20<br>
sentences.  The year long trial has been the centerpiece of the=20<br>
government's campaign against the country's largest opposition=20<br>
party, the Armenian revolutionary Federation (ARF), and the course=20<br>
of the trial has been marked by several legal irregularities and=20<br>
the sporadic violation of the civil liberties of the defendants.<br>
<p>
11 December: In a reflection of the growing level of corruption in=20<br>
the reforming economies of the former Soviet Union, Armenian=20<br>
officials announce that some 200 state tax inspectors have been=20<br>
dismissed amid charges of abuse of power and bribery.  There have=20<br>
been serious incidents of state corruption, including within the=20<br>
ranks of the police and law enforcement structures and among=20<br>
customs and tax inspectors in Armenia.=20<br>
<p>
11 December: The Turkish foreign ministry announces that Turkey=20<br>
will no longer open its border with Armenia as earlier promised by=20<br>
Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller.  The statement adds that the=20<br>
border will remain closed until Armenia "respects Azerbaijan's=20<br>
territorial integrity" and until the withdrawal of Nagorno Karabagh=20<br>
forces from the occupied areas of Azerbaijan proper.  The Armenian-<br>
Turkish border has been closed since 1992 in an effort to exert=20<br>
strategic economic pressure over the fragile Armenian economy.<br>
<p>
11 December: The head of the Armenian Church, Supreme Patriarch and=20<br>
Catholicos of All Armenians Garegin I, meets with Pope John Paul II=20<br>
at the Vatican.  The Pope states that he hopes the Armenian=20<br>
Apostolic Church will eventually reunite with the Roman Catholic=20<br>
Church.  The Armenian church split from Rome during the 5th=20<br>
century.<br>
<p>
13 December: Armenia's new Prime Minister Armen Sarkisian holds a=20<br>
meeting with representatives of the banned opposition Armenian=20<br>
Revolutionary Federation (ARF).  The meeting reviews the prime=20<br>
minister's plan for the coming year and discusses the importance of=20<br>
involving all political parties and groups in a constructive=20<br>
attempt to resolve the country's tense internal political crisis. =20<br>
<p>
13 December: The Korean electronics company Samsung opens its first=20<br>
store in Armenia, adding to its presence in the former Soviet=20<br>
Union.  Samsung maintains distribution outlets and stores in=20<br>
Russia, Ukraine and Kazakhstan. The company is also reportedly=20<br>
considering opening three other stores in Armenia.<br>
<p>
16 December: An official of the International Monetary Fund (IMF)=20<br>
announces that the Armenian government must make corrections to its=20<br>
economic program.  Specifically, the IMF criticizes the Ter=20<br>
Petrosian government's plan to allow a rise in inflation from this=20<br>
year's level of 10 percent to an annual rate of 14 percent for=20<br>
1997.  The country's fragile commercial banking sector is also=20<br>
cited as a systemic flaw, calling for immediate attention and for=20<br>
mergers and closures of some banking institutions.  The IMF also=20<br>
expresses concern over the government's failure to meet spending=20<br>
reduction targets set this year and its continued granting of state=20<br>
credit to the central bank beyond previously agreed upon limits.<br>
<p>
18 December: According to a new report issued by the U.S.=20<br>
organization Freedom House, Armenia is categorized as being only=20<br>
"partly free" by virtue of repression of the country's opposition=20<br>
political parties and their press and the less than democratic=20<br>
nature of the country's recent parliamentary and presidential=20<br>
elections.  The report, issued annually, is a world survey of=20<br>
governments and their patterns of democracy and governance as well=20<br>
as a review of each country's state of civil and political=20<br>
liberties.<br>
<p>
20 December: A recently formed U.S.-Armenian joint geological and=20<br>
prospecting company announces plans to drill three wells outside of=20<br>
Yerevan and conduct a seismic study of the region over the next=20<br>
five years.  The U.S. partner in the venture plans to invest some=20<br>
$10 million for the exploration and will launch oil production if=20<br>
any significant reserves are discovered.  Based on earlier surveys=20<br>
done by the Portuguese Parteko company and the British firm SPT,=20<br>
Armenia is expected to hold reserves of nearly 35 million tons of=20<br>
crude oil and 80 billion cubic meters of natural gas.  Any energy=20<br>
reserves found would be beneficial to the Armenian economy which is=20<br>
stalled by the paralyzing effects of the blockade of the country=20<br>
imposed five years ago by neighboring Turkey and Azerbaijan and due=20<br>
to the country's over 90 percent dependence on imports for its=20<br>
energy needs.<br>
<p>
_________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
Republic of Georgia<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
69,700 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than S. Carolina<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia 164 km<br>
Azerbaijan 322 km<br>
Russia 723 km<br>
Turkey 252 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
<p>
5.57 million<br>
56% urban<br>
78 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
69% Georgian<br>
9% Armenian<br>
6% Russian<br>
6% Ajarian<br>
5% Azerbaijani<br>
3% Ossetian<br>
2% Abkhazian<br>
<p>
Georgia includes the autonomous republics of Abkhazia and Ajaria=09<br>
and the South Ossetian Autonomous Region.<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Eduard Shevardnadze, President; Irakli Menagrashvili,=20<br>
Foreign Minister, Nickol Lekishvili, Secretary of State, Zurab=20<br>
Zhvania, Parliamentary Chairman.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Georgia established its independence on April 9,=20<br>
1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  The Georgian government joined the CIS on=20<br>
October 23, 1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was adopted in August, 1995,=20<br>
which reinstates a presidential form of government and provides for=20<br>
a strong executive branch and a unicameral 235-seat parliament.  A=20<br>
constitutional court was also created.  The constitution, however,=20<br>
does not address the status of Abkhazia, Ossetia or Ajaria.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Presidential and parliamentary elections were last held=20<br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to=20<br>
Georgia is Ambassador Kent Brown. The Georgian representative to=20<br>
the United States, as well as Canada and Mexico, is Ambassador Tedo=20<br>
Japaridze.  The Georgian representative to the United Nations is=20<br>
Ambassador Peter Chkiedze.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
GEORGIA - Human Rights Watch World Report 1997<br>
<p>
Human rights progress in Georgia stagnated in 1996.  Abuses=20<br>
persisted, especially torture and other forms of mistreatment in=20<br>
detention, arbitrary detention, appalling prison conditions, use of=20<br>
the death sentence, corruption of law enforcement officials and the=20<br>
judiciary, and harassment of some political dissidents. =20<br>
The year got off to a mixed start.  Monitors from the Organization=20<br>
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) termed the November=20<br>
5, 1995, parliamentary and presidential elections and the November=20<br>
19, 1995 , parliamentary run-offs "relatively open;" the=20<br>
assessments of the British Helsinki Group and others were generally=20<br>
less positive.<br>
Press freedom was widely enjoyed, although self-censorship remained=20<br>
a problem, particularly in the government media.  The September=20<br>
adoption of a law on state secrets that restricts some freedom of=20<br>
the media, and the de facto closure of independent TV channel=20<br>
Rustavi-2 on July 17, apparently for political reasons, raised some=20<br>
concern over the state of the independent media.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
8 December: The Georgian defense ministry announces the dismissal=20<br>
of the commander of the Georgian Navy, Rear Admiral Aleksandr=20<br>
Javakhishvili.  The Georgian naval forces have been undergoing=20<br>
recent modernization efforts and have moved swiftly in the last two=20<br>
months to exert a more assertive role in patrolling the waters off=20<br>
the strategic Georgian port facilities along the Black Sea coast.<br>
<p>
8 December: In a clash with Georgian forces, three Abkhazian=20<br>
officers are killed and two others are wounded in the Gali border=20<br>
district.  The Abkhazian government reacts by criticizing the=20<br>
Russian military peacekeepers stationed in the border region for=20<br>
their inability to prevent the attack.  The clash is reportedly the=20<br>
latest in a series of attacks seen as a new military offensive by=20<br>
the newly formed units of ethnic Georgian within Abkhazia.  The=20<br>
Abkhazian leadership has accused the Georgian security forces of=20<br>
having trained and armed theses units.<br>
<p>
9 December: The Ajarian parliament issues a statement protesting=20<br>
the Georgian refusal to authorize the creation of a free economic=20<br>
zone for the port city of Batumi.  The Georgian government has been=20<br>
reluctant to allow such a move, fearing that the economic zone=20<br>
would "encourage separatism" within the Ajarian Autonomous=20<br>
Republic.<br>
<p>
10 December: President Eduard Shevardnadze announces a formal=20<br>
moratorium on capital punishment.  Coinciding with International=20<br>
Human Rights Day, the announcement further states that the=20<br>
government will propose amendments to the penal code prohibiting=20<br>
the death sentence for high treason and other crimes, with the sole=20<br>
exception of premeditated murder with aggravating circumstances.<br>
<p>
10 December: During the course of a meeting with visiting Russian=20<br>
Duma chairman Gennady Seleznev, Shevardnadze and State Minister=20<br>
Niko Lekishvili protest the Russian government's trade restrictions=20<br>
on Georgian fruit and vegetables, wine and tea products.  The=20<br>
Georgian government has recently complained of the serious lack of=20<br>
market access for Georgian exports, citing the decline in bilateral=20<br>
trade.  Georgia is currently only the seventh leading trading=20<br>
partner with the Russian Federation.<br>
<p>
11 December: Chairman Seleznev, meets with Georgian officials=20<br>
during his participation in the summit of the Parliamentary=20<br>
Assembly of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation in Tbilisi.  The=20<br>
Russian official, in an address to the Georgian parliament, states=20<br>
that the Russian ratification of the pending bilateral accord on=20<br>
cooperation and political relations depends on the Georgian=20<br>
ratification of an agreement on the stationing of Russian troops in=20<br>
the country and other concessions by Tbilisi.  In protest to the=20<br>
statements, the Georgian opposition National Democratic=20<br>
parliamentary bloc walks out on the session.  The Russian official=20<br>
also states that Moscow would like to open a consulate in Batumi=20<br>
"to safeguard the interests of the 30,000 ethnic Russian community=20<br>
in Ajaria."=20<br>
<p>
14 December: Opposition National Democrats parliamentary bloc=20<br>
leader, Beso Djugeli, calls for the impeachment of Georgian Defense=20<br>
Minister Vardiko Nadibaidze for his "destruction of the country's=20<br>
military-industrial complex."  The defense minister has come under=20<br>
fire lately in the wake of his dismissal of Georgia's Navy=20<br>
commander.<br>
<p>
15-16 December: Tensions between Georgia and Russia escalate=20<br>
following the seizure of a Ukrainian ship by Russian naval forces=20<br>
near the Georgian Black Sea port of Batumi.  Georgia's=20<br>
parliamentary defense and security commission chairman Revaz Adamia=20<br>
and border troops commander, Major General Valeri Chkeidze, condemn=20<br>
the action by the Russian military as a threat to Georgian=20<br>
sovereignty and warn that it undermines prospects for the=20<br>
ratification of the 1994 bilateral Russian-Georgian border treaty. =20<br>
Further complicating the situation, Russian border troops have also=20<br>
sealed the Russian border with South Ossetia seriously disrupting=20<br>
commerce and trade.<br>
<p>
17 December: Ajarian parliamentary chairman Aslan Abashidze issues=20<br>
a communiqu=E9 announcing that Ajarian security forces have secured=20<br>
the administrative border with Georgia.  The statement explains the=20<br>
move as an attempt to control the transit of armed groups through=20<br>
Ajaria into Abkhazia.  The border area has been used by several=20<br>
armed Georgian groups to enter Abkhazia and despite numerous=20<br>
complaints to Tbilisi by the Ajarian leadership, these groups have=20<br>
also targeted Ajarian civilians in the area.<br>
