-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
AZERBAIJAN - Human Rights Watch World Report 1997<br>
<p>
The treason trials of President Heydar Aliyev's personal enemies,=20<br>
brutal treatment in detention, and continued repression of free=20<br>
speech stood in grim contrast to the Azerbaijan government's=20<br>
efforts to join international human rights institutions in 1996. =20<br>
Continued ill treatment in detention demonstrated how far=20<br>
Azerbaijan has to go in order to conform with Council of Europe=20<br>
standards and with the Convention Against Torture and Other Cruel=20<br>
Inhuman and Degrading Treatment or Punishment, which was ratified=20<br>
by the Azerbaijani parliament on May 31, 1996.<br>
The government continued to stifle political speech.  Government=20<br>
censors routinely refused to allow publication of issues of=20<br>
opposition newspapers that contained articles criticizing Aliyev. =20<br>
The Ministry of Justice repeatedly refused to register the=20<br>
Committee for Human Rights and Democracy, citing, among other=20<br>
things , the organization's failure to provide copies of the=20<br>
founder's passports, which is not among registration rules.  The=20<br>
government continued to deny the ICRC access to pre-trial=20<br>
detainees, but granted unhindered access to prisoners of war.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
2 December: An official of the Organization for Security and=20<br>
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), Tibor Lakatti, is attacked during a=20<br>
tour of the militarized zone separating Azerbaijani and Nagorno=20<br>
Karabagh forces near Agdam. Azerbaijani security officials blame=20<br>
Nagorno Karabagh units for provoking the incident due to the=20<br>
"difficulty in distinguishing peacekeepers from Nagorno Karabagh=20<br>
forces."  Such attacks have occurred in the past, for example, when=20<br>
Azerbaijani forces fired upon a OSCE delegation touring the zone=20<br>
last April.<br>
<p>
3 December: The international human rights organization Helsinki=20<br>
Watch sends a letter to Azerbaijani President Geidar Aliyev=20<br>
protesting the Azerbaijani government's handling of the criminal=20<br>
case against former Defense Minister Rakhim Gaziyev.  The former=20<br>
defense minister, charged with crimes against the state in the=20<br>
military losses to Nagorno Karabagh forces during the May 1992=20<br>
defeats in Shushi and Lachin, has been denied visits by relatives=20<br>
and has been held in isolation without access to his lawyer beyond=20<br>
an initial meeting.  Gaziyev served as the defense minister under=20<br>
the government of Azerbaijani Popular Front leader Abulfez=20<br>
Elchibey, ousted from power in a coup d'=E9tat.  Following the coming=20<br>
to power by Aliyev in June 1993, Gaziyev fled to Russia but was=20<br>
extradited to Baku in April 1996 after repeated Azerbaijani=20<br>
demands.  =20<br>
<p>
4 December: Speaking at a Baku press conference, Azerbaijani=20<br>
economic policy advisor Vakhid Akhundov announces that Azerbaijan=20<br>
plans on shipping 800,000 tons of crude oil through the Baku-<br>
Grozny-Novorossiisk pipeline.  The Azerbaijani official states that=20<br>
the state oil company SOCAR expects profits of $100 million from=20<br>
these early exports, estimated to be ready for shipment sometime=20<br>
next summer.  Azerbaijani officials also reveal that the country=20<br>
currently produces nine million tons of oil annually and is=20<br>
planning on annual exports of 1.5-2 million tons.<br>
<p>
5 December: The Azerbaijani ministry of communications announces a=20<br>
new $43 million project to upgrade the country's aging=20<br>
telecommunications sector.  The project involves the Azerbaijani=20<br>
state telecommunications firm with investment by Swedish and=20<br>
Turkish companies.  To date, the country's telecommunications=20<br>
sector enjoys significant Israeli and Turkish investment as well as=20<br>
assistance in its modernization from the European Union's TACIS aid=20<br>
program.<br>
<p>
5 December: Representatives of the country's main independent media=20<br>
issue a statement protesting the Azerbaijani government's decision=20<br>
to revoke the press credentials of the parliamentary correspondent=20<br>
for the opposition Azeri Popular Front's newspaper "Azadlyg."  The=20<br>
Aliyev government has a record of continued repression and=20<br>
censorship of the country's media.<br>
<p>
7 December: Azerbaijani foreign ministry officials announce that=20<br>
they have requested that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization=20<br>
(NATO) stage a seminar in Baku to examine issues related to=20<br>
pipeline security and environmental protection.  Azerbaijani state=20<br>
oil company SOCAR officials have added that the country's=20<br>
ministries of defense, interior and national security are seeking=20<br>
European Union assistance in the formulation of a security policy=20<br>
to effectively guarantee the safety of the pipelines planned to=20<br>
export Azerbaijan's significant energy reserves from the Caspian=20<br>
Sea.<br>
<p>
10 December: Azerbaijani security forces arrest a former special=20<br>
interior ministry forces (OPON) commander, Yelcin Amiraslanov, on=20<br>
charges of complicity in the March 1995 armed uprising seeking the=20<br>
overthrow of the Aliyev government.  To date, some nineteen coup=20<br>
participants have been arrested.  The March 1995 uprising consisted=20<br>
of members of the elite OMON branch of the interior ministry and=20<br>
was brutally defeated by regular army troops.  The elite units were=20<br>
then dissolved by President Aliyev and replaced by a restructured=20<br>
division, now known as OPON, and returned to direct control by the=20<br>
interior ministry.  This latest arrest follows a recent arrest of=20<br>
the leaders of another coup attempt directed against the Aliyev=20<br>
regime.  The so-called "Generals' coup," was led by three high=20<br>
ranking Azerbaijani military generals and involved the former aides=20<br>
to ousted Prime Minister Surat Guseynov and former Azerbaijani=20<br>
Communist Party boss and president Ayaz Mutalibov.=20<br>
<p>
12 December: The Azerbaijani parliament formally approves the=20<br>
country's 1997 budget.  The $758 million budget includes a $163=20<br>
million deficit, an increase from last year's budget deficit of=20<br>
$117 million.  The Azeri economic and finance ministries announce=20<br>
that the deficit will be financed from the signing bonuses paid to=20<br>
Azerbaijan by Western oil companies involved in energy deals in the=20<br>
country.  The government also forecasts a two percent rise in the=20<br>
Azerbaijani Gross Domestic Product (GDP).  In terms of state=20<br>
spending, education accounts for the largest amount, followed by=20<br>
military expenditures and social security and health care.<br>
<p>
14 December: In the fourth international contract between=20<br>
Azerbaijan and a consortium of Western oil companies anxious to=20<br>
develop the energy fields of the Caspian Sea, representatives sign=20<br>
a new deal to explore and develop the offshore Ashrafi and Dan=20<br>
Uluzu oil fields.  This new contract consists of a consortium of=20<br>
Western companies including the U.S. firm Amoco with a thirty=20<br>
percent share, an alliance of California-based UNOCAL with 25.5=20<br>
percent and the Saudi Arabian firm Delta with 4.5 percent, the=20<br>
Japanese oil company Itochu with twenty percent, and the=20<br>
Azerbaijani state oil concern SOCAR with the remaining twenty=20<br>
percent.  This $2 billion deal focuses on the exploitation of the=20<br>
two fields which hold an estimated 150 million tons of oil and 50=20<br>
billion cubic meters of natural gas reserves.  The project plans on=20<br>
yielding its first commercial exports by the year 2003 and a peak=20<br>
of seven million tons of crude oil annually by 2007.  This fourth=20<br>
international contract is the first one to exclude Russian=20<br>
participation and brings the total amount of foreign investment in=20<br>
the Azerbaijani energy sector to $13 billion.  This project also=20<br>
stipulates a bonus payment of $75 million from each of the=20<br>
consortium members to the Azerbaijani government.  The deal must be=20<br>
subject to parliamentary approval, however. =20<br>
<p>
16 December: Ukraine, Georgia and Azerbaijan formally mark the=20<br>
opening of a new Black Sea ferry link between Odessa and Poti.. =20<br>
The new transport link is an element of a "Euro-Asian Transport=20<br>
Corridor" plan calling for the formation of a new regional=20<br>
infrastructure and transport network connecting all countries in=20<br>
the region.  The ferry link is vital to Ukraine due to its large=20<br>
dependence on energy imports from Russia.  Georgia and Azerbaijan=20<br>
hope to utilize the transit link in the export of oil from offshore=20<br>
Azerbaijani reserves in the Caspian Sea.  Additional elements of=20<br>
the regional plan include the construction a new railway line from=20<br>
Azerbaijan through Georgia, a new $300 million project to construct=20<br>
a 40 million ton-capacity oil terminal facility at the Ukrainian=20<br>
port of Pivdenny near Odessa, and the completion of the=20<br>
modernization of the oil terminal at Batumi on the Georgian Black=20<br>
Sea coast.<br>
<p>
17 December: Meeting in Moscow with Chechen government official=20<br>
Eduard Khachukaev, Terry Adams, the chairman of the Azerbaijan=20<br>
International Oil Company (AIOC), the operational arm of the=20<br>
consortium of Azerbaijani and Western oil companies involved in the=20<br>
multi-billion dollar project to develop the offshore energy=20<br>
reserves of the Caspian Sea, discusses the issue of transporting=20<br>
oil from Azerbaijan through the pipeline transiting Chechenya.  The=20<br>
Chechen government is now seeking a share of transit tariffs and=20<br>
fees from the use of the Baku-Chechenya-Tikhoretsk-Novorossiisk=20<br>
pipeline.  The use of the this so-called "northern route" pipeline=20<br>
for transporting Azerbaijani oil is essential to the viability of=20<br>
the multi-billion oil deal and is strongly advocated by Russia. =20<br>
Recently, Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin met with the=20<br>
interim Chechen government led by Prime Minister Aslan Maskhadov to=20<br>
negotiate the secure use of the pipeline.<br>
<p>
20 December: The U.S. oil company Mobil announces a new plan to=20<br>
develop the Oguz oil and natural gas deposits in the Caspian Sea. =20<br>
The offshore reserves are estimated to contain 40 million tons of=20<br>
crude oil and 20 billion cubic meters of natural gas.  Negotiations=20<br>
on the details of the project are underway between Mobil and the=20<br>
Azerbaijani state oil company SOCAR.  Both the Russians and the=20<br>
Iranians are interested in gaining a share in this project.<br>
<p>
21 December: The operational arm of the 12-nation consortium of=20<br>
international oil companies formed to develop and exploit three=20<br>
offshore oil fields in the Caspian Sea, the Azerbaijan=20<br>
International Operating Company (AIOC), announces the completion of=20<br>
initial drilling in the offshore Azeri and Chirag fields.  The=20<br>
drilling of the fields by a Western firm marks the first direct=20<br>
Western involvement in Azerbaijan's energy sector since the=20<br>
beginning of the century.  Early production from the fields are=20<br>
expected to be ready for export sometime in early 1997 and will=20<br>
most likely be recovered from the nearby Guneshli field.<br>
