<p>
Republic of Nagorno Karabagh<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
4,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Delaware<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
150,000<br>
31 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
95% Armenian<br>
5% Assyrian, Greek,<br>
Kurdish, other<br>
<p>
<p>
Leadership:  Robert Kocharian, President (elected December 22,=20<br>
1994);  Leonard Petrossian, Prime Minister;  Arkady Gukasyan,=20<br>
Foreign Minister;  Samvel Babayan, Defense Minister.<br>
<p>
Independence:  The Republic of Nagorno Karabagh was established on=20<br>
September 2, 1991 and declared its independence on January 6, 1992.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Nagorno Karabagh is not a member of the=20<br>
CIS.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  The Parliament, which approved a temporary=20<br>
constitution in June 1992, had been working on drafting a=20<br>
constitution for the republic.  This task will now be assumed by=20<br>
the new parliament.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Parliamentary elections were held April 30, 1995 for a=20<br>
new 33-seat parliament.  Presidential elections are scheduled for=20<br>
November 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  Nagorno Karabagh's representative to=20<br>
the United States is Ardem Haroutunian.  Varoujan Krikorian is the=20<br>
representative of Nagorno Karabagh to the European Community and=20<br>
the European Parliament.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
1 December: As the international summit of the Organization for=20<br>
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) looms, Azerbaijani=20<br>
officials begin pressuring Armenian government figures to soften=20<br>
the Armenian diplomatic position regarding the Nagorno Karabagh=20<br>
conflict.  Azerbaijan promises Armenia a share in the revenue from=20<br>
the multi-billion dollar oil deals underway between Baku and=20<br>
Western oil companies.<br>
<p>
2-3 December: A summit of the member states of the Organization for=20<br>
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) convenes in Lisbon to=20<br>
review the international security group's structure, charter and=20<br>
agenda of diverse conflict mediation and preventive diplomacy.  The=20<br>
54-nation OSCE summit places the Nagorno Karabagh conflict high on=20<br>
its agenda in accordance with its long standing attempt at=20<br>
mediation over the past several years.  A preliminary mediation=20<br>
effort is launched by a working group of eleven OSCE nations led by=20<br>
Finland and Russia preceding the full summit with talks between=20<br>
Armenian and Azerbaijani officials failing to reach any significant=20<br>
accord.  The summit's handling of the Nagorno Karabagh conflict=20<br>
remains deadlocked over Azerbaijan's adamant demand for full=20<br>
recognition and endorsement of its territorial integrity despite=20<br>
the Armenian call for a guarantee of the right of self-<br>
determination for Nagorno Karabagh.  The Karabagh position regards=20<br>
its need for effective security guarantees and the articulation of=20<br>
its legal and diplomatic status as its priorities.  To date,=20<br>
Azerbaijan has conceded to offer Nagorno Karabagh a "high degree of=20<br>
autonomy" within Azerbaijan proper, contingent on the return of the=20<br>
occupied areas of Azerbaijan currently held by Karabagh forces and=20<br>
the return of the Azerbaijani refugees to those areas.  =20<br>
<p>
3 December: The Nagorno Karabagh Central Electoral Commission=20<br>
announces the final results of the November 24th election in which=20<br>
President Robert Kocharian was reelected to the presidency. =20<br>
According to the official final results, Kocharian garnered 88.9=20<br>
percent of the vote, followed by Boris Aroushanian with 7.05=20<br>
percent and Hrand Melkoumian with four percent.  Total voter=20<br>
turnout reached 70,058, or 80 percent of the eligible electorate.<br>
<p>
5 December: The Nagorno Karabagh ministry of health appeals for=20<br>
medical personnel due to the critical shortage of doctors and other=20<br>
medical staff in the republic.  According to the ministry, many=20<br>
qualified medical specialists are serving in the defense forces and=20<br>
that the shortfall of doctors is not being met by the small number=20<br>
of trained doctors coming to Nagorno Karabagh from Armenia.=20<br>
<p>
7 December: Recently reelected Nagorno Karabagh President Robert=20<br>
Kocharian announces that he is retaining Prime Minister Leonard=20<br>
Petrosian.  The prime minister is now empowered to form his new=20<br>
government within the next ten days.  The new government is=20<br>
reportedly adding new emphasis on the need for introducing more=20<br>
comprehensive systemic economic reforms and the challenges posed by=20<br>
the republic's unemployed and pensioners.=20<br>
<p>
10 December: The Nagorno Karabagh foreign ministry and parliament=20<br>
issue statements sharply critical of the recent summit of the=20<br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in=20<br>
Lisbon.  The statements threaten a review of Nagorno Karabagh's=20<br>
participation in the OSCE-brokered mediation attempt in light of=20<br>
the summit's acceptance of the Azerbaijani position regarding the=20<br>
Nagorno Karabagh conflict.  The Nagorno Karabagh position=20<br>
specifically faults the OSCE's endorsement of the principle of=20<br>
territorial integrity over the right of self-determination.  This=20<br>
conflict of principles is the fundamental diplomatic dispute=20<br>
deadlocking the mediation of the Karabagh question. =20<br>
<p>
10 December: Nagorno Karabagh President Robert Kocharian arrives in=20<br>
France leading a delegation of government officials and ministers. =20<br>
President Kocharian meets with French Senator Rene Rouquet, the=20<br>
head of the French Assembly's France-Armenia friendship group.  The=20<br>
French parliamentarian, speaking at a community gathering with the=20<br>
Karabagh delegation, commends the will of the Karabagh population=20<br>
in seeking their independence from Azerbaijan and recognizes the=20<br>
right of self-determination of Nagorno Karabagh.=20<br>
<p>
12 December: Arriving in Stepanakert on a working visit,=20<br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)=20<br>
representative Anjey Kasprchik meets with Nagorno Karabagh=20<br>
officials to review the situation in the region and to discuss=20<br>
further mediation efforts by the international security group in=20<br>
the wake of the recent summit in Lisbon.  The meetings also discuss=20<br>
the security needs of the Karabagh population.<br>
<p>
25 December: The Russian co-chairman of the OSCE Minsk group for=20<br>
Nagorno Karabagh Yuri Yukalov meets with Nagorno Karabagh officials=20<br>
in Stepanakert during a visit to the region.  The OSCE official=20<br>
also met with the Azerbaijani president and some Armenian officials=20<br>
earlier in the trip.  During the meetings, the OSCE representative=20<br>
favored continuing the mediation talks aimed at reaching a=20<br>
settlement of the Karabagh conflict.  In a statement made at the=20<br>
OSCE summit meeting in Lisbon, the current OSCE chairman, Swiss=20<br>
Foreign Minister Flavio Cotti, adhered to a strict set of=20<br>
principles to settle the Karabagh conflict.  These principles=20<br>
consisted of the recognition of Azerbaijan's territorial integrity=20<br>
by the international community, the granting of autonomy to Nagorno=20<br>
Karabagh and the guarantee of the security of the Nagorno Karabagh=20<br>
population.=20<br>
<p>
29 December: By the terms of a presidential decree, President=20<br>
Kocharian announces the new members of the Nagorno Karabagh=20<br>
cabinet.  Gerard Poghossian is appointed deputy prime minister;=20<br>
Minister of Health Care, Julia Logorian; Minister of Foreign=20<br>
Affairs, Arkady Ghoukasian; Minister of Agriculture, Valery=20<br>
Alexanian; Minister of Economy and Finance, Spartak Tevossian;=20<br>
Minister of Education and Science, Hamlet Assatrian; Minister of=20<br>
Internal Affairs, Garen Babayan; Minister of Construction, Edward=20<br>
Shahramanian; Minister of Defense, Samvel Babayan; Minister of=20<br>
Social Security, Serge Aroushanian; Minister of Justice, Yuri=20<br>
Hayrapetian; and Head of the Department for Statistics, State=20<br>
Register and Analysis, Oleg Yessayan.<br>
<p>
___________________________________________________________________<br>
<p>
<p>
The source for the Human Rights Watch World Report 1997 in the=20<br>
Caucasus profile is the:<br>
Human Rights Watch, World Report 1997, Events of 1996<br>
<p>
<p>
*The E-mail version of the TransCaucasus: A Chronology differs from=20<br>
the   official printed version in two ways:  (1) text formatting=20<br>
and (2) the   printed version includes maps of the Transcaucasus=20<br>
countries.<br>
