<!-- body="start" -->
The following is the latest version of the monthly publication, <br>
"TransCaucasus: A Chronology," covering events in Armenia, Georgia, <br>
Azerbaijan and Nagorno Karabagh for the month of October.<br>
    For more information, please contact the author, Richard Giragosian, <br>
at giragosi@essential.org<br>
<p>
Richard Giragosian<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
giragosi@essential.org<br>
<p>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
<p>
                        TransCaucasus<br>
                        A Chronology<br>
                       (E-Mail Version)*<br>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
Vol. 5                 November, 1996                         No.11<br>
<p>
<p>
The TransCaucasus: A Chronology is a chronological summary of the <br>
significant social, economic, and political events in the lower <br>
Caucasus, as reported by local and international media and selected <br>
sources in the region.  Full acknowledgement should be given to all <br>
material quoted from or based on this publication.<br>
<p>
Compiled and written by Richard Giragosian<br>
  email: giragosi@essential.org<br>
Edited and designed by Christopher Hekimian<br>
<p>
ISSN 1078-3113<br>
<p>
A Publication Of The Armenian National Committee of America<br>
**********************************************************<br>
<p>
Republic of <br>
Armenia<br>
<p>
<p>
Total area:<br>
29,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than Maryland<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan (east) 566 km<br>
Nakhichevan (south) 221 km<br>
Georgia 164 km<br>
Iran 35 km<br>
Turkey 268 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
3.6 million<br>
68% urban<br>
110.5 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
93.3% Armenian<br>
1.5% Russian<br>
1.7% Kurdish<br>
3.5% Assyrian, Greek, other<br>
<p>
<p>
Leadership:  Levon Ter Petrosian, President; Hrant Bagratian, Prime <br>
Minister; Vahan Papazian, Foreign Minister. <br>
<p>
Independence:  Armenia re-established its independence on September <br>
23, 1991, after more than 70 years of Soviet rule.  The first <br>
Armenian Republic was established on May 28, 1918.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Armenia joined the CIS in March 1992 and <br>
CIS Defense Treaty in May 1992.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A constitution was adopted by national referendum on <br>
July 5, 1995.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Elections were held for Parliament July 5, 1995 and for <br>
President September 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to <br>
Armenia is Ambassador Peter Tomsen. The Armenian representative to <br>
the United States is Ambassador Rouben Shugarian.  The Armenian <br>
representative to the United Nations is Ambassador Alexander <br>
Arzoumanian.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
1 October: A group of wives and mothers of arrested opposition <br>
leaders and deputies issue an appeal to international organizations <br>
and the media calling for an independent review of last month's <br>
presidential election, the restoration of civil liberties, and the <br>
release of all those arrested in the government crackdown on the <br>
opposition following the elections.  Western diplomats estimate <br>
that at least 250 opposition leaders and supporters have been <br>
arrested since September 25th.  The U.S. Department of State issues <br>
a statement expressing concern over the arrests and urges all <br>
parties to adhere to the democratic rule of law.  The tense <br>
political situation stems from the official declaration that Levon <br>
Ter Petrosian won reelection with 51.6 percent of the vote in the <br>
first round amid widespread allegations of fraud and voting <br>
irregularities.  The Armenian Communist Party withdraws its 8 <br>
deputies from parliament in protest over the government's actions, <br>
effectively leaving the parliament without an opposition.<br>
<p>
1 October: In a Russian television interview, opposition <br>
presidential candidate Vazgen Manukian announces that he favors a <br>
peaceful political solution to the current political crisis in <br>
Armenia.  Manukian, currently in hiding to evade arrest, accuses <br>
the Ter Petrosian government of rigging the election's results and <br>
asserts that actual vote tabulations show Manukian with over 50 <br>
percent.  The chairman of the state Central Election Commission <br>
Khachatour Bezirjian refutes charges of voting irregularities and <br>
accuses the opposition of manipulating the situation.  The <br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), <br>
however, reports that there are 22,000 ballots missing, which <br>
roughly equals the number of votes Ter Petrosian claimed to avoid a <br>
run-off.<br>
<p>
4 October: Opposition parliamentarian Aramazd Zakarian of the <br>
National Self-Determination Union files a lawsuit in the U.S. <br>
Federal District Court for the Southern District of New York <br>
against Armenian presidential advisor and U.S. citizen Jirair <br>
Libaridian for his part in the government's campaign of arrest and <br>
prosecution of the opposition.   The suit charges Libaridian with <br>
complicity in the physical assault against Zakarian under the Alien <br>
Tort Claims Act, a statute allowing for judicial redress for <br>
victims of international human rights abuses.<br>
<p>
8 October: At a press conference in Washington, the International <br>
Foundation for Election Systems (IFES) releases its report <br>
regarding the Armenian presidential election.  The report terms the <br>
election as "flawed" and calls for "further investigations and <br>
international scrutiny" of the results.  IFES cites some <br>
advancements in the electoral process, greater transparency and <br>
increases in voter education.  However, the report adds that "the <br>
election process broke down as the vote count started, with <br>
multiple reports of proxies being threatened, documents being <br>
falsified, and in one case witnessed by the political officer of <br>
the U.S. Embassy, the ballots of an entire precinct being stolen."  <br>
According to the official statement of the state Central Election <br>
Commission, Ter Petrosian received over 50% of the vote, thus <br>
avoiding a run-off election round, by some 21,941 votes.  The IFES <br>
report stresses that 22,013 ballots were missing.  The IFES report <br>
follows critical statements from Amnesty International, Human <br>
Rights Watch, the Moscow-based Memorial Human Rights Center and a <br>
group of Russian parliamentarians.<br>
<p>
10 October: President Ter Petrosian announces the lifting of his <br>
earlier decree banning all public gatherings, rallies and <br>
demonstrations and suspending other civil liberties.  The decree <br>
was issued on September 26th in response to the disruption and <br>
shootings at a mass opposition rally at the parliament.<br>
<p>
11 October: An official of the Armenian Scientific-Industrial Civil <br>
Union (SICU), Rafael Ghazarian, holds a press conference at the <br>
Russian State Duma to report on the recent Armenian presidential <br>
election.  According to Ghazarian, the election was seriously <br>
marred by the government's campaign of fraud and voting <br>
irregularities, and that incumbent President Levon Ter Petrosian <br>
had really garnered a mere 30 percent of the vote while the <br>
opposition candidate Vazgen Manukian actually had 60 percent.  The <br>
beatings and physical assaults of opposition deputies and activists <br>
by the state security forces is also raised during the press <br>
conference.<br>
<p>
11 October: According to statistics released by the International <br>
Monetary Fund (IMF), Armenia's recent economic recovery is slowing.  <br>
Growth in the country's gross domestic product (GDP) slowed during <br>
the first half of the year, while the trade deficit grew due to <br>
declining exports.  There is improvement in inflation, however, <br>
with the level of consumer prices rising by only three percent from <br>
January to August.  Wages in the country are rising in real dollar <br>
terms, but they remain low when compared to other newly independent <br>
countries.  The IMF cites unemployment as steadily holding at 9 <br>
percent, but notes that the true unemployment figure is at least <br>
double the official rate.<br>
<p>
11 October: As the government withdraws the last security forces <br>
and armored vehicles from their positions within the capital, <br>
former National Security Minister David Shahnazarian calls on the <br>
Ter Petrosian government to dismiss the prime minister and the <br>
ministers of interior and defense for their part in the <br>
confrontation with demonstrators following last month's <br>
presidential election.  The political situation remains tense, <br>
however, as there are several indictments of opposition leaders <br>
pending and the opposition parties and the press are still not <br>
allowed to operate freely.  With local and municipal elections <br>
scheduled for November 11th, many expect renewed confrontation <br>
between the opposition and the Ter Petrosian government.<br>
 <br>
11-12 October: A three-member delegation of officials from the <br>
Council of Europe arrive in Yerevan on a  three day fact-finding <br>
mission to investigate the political situation in the country <br>
following the marred presidential elections.  The delegation meets <br>
with various government officials and also conducts interviews with <br>
opposition presidential candidates Sergei Badalian and Vazgen <br>
Manukian and imprisoned opposition deputies and leaders Rouben <br>
Hakobian, David Vardanian, Kim Balayan and the recently released <br>
Shavarsh Kocharian.  The European delegation states that they <br>
believe that the arrest of the deputies is a retreat from democracy <br>
and expresses its grave concern with reports of beatings and <br>
violations of rights of the detainees by the Armenian authorities.  <br>
A Council of Europe official participating in the delegation, <br>
Hanneka Gelderblom, categorizes the election as being undemocratic.  <br>
The delegation's final report is to be released sometime next <br>
month.  Another delegation from the European Union was to have held <br>
meetings with Armenian officials concerning trade issues but <br>
canceled the visit following the election turmoil.<br>
<p>
12-13 October: The last of the imprisoned opposition <br>
parliamentarians, Rouben Hakobian of the Armenian Revolutionary <br>
Federation (ARF) and David Vardanian of the National Democratic <br>
Union (NDU), are freed from detention but their travel is <br>
restricted to Yerevan and they are still being charged with various <br>
crimes.  The tense political situation is further exacerbated by <br>
the announcement that the Armenian Constitutional Court is <br>
rejecting the appeal of the election lodged by Manukian on the <br>
grounds that his appeal was written incorrectly.  ARF member and <br>
former parliamentarian, Kim Balayan, remains imprisoned and without <br>
access to council.<br>
<p>
14 October: A three-day international conference, sponsored by the <br>
World Bank, the French Embassy, and the United Nations Development <br>
Program (UNDP), convenes in Yerevan to discuss the ecological <br>
situation of Lake Sevan.  The conference examines the declining <br>
water table and the worsening ecological conditions of the lake, <br>
with a recovery period expected to last as much as 20-30 years to <br>
restore Lake Sevan to its natural water level.<br>
<p>
18 October: Municipal authorities of the capital Yerevan reverses <br>
its earlier ruling and withdraws its permission for an opposition <br>
rally citing errors in the application.  The opposition announces <br>
that it will resubmit its application and will stage a rally the <br>
next week.  The opposition's move follows the recent lifting of the <br>
government's ban on all public gatherings and rallies.<br>
<p>
23 October: By order of governmental decree, Prime Minister Hrant <br>
Bagratian announces the dismissals of the deputy Mayor of Yerevan, <br>
Gevork Arzoumanian, first deputy Minister for Education Ashot <br>
Bleyan, and the Civil Aviation Departmental Chief, Shahen <br>
Petrossian.  The dismissals are reported to be part of the <br>
government's attempted crackdown on corruption.<br>
<p>
25 October: Over 100,000 demonstrators converge on central Yerevan <br>
in an opposition rally in support of the five-party opposition <br>
coalition's petition to the Constitutional Court demanding new <br>
presidential elections.  The pro-government Constitutional Court, <br>
consisting of presidential appointees, has already rejected one <br>
such petition by the opposition on questionable grounds and is <br>
widely expected to refuse this new petition.  Additional opposition <br>
rallies are planned for the beginning of November.  The five <br>
opposition parties also announce their boycott of local and <br>
municipal elections slated for November 11th.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Republic of Georgia<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
69,700 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than S. Carolina<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia 164 km<br>
Azerbaijan 322 km<br>
Russia 723 km<br>
Turkey 252 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
<p>
5.57 million<br>
56% urban<br>
78 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
69% Georgian<br>
9% Armenian<br>
6% Russian<br>
6% Ajarian<br>
5% Azerbaijani<br>
3% Ossetian<br>
2% Abkhazian<br>
<p>
Georgia includes the autonomous republics of Abkhazia and Ajaria<br>
and the South Ossetian Autonomous Region.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Leadership:  Eduard Shevardnadze, President; Irakli Menagrashvili, <br>
Foreign Minister, Nickol Lekishvili, Secretary of State, Zurab <br>
Zhvania, Parliamentary Chairman.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Georgia established its independence on April 9, <br>
1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  The Georgian government joined the CIS on <br>
October 23, 1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was adopted in August, 1995, <br>
which reinstates a presidential form of government and provides for <br>
a strong executive branch and a unicameral 235-seat parliament.  A <br>
constitutional court is also created.  The constitution, however, <br>
does not address the status of Abkhazia, Ossetia or Ajaria.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Presidential and parliamentary elections were last held <br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to <br>
Georgia is Ambassador Kent Brown. The Georgian representative to <br>
the United States, as well as Canada and Mexico, is Ambassador Tedo <br>
Japaridze.  The Georgian representative to the United Nations is <br>
Ambassador Peter Chkiedze.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
8 October: Deputy chairman of the International Affairs Committee <br>
of the Russian State Duma Aleksey Podberezkin meets with President <br>
Eduard Shevardnadze to discuss the Abkhazian conflict and to review <br>
developments in bilateral relations between Georgia and Russia.  <br>
The meeting is the latest in the new strategic partnership between <br>
the two countries and is an attempt to renew the deadlocked <br>
negotiations over the Abkhazian conflict and to soften <br>
disagreements on the issue of Russian military basing rights in <br>
Georgia.<br>
<p>
8 October: A Tbilisi district court sentences former Defense <br>
Minister Tengiz Kitovani and two of his associates on charges <br>
related to his military attempt at forcibly seizing control over <br>
Abkhazia in January 1995. Following an eleven month investigation <br>
and a nine month trial, Kitovani is sentenced to serve an eight <br>
year prison term.  Kitovani's two associates, former deputy Prime <br>
Minister Irakli Surguladze and Valerii Fisyun, receive sentences of <br>
21 months and six years respectfully.  Surguladze is freed because <br>
of time served since his January 1995 arrest.<br>
<p>
10 October: The United Nations Special Envoy for the Abkhazian <br>
conflict, Eduard Brunner, meets with Abkhazian President Vladislav <br>
Ardzinba in Sukhumi.  The talks represent a renewed mediation <br>
attempt by the United Nations and focus on reaching a political <br>
settlement to the Abkhazian conflict.  The United Nations envoy <br>
also urges a new attempt at honoring the earlier agreement <br>
providing for the safe return of the several hundred thousand <br>
Georgian refugees displaced from their homes in Abkhazia.  The <br>
situation has worsened lately due to the decision by the Abkhazian <br>
parliament to hold elections on November 23rd.  The Georgian <br>
government has strongly renounced the decision and has stated that <br>
the move threatens further negotiations.<br>
<p>
10 October: The Russian Foreign Ministry condemns the October 2 <br>
resolution of the Georgian parliament calling for the revision of <br>
Georgian-Russian relations.  The Russians see the resolution as <br>
questioning their role in the Abkhazian conflict, and putting into <br>
doubt their role as primary military peace-keeper in the region.  <br>
The Georgian decision also calls for a renegotiation of the current <br>
military basing agreement between Moscow and Tbilisi.  <br>
<p>
10 October: The president of the Chevron oil company, Richard <br>
Matzke, meets with Shevardnadze and Ajarian parliamentarian <br>
chairman Aslan Abashidze to discuss the use of the Batumi port <br>
facilities on the Black Sea for the transport of oil from <br>
Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan.  The issue of transporting the oil from <br>
the massive energy deals in Azerbaijan and Central Asia is key to <br>
the projects' long-term viability.<br>
<p>
11 October: A representative of the United Nations High Commission <br>
for Refugees (UNHCR) announces that an opening ceremony for the <br>
reconstructed bridge spanning the southern Georgian Banoshou river <br>
will be held on November fifth.  The restoration of the railway and <br>
transport links between Georgia and Armenia is crucial to the <br>
Armenian economy and will restore normal levels of trade with <br>
Russia.  These transport routes have been sabotaged by sporadic <br>
bombings for several years in the Azeri-populated Marneuli <br>
district.<br>
<p>
11 October: Abkhazian parliamentary chairman Vladislav Ardzinba <br>
announces his rejection of the Georgian proposal for negotiations <br>
on the status of Abkhazia.  Ardzinba also welcomes the statement of <br>
the UN Special Envoy to Abkhazia, Eduard Brunner, endorsing <br>
Abkhazia's plan to hold parliamentary elections on November 23rd.<br>
<p>
14 October: The European Union (EU) announces that it is awarding a <br>
$4 million aid package for the three Caucasus states.  Most of the <br>
EU assistance is to go toward relief projects in Georgia to be <br>
coordinated through the offices of the Red Cross, Oxfam, Caritas <br>
and Medicins Sans Frontiers.  Georgia is slated to receive some <br>
$2.5 million in clothing, medicine and other humanitarian supplies, <br>
with Armenia being allocated slightly more than $1 million and <br>
$250,000 in aid for Azerbaijan.<br>
<p>
22 October: The United Nations Security Council adopts a resolution <br>
calling on Abkhazia to cancel its parliamentary elections scheduled <br>
for next month.  The UN move seeks to restore an atmosphere <br>
conducive for further negotiations between Georgian and Abkhazian <br>
representatives and see the election as a complication since its <br>
precedes any firm negotiations for a political solution to the <br>
Abkhazian conflict. <br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Republic of Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
81,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Maine<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia (West) 566 km<br>
Armenia (southwest) 221 km<br>
Georgia 332 km<br>
Iran (south) 432 km<br>
Iran (southwest) 179 km<br>
Russia 284 km<br>
Turkey 9 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
7.3 million<br>
54% urban<br>
89 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
71% Azerbaijani<br>
11% Talish<br>
6% Russian<br>
4% Lezgi <br>
3% Daghestani<br>
3% Kurdish<br>
2% Avar<br>
The autonomous republic of Nakhichevan (pop. 350,000; 5,500 sq. <br>
km)was placed under Azerbaijani administration in 1921.	<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Geidar Aliyev, President; Artur Rasizade, Prime <br>
Minister; Hasan Hasanov, Foreign Minister; Shamshaddin Khanbabayev, <br>
Premier of Nakhichevan.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Azerbaijan established its independence on August <br>
30, 1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Azerbaijan joined the CIS on September 24, <br>
1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was passed by referendum in <br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Elections: Parliamentary elections for a new 125-seat legislature <br>
were held November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to <br>
Azerbaijan is Ambassador Richard Kauzlarich.  The Azerbaijani <br>
representative to the United States is Ambassador Hafiz Pashayev.  <br>
The Azerbaijani representative to the United Nations is Yashar <br>
Aliyev.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
1 October: A news conference is convened in a Baku mosque by the <br>
Committee for the Rights of Arrested Islamic Activists to demand <br>
the release of nine Party of Islam activists detained by <br>
Azerbaijani security officials since last spring.  The Islamic <br>
activists are reportedly in ill health and suffering from poor <br>
prison conditions.  Azerbaijani security officials have charged the <br>
Islamic detainees with committing anti-state actions, espionage and <br>
other activities in support of the Iranian regime.  The Islamic <br>
group is not formally recognized by the Aliyev government and their <br>
detention remains a problem in the development of Iranian-<br>
Azerbaijani relations.<br>
<p>
4 October: The recently convened Azerbaijani parliament formally <br>
ratifies an agreement with a consortium of international oil <br>
companies to explore and develop the Shah-Deniz oil and natural gas <br>
deposits along the Caspian Sea continental shelf.  This $4 billion <br>
project, second in scope only to the $7.5 billion consortium deal <br>
involving the Chirag-Azeri-Guneshli fields, calls for the <br>
development of an estimated 400-500 billion cubic meters of natural <br>
gas, 200 million metric tons of gas condensate and 100-190 million <br>
metric tons of oil at a depth of 60 to 550 meters.  The development <br>
phase of the deal is planned to last thirty-five years, with <br>
initial production ready by the year 2002.  The Shah-Deniz field is <br>
one of twenty-four currently being surveyed and readied for <br>
negotiation and would enable Azerbaijan to meet its domestic <br>
natural gas requirements with enough of a surplus to make the <br>
country into a fairly significant exporter.  The consortium <br>
comprises 25.5 percent shares for British Petroleum and Norway's <br>
Statoil, the French Elf Aquitaine firm, Russia's Lukoil, the <br>
Iranian Sate Oil Company and Azerbaijan's SOCAR state oil company <br>
with a 10 percent share each, and the Turkish State Oil Company <br>
with a nine percent stake.  The U.S. has pressured U.S. oil <br>
companies to withdraw from the project following the inclusion of <br>
the Iranians.<br>
<p>
5 October: Russian government officials announce the reopening of <br>
cross-border rail transit along the Russian-Azerbaijani borders.  <br>
The railway line and most major transport links and roads through <br>
the Daghestan region, which is situated on either side of the <br>
Russian-Azerbaijani border, have been closed since December 1994, <br>
resulting in a sharp decline in trade and commerce.<br>
<p>
9 October: The president of the Azerbaijani International Operating <br>
Company, Terry Adams, meets with Azerbaijani President Geidar <br>
Aliyev to discuss the latest developments in the multi-billion <br>
dollar oil exploration project.  Specifically, the meeting focuses <br>
on the continued problem of securing a definitive and adequate <br>
route through which to export the oil.  A pipeline from Baku to the <br>
Georgian port of Supsa along the Black Sea, is not expected to <br>
become fully operational until late 1998.  Also, another pipeline <br>
route to the Russian port of Novorossiisk is tentatively planned to <br>
be operational by August 1997 for the transport of oil from the <br>
Chirag field.  <br>
<p>
9 October: Representatives of a committee organizing an <br>
international conference on the status and treatment of the Lezgin <br>
people of northern Azerbaijan, issue a call for immediate dialogue <br>
with the Russian and Azerbaijani governments to prevent "acts of <br>
violence."  The Lezgin population is divided among Azerbaijan and <br>
the Russian Federation's Daghestan region.  The call also demands <br>
an easing of travel restrictions imposed on the Lezgins in the <br>
border area and appeals for an end to the Azerbaijani government's <br>
policy of discrimination against the Lezgin minority.  The Congress <br>
of Lezgin People is scheduled to be held in Moscow in January 1997.  <br>
 <br>
11 October: British Prime Minister John Major appeals to Azerbaijan <br>
to form a new international consortium to develop offshore oil <br>
fields in the Caspian Sea.  According to the chairman of the <br>
Azerbaijani state oil company SOCAR, Natik Aliyev, the British <br>
proposal includes the U.S. company Mobil, France's Total Oil and <br>
the British Ramco Energy firm.  A similar proposal for a new <br>
consortium has also been submitted to Baku by French Foreign <br>
Minister Herve de Charette.  The French plan calls for the <br>
formation of a new consortium to explore and develop the offshore <br>
Lenkorandeniz and Astaradeniz reserves.  The French state oil <br>
company Elf Aquitaine, which is awaiting approval from Aliyev to <br>
develop two other oil fields, is bidding for a 75 percent share in <br>
this proposal<br>
<p>
11 October: According to the new agreement between the Azerbaijani <br>
state oil company SOCAR and Chevron's division dealing with oil <br>
projects in Kazakhstan, Tengizchevroil, an initial shipment of oil <br>
from the Kazakh Tengiz field arrives at Baku's Dyubendi port <br>
facility along the Caspian Sea.  The agreement calls for the <br>
shipment of some 20,000 metric tons of oil from Kazakhstan across <br>
the Caspian to Baku port facilities from where SOCAR will transport <br>
the oil by rail to the Georgian port of Batumi. <br>
<p>
15 October: Following an earlier proposal by the British <br>
government, Azerbaijani officials announce the formation of a new <br>
consortium of Western oil companies and the Azerbaijani state oil <br>
company to explore and develop additional offshore oil reserves in <br>
the southern Caspian Sea.  The new consortium includes the British <br>
firm Ramco, Mobil and Total in an unspecified sharing agreement.<br>
<p>
15 October: The Azerbaijani parliament elects Murtuz Aleskerov as <br>
its chairman, replacing the ousted Rasul Guliev.  Guliev was forced <br>
from the post following his call for a speeding up of economic <br>
reform and privatization, a position which clashed with other <br>
Aliyev advisors.  The new parliamentary chairman, a position second <br>
only to President Aliyev, was a prominent member of the Azerbaijani <br>
Popular Front, the banned party of former President Abulfez <br>
Elchibey.  Aleskerov left the Popular Front in 1992 and began <br>
assisting the efforts of current President Geidar Aliyev to come to <br>
power from his base in Nakhichevan.  The new chairman is also one <br>
of the founders and deputy chairman of the pro-Aliyev Yenni (New) <br>
Azerbaijani party.<br>
<p>
16 October: President Aliyev welcomes the participants of a two-day <br>
conference on refugees and displaced people organized by the <br>
Azerbaijani State Commission for Technical and Humanitarian Aid.  <br>
The conference consists of delegates from various Islamic <br>
countries, including Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Turkey.  <br>
<p>
19 October: Top officials of the Russian state oil company Lukoil <br>
meet with Azerbaijani officials to review plans to develop the <br>
offshore Inam oil reserve in the Caspian Sea.  Lukoil is seeking a <br>
fifty percent share in the project which is estimated to hold 120-<br>
150 million metric tons of oil.  President Aliyev is also said to <br>
be discussing additional cooperative ventures with LUKoil including <br>
the formation of a joint insurance company and a Russian-<br>
Azerbaijani project to modernize floating oil rigs in the Caspian. <br>
<p>
22 October: Azerbaijani government officials reach an agreement <br>
with visiting delegations from the World Bank and United Nations <br>
Development Program (UNDP) providing for financial assistance for <br>
the reconstruction of the country's infrastructure.  The estimated <br>
cost of reconstruction stands at a daunting $22 billion. The World <br>
Bank has pledged some $50 million in aid and other donor nations <br>
have committed to $7.6 million in assistance to be directed toward <br>
projects underway by the United Nations High Commission for <br>
Refugees (UNHCR). <br>
<p>
25 October: During the course of a summit in Moscow of the Black <br>
Sea Economic Cooperation group, Azerbaijani President Aliyev meets <br>
with his Armenian and Turkish counterparts, Presidents Ter <br>
Petrosian and Suleyman Demirel.  The three heads of state discuss <br>
several regional issues, including the developing bilateral <br>
relations between Iran and Armenia and the issue of the closure of <br>
the Armenian-Turkish border.  Under Azerbaijani pressure, the <br>
Turkish president promises to maintain the border's closure until <br>
the full return of all Azerbaijani territory held by Nagorno <br>
Karabagh forces. An additional private meeting is held between the <br>
Armenian and Azerbaijani presidents, with no details on their <br>
discussions available. <br>
<p>
26 October: The head of the Russian Foreign Ministry's working <br>
group on the Caspian Sea, Ambassador Feliks Kovalev, announces that <br>
Russia has accepted the delineation of the national sovereign <br>
sectors and economic zones in a forty mile offshore area of the <br>
Caspian Sea.  The Russian position advocates the creation of a <br>
common littoral zone to be shared by all countries bordering the <br>
Sea beyond the forty mile area.  Azerbaijani Foreign Minister Hasan <br>
Hasanov welcomes the new Russian position, which reverses Moscow's <br>
prior refusal to allow any sector division, but notes that the <br>
Russian proposal for a common jurisdictional zone beyond the forty <br>
mile area would significantly complicate the international oil <br>
deals that Azerbaijan is pursuing.  The Kazakhstan government <br>
reacts by supporting Baku's stance, in line with the recent <br>
bilateral agreement between the two countries establishing a <br>
regulatory framework of military navigation in the Caspian.  This <br>
agreement conspicuously excludes mention of both Iran and Russia <br>
and, therefore, challenges the concept of shared rights and <br>
obligations of all littoral states.<br>
<p>
--------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Republic of Nagorno Karabagh<br>
<p>
<p>
Total area:<br>
4,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Delaware<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
150,000<br>
31 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
95% Armenian<br>
5% Assyrian, Greek,<br>
Kurdish, other<br>
<p>
<p>
Leadership:  Robert Kocharian, President (elected December 22, <br>
1994);  Leonard Petrossian, Prime Minister;  Arkady Gukasyan, <br>
Foreign Minister;  Samvel Babayan, Defense Minister.<br>
<p>
Independence:  The Republic of Nagorno Karabagh was established on <br>
September 2, 1991 and declared its independence on January 6, 1992.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Nagorno Karabagh is not a member of the <br>
CIS.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  The Parliament, which approved a temporary <br>
constitution in June 1992, had been working on drafting a <br>
constitution for the republic.  This task will now be assumed by <br>
the new parliament.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Parliamentary elections were held April 30, 1995 for a <br>
new 33-seat parliament.  Presidential elections are scheduled for <br>
November 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  Nagorno Karabagh's representative to <br>
the United States is Ardem Haroutunian.  Varoujan Krikorian is the <br>
representative of Nagorno Karabagh to the European Community and <br>
the European Parliament.<br>
------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
3 October: Azerbaijani President Geidar Aliyev criticizes the <br>
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) and its <br>
special working group on the Karabagh conflict, the Minsk Group, <br>
for failing to accomplish anything beyond declarations since its <br>
1994 OSCE Budapest summit.  The Azerbaijani president, during <br>
meetings with OSCE representatives, specifically condemns the OSCE <br>
for its "failure to explain to Armenia that the Armenian community <br>
of Karabagh will not receive the status of an independent state."  <br>
<p>
4 October: Following the heated meetings with the Azerbaijani <br>
president in Baku, the delegation of Organization for Security and <br>
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) officials arrive in Stepanakert to <br>
meet with Nagorno Karabagh government representatives.  The talks <br>
focus on a rapid political settlement prior to the OSCE's summit to <br>
be held in Lisbon in December.  The co-chairmen of the OSCE's Minsk <br>
Group, Heikki Talvitie and Valentin Lozinski, also express <br>
displeasure with the plan to hold presidential elections in <br>
Karabagh and state that the election only provokes a harsh <br>
Azerbaijani reaction which seriously impedes their organization's <br>
mediation effort. <br>
<p>
8 October: Iranian deputy Foreign Minister Mahmoud Vayezi announces <br>
that his country will be launching a new diplomatic initiative <br>
seeking to mediate the Nagorno Karabagh conflict.  The Iranian <br>
official makes the announcement following a meeting in Moscow with <br>
Russian deputy Foreign Minister Boris Pastoukhov.<br>
<p>
15 October: The Nagorno Karabagh government prepares for the <br>
upcoming presidential election slated for November 24th.  According <br>
to the recently passed legal framework on elections, the new <br>
president will serve a term of five years and will formally replace <br>
the temporary term of current President Robert Kocharian.  <br>
Candidates are required to have lived in Nagorno Karabagh for the <br>
last ten years and must collect 1500 signed petitions supporting <br>
their candidacy by October 25th.  Official candidates will be <br>
registered from October 30th to November 4th, with the formal <br>
election campaign starting on November 5th and lasting until <br>
November 23rd.  A new electoral district is to be formed for the <br>
Nagorno Karabagh citizens currently residing in Armenia. Candidates <br>
for the presidential election proposed to date include current <br>
President Robert Kocharian, parliamentarian and former deputy <br>
parliamentary speaker Boris Arushanian, and the leader of the <br>
organizational committee of the Nagorno Karabagh Communist Party, <br>
Hrant Melkoumian. <br>
<p>
22 October: With presidential elections only a little more than a <br>
month away, Nagorno Karabagh officials reveal that a new candidate <br>
has been formally registered for the race.  The new candidate is <br>
state administrator Albert Gazarian, bringing the total field to <br>
four candidates.  For the remainder of the month, the Karabagh <br>
Central Electoral Commission will verify the candidates' petitions <br>
and complete the registration process before launching the full <br>
campaign.<br>
<p>
23 October: The coordinator of the "Helsinki Initiative-92" <br>
Committee on Nagorno Karabagh, Karen Ohanjanian, announces that he <br>
can no longer to continue to cooperate with his Azerbaijani <br>
counterpart, Arzu Abdullayeva, the coordinator of the Azerbaijani <br>
Helsinki Citizen Assembly.  The Karabagh civic activist criticizes <br>
the Azerbaijani side for their position advocating military <br>
attempts to settle the Nagorno Karabagh conflict, stressing that <br>
such a position contradicts the peaceful aims of the citizen groups <br>
seeking a dialogue between all sides to the conflict. The Nagorno <br>
Karabagh civic group also announces a new international conference <br>
of non-governmental organizations (NGOs) to examine "preventive <br>
diplomacy in conflict settlement" to be held in Stepanakert from <br>
November 1-4.  Participation in the conference includes NGO <br>
delegations and representatives from the United States, <br>
Switzerland, Great Britain, Bulgaria, the Netherlands, Russia, <br>
Ukraine, Armenia and Georgia. <br>
<p>
24 October: The Azerbaijani government issues a statement <br>
condemning the scheduled presidential elections in Nagorno Karabagh <br>
as "illegal and invalid,"  The statement continues that any <br>
elections for legitimate bodies of power in the region can only <br>
occur after the return of all Azerbaijani refugees, the return of <br>
Azerbaijani territory currently held by Karabagh forces, and the <br>
restoration of the Soviet-era ethnic composition of the republic.<br>
<p>
26 October: The Russian Foreign Ministry issues a statement <br>
regarding the presidential elections in Nagorno Karabagh slated for <br>
late next month.  The Russian statement criticizes the election for <br>
running counter to the mediation effort underway seeking a <br>
political solution to the Karabagh conflict. <br>
<p>
28 October: Nagorno Karabagh President Robert Kocharian announces <br>
that presidential elections will proceed as scheduled despite <br>
criticism from Russian and Azerbaijani government spokesmen.  The <br>
elections are also the subject of a statement by the U.S. <br>
Department of State, which expressed concern over the election as <br>
possibly "complicating the outcome of the Organization for Security <br>
and Cooperation in Europe's Minsk Group peace process." <br>
<p>
28 October: A new round of OSCE mediation talks on the Karabagh <br>
conflict convenes in Moscow.  Expected to last three days, the <br>
talks focus on the issues related to the demilitarization of the <br>
Armenian-Azerbaijani border area.  This round of talks is somewhat <br>
hindered by the strong Azerbaijani opposition to the scheduled <br>
presidential elections in Nagorno Karabagh, stating that the <br>
November 24th election is illegal as it precedes the holding of <br>
negotiations over the political status of Nagorno Karabagh.<br>
<p>
29 October: In an Armenian television interview, President <br>
Kocharian reacts to the criticism of the Nagorno Karabagh <br>
presidential election by the Organization for Security and <br>
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) by restating his government's firm <br>
stand on the Karabagh conflict "from which there can be no retreat <br>
and no fallback positions."  Kocharian states that Nagorno Karabagh <br>
will "never" be part of Azerbaijan or become subordinate to Baku.  <br>
The response follows a critical OSCE interpretation of the election <br>
as hampering the mediation efforts underway.  The election is <br>
scheduled for November 24th and President Kocharian is expected to <br>
win a second term easily.<br>
<p>
29 October: President Kocharian meets with Sergei Badalian, the <br>
First Secretary of the Armenian Communist Party, during a visit to <br>
Yerevan.  The meeting centers on the current OSCE peace initiative <br>
and reviews the upcoming election in Nagorno Karabagh.  President <br>
Kocharian also meets with his election rival, Karabagh Communist <br>
Party figure Hrant Melkoumian.<br>
<p>
*****************************************************************<br>
<p>
*The E-mail version of the TransCaucasus: A Chronology differs from <br>
the   official printed version in two ways:  (1) text formatting <br>
and (2) the   printed version includes maps of the Transcaucasus <br>
countries.<br>
