<!-- body="start" -->
The following is the latest issue of the monthly publication<br>
"TransCaucasus: A Chronology," providing coverage of significant events<br>
in Armenia, Georgia, Azerbaijan and Nagorno Karabagh. This issue includes<br>
<p>
coverage of the events of September 1996. For more information, or to be<br>
included in the free email distribution, please contact the author,<br>
Richard Giragosian, via email, at: giragosi@essential.org<br>
<p>
Richard Giragosian<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
Internet: giragosi@essential.org<br>
Tel: 202-546-4996 ext.301 Fax: 202-547-7392<br>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
<p>
                        TransCaucasus<br>
                        A Chronology<br>
                       (E-Mail Version)*<br>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
Vol. 5                  October, 1996                         No.10<br>
<p>
<p>
The TransCaucasus: A Chronology is a chronological summary of the<br>
significant social, economic, and political events in the lower<br>
Caucasus, as reported by local and international media and selected<br>
sources in the region.  Full acknowledgement should be given to all<br>
material quoted from or based on this publication.<br>
<p>
Compiled and written by Richard Giragosian<br>
Edited and designed by Christopher Hekimian<br>
<p>
ISSN 1078-3113<br>
<p>
A Publication Of The Armenian National Committee of America<br>
**********************************************************<br>
<p>
Republic of<br>
Armenia<br>
<p>
<p>
Total area:<br>
29,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than Maryland<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan (east) 566 km<br>
Nakhichevan (south) 221 km<br>
Georgia 164 km<br>
Iran 35 km<br>
Turkey 268 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
3.6 million<br>
68% urban<br>
110.5 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
93.3% Armenian<br>
1.5% Russian<br>
1.7% Kurdish<br>
3.5% Assyrian, Greek, other<br>
<p>
<p>
Leadership:  Levon Ter Petrosian, President (elected October 16,<br>
1991 and re-elected to a second term on September 22, 1996); Hrant<br>
Bagratian, Prime Minister; Vahan Papazian, Foreign Minister, Babken<br>
Ararkstian, parliamentary chairman.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Armenia re-established its independence on September<br>
23, 1991, after more than 70 years of Soviet rule.  The first<br>
Armenian Republic was established on May 28, 1918.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Armenia joined the CIS in March 1992 and<br>
CIS Defense Treaty in May 1992.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A constitution was adopted by national referendum<br>
during elections in July.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Parliamentary elections were held on July 5, 1995. <br>
Presidential elections were held on September 22, 1996.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to<br>
Armenia is Ambassador Peter Tomsen. The Armenian representative to<br>
the United States is Ambassador Rouben Shugarian.  The Armenian<br>
representative to the United Nations is Ambassador Alexander<br>
Arzoumanian.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
2 September: Following a meeting with Armenian defense ministry<br>
officials, Bulgarian Defense Minister Dimitri Pavlov signs a<br>
bilateral agreement on military cooperation between Armenia and<br>
Bulgaria.  The bilateral agreement calls for the exchange of<br>
military equipment and hardware, the joint training of military<br>
personnel and cooperative ventures in military-related<br>
technological research and production.<br>
<p>
2 September: Armenian President Levon Ter Petrosian releases his<br>
election platform for the upcoming presidential election.  The<br>
platform's priorities include the development and strengthening of<br>
democratic institutions, continued elimination of corruption and<br>
crime, the strengthening of the army and intelligence agencies, and<br>
the acceleration of economic reforms with supplemental increases in<br>
wages and the creation of a national social security system.  The<br>
platform also calls for increasing cooperation with Russia, Georgia<br>
and Iran, as well as establishing more stable relations with<br>
Azerbaijan and Turkey.  Ter Petrosian promises to find a compromise<br>
solution to the Nagorno Karabagh conflict and to improve relations<br>
with the substantial Armenia diaspora throughout the world.  <br>
<p>
2 September: The head of Armenian State Radio, Stepan Zakarian, is<br>
dismissed from his post following a controversial court case<br>
involving Mikael Martirossian, the head of a state-owned bread<br>
factory and member of the ANM.  Several reports carried by Armenian<br>
radio accused bread producers of selling low-weight bread in order<br>
to increase profits. These reports led to court challenges and<br>
forced the radio station to issue a retraction.<br>
<p>
4-5 September: A group of prominent intellectuals publishes a call<br>
for the government to end the ban of the opposition Armenian<br>
Revolutionary Federation (ARF).  The statement criticizes the Ter<br>
Petrosian government for its illegal suspension of the ARF and for<br>
its state campaign targeting the opposition within the country.  A<br>
similar plea is also issued the next day by a coalition of fourteen<br>
different political and public organizations and parties. The<br>
statement also condemns the government's disregard for the civil<br>
liberties of free speech and the right to voice political dissent. <br>
Both statements appear to coincide with an effort by the ARF to<br>
gather at least 200,000 signatures of Armenian citizens urging the<br>
legal reinstatement of the ARF in the country.<br>
<p>
5 September: The opposition Scientific Industrial and Civil Union<br>
(SICU) and the National Democratic Union (NDU) hold a joint rally<br>
with more than 20,000 participants supporting the opposition in the<br>
upcoming presidential election.  The opposition parties' leaders<br>
urge their supporters to vote against the corrupt Ter Petrosian<br>
government and specifically condemns the government's persecution<br>
of the opposition Armenian Revolutionary Federation .<br>
<p>
6 September: The head of election observers for the Organization<br>
for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), Simon Osborn, states<br>
that his team is preparing for the comprehensive task of monitoring<br>
the September 22nd presidential election.  The OSCE observers are<br>
planning to visit various polling stations throughout the country. <br>
The OSCE is said to be maintaining vigilance given the "free but<br>
not fair" nature of the parliamentary elections.<br>
<p>
7-8 September: Opposition candidates Pariur Hairikian of the<br>
National Self-Determination Union, Aram Sargsian of the Democratic<br>
Party and Lenser Aghalovian of the Artsakh-Hayastan movement<br>
announce their withdrawal from the Armenian presidential race and<br>
support for Vazgen Manoukian (NDU).  The two other major opposition<br>
candidates, Sergei Badalian of the Armenian Communist Party and<br>
Ashot Manoucharian of the Scientific-Industrial and Civil Union<br>
(SICU), remain in the presidential race.  The country's largest<br>
opposition party, the Armenian Revolutionary Federation (ARF),<br>
still banned by the government, is also supporting Manoukian.<br>
<p>
8 September: The presidential candidate Vazgen Manoukian, releases<br>
a new common campaign platform of the three newly united opposition<br>
parties.  The united plan calls for full independence for the<br>
Republic of Nagorno Karabagh, state policies "based on Armenian<br>
national values," formation of a new government of national accord<br>
by the allied opposition parties, new parliamentary elections, and<br>
the adoption of a new constitution strengthening the legislative<br>
and judicial branches of government to better balance power against<br>
the strong executive branch.  Additional proposals include<br>
industrial policies to promote indigenous industry in order to<br>
foster greater self-sufficiency, a broad campaign aimed at<br>
eliminating corruption and organized crime, and a new focus on<br>
social programs to ease the effects of economic reform and<br>
privatization.<br>
<p>
10 September: Iranian deputy Foreign Minister Mahmud Vaezi meets<br>
with Armenian officials to review bilateral plans for increasing<br>
trade, commerce and economic cooperation.  Specifically, the<br>
proposals include the construction of a cross-border natural gas<br>
pipeline and a high voltage electricity line, further Iranian<br>
investment in Armenia's infrastructure with a focus on modernizing<br>
and expanding Armenia's railway and highway network, and a<br>
trilateral agreement providing for the shipment of natural gas from<br>
Turkmenistan, through Iran and to Armenia.<br>
<p>
18 September: In the largest military exercise in the region since<br>
1991, four thousand Russian and Armenian troops stage joint<br>
military exercises using armored vehicles, tanks, artillery and<br>
military aircraft.<br>
<p>
22 September: Incumbent President Ter Petrosian claims victory in<br>
the day's presidential elections as early unofficial returns<br>
released by the Armenian Central Election Commission show a 56 to<br>
37 percent margin for the president over his opposition rival<br>
Vazgen Manoukian of the National Democratic Union.  An estimated<br>
2.4 million Armenian voters participated in the election.  The<br>
opposition stages a rally to protest the election, accusing the<br>
authorities of massive fraud in the counting of the ballots.<br>
<p>
23 September: The independent and non-political European Institute<br>
for the Media, which actively monitored the presidential campaign,<br>
criticizes the election and reports that state-run television and<br>
media "clearly favored Ter Petrosian through its tendentious<br>
coverage."  Additionally, the Organization for Security and<br>
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) admitted that television air-time<br>
allotted to Ter Petrosian had far exceeded the air-time available<br>
to all other candidates put together.  The OSCE also noted concern<br>
over numerous blatant local voting irregularities by the<br>
authorities, although an OSCE preliminary report stated that these<br>
factors "did not significantly affect" the election's outcome. <br>
Other Western monitors reported that they witnessed widespread<br>
fraud.<br>
<p>
23-24 September: The opposition states that they have substantial<br>
evidence of voting fraud and massive ballot rigging and claim a<br>
national return of at least 60 percent for Manoukian, who they term<br>
as the legitimate president-elect.  The opposition, barred from<br>
state-run television and radio and denied a hearing before the<br>
Central Election Commission, accuse the authorities of carrying out<br>
a virtual coup d'tat through falsification of the returns and vow<br>
to resist the results through peaceful mass protests.<br>
<p>
23-25 September: Opposition demonstrators, for three straight days,<br>
hold massive rallies with over 100,000 participants outside the<br>
parliament building which houses the offices of the Central<br>
Election Commission (CEC).  On the 25th, after reports circulate<br>
that Vazgen Manoukian and others had been arrested while trying to<br>
file a petition for a recount with the CEC, a small group of<br>
demonstrators push open the parliament gates and enter the grounds. <br>
The security forces, already on hand along the parliament's<br>
perimeter and equipped with full riot gear, react by firing upon<br>
the unarmed crowd, killing at least one person and wounding at<br>
least fifty-nine.  In the chaos of the incident, parliamentary<br>
chairman Babken Ararktsian and his deputy Ara Sahakian are<br>
physically assaulted by a several individuals.  President Ter<br>
Petrosian holds emergency meetings with his top ministers and<br>
issues orders banning all movement into the capital and deploying<br>
tanks and armored personnel carriers throughout the city's main<br>
intersections and thoroughfares.<br>
<p>
26 September: Meeting in an emergency session, the Armenian<br>
parliament votes to lift parliamentary immunity for opposition<br>
deputies in order to initiate criminal charges of treason,<br>
terrorism and an attempted seizure of power.  Parliamentary<br>
immunity is revoked for opposition candidate Vazgen Manoukian and<br>
seven other opposition deputies by a vote of 155-0 with two<br>
abstentions.  Several of the opposition deputies, attending the<br>
parliamentary session, are physically assaulted and beaten during<br>
the session in front of the television cameras broadcasting the<br>
parliament's meeting to the nation.  In Yerevan, tanks with escorts<br>
of special riot police patrol the streets and, with the assistance<br>
of plain clothes police units, roughly disperse any and all groups<br>
of citizens on the streets.  Acting on the president's orders,<br>
Armenian security forces arrest several hundred leading opposition<br>
leader and members throughout the country.  Manoukian is reportedly<br>
in hiding as security officers seek to arrest him.<br>
<p>
------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Republic of Georgia<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
69,700 sq. km<br>
Slightly larger than S. Carolina<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia 164 km<br>
Azerbaijan 322 km<br>
Russia 723 km<br>
Turkey 252 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
<p>
5.57 million<br>
56% urban<br>
78 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
69% Georgian<br>
9% Armenian<br>
6% Russian<br>
6% Ajarian<br>
5% Azerbaijani<br>
3% Ossetian<br>
2% Abkhazian<br>
<p>
Georgia includes the autonomous republics of Abkhazia and Ajaria<br>
and the South Ossetian Autonomous Region.<br>
<p>
Leadership:  Eduard Shevardnadze, President; Irakli Menagrashvili,<br>
Foreign Minister, Nickol Lekishvili, Secretary of State, Zurab<br>
Zhvania, Parliamentary Chairman.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Georgia established its independence on April 9,<br>
1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  The Georgian government joined the CIS on<br>
October 23, 1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was adopted in August, 1995,<br>
which reinstates a presidential form of government and provides for<br>
a strong executive branch and a unicameral 235-seat parliament.  A<br>
constitutional court is also created.  The constitution, however,<br>
does not address the status of Abkhazia, Ossetia or Ajaria.<br>
<p>
Elections:  Presidential and parliamentary elections were held<br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to<br>
Georgia is Ambassador Kent Brown. The Georgian representative to<br>
the United States, as well as Canada and Mexico, is Ambassador Tedo<br>
Japaridze.  The Georgian representative to the United Nations is<br>
Ambassador Peter Chkiedze.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
1 September: Abkhazian President Vladislav Ardzinba announces new<br>
parliamentary elections for November 23, 1996.  The current<br>
Abkhazian legislature was elected in early 1992 but has been<br>
hampered by the loss of its Georgian deputies who fled to Tbilisi<br>
during the worst part of the Abkhazian conflict in 1992-1993. <br>
These deputies established their own pro-Georgian body in Tbilisi<br>
in an attempt to form a parliament-in-exile.<br>
<p>
3 September: Foreign Minister Menagrashvili holds a news conference<br>
upon his return from a three day visit to Ukraine.  He reports that<br>
Ukrainian officials have announced their intention to dispatch<br>
cease-fire monitors to Abkhazia and, if the United Nations Security<br>
Council approves, a detachment of Ukrainian peacekeeping forces to<br>
the region.  Additionally, it is revealed that among the Georgian<br>
delegation were the commander of Georgian land forces, Major<br>
General Guzhar Kurashvili, and the border troops commander, Major<br>
General Valery Chkheidze.  The Georgian military officials met with<br>
their Ukrainian counterparts to formalize a preliminary agreement<br>
providing for Ukrainian assistance in the restructuring of the<br>
Georgian army.  The Ukrainian officials, including president Leonid<br>
Kuchma and Foreign Minister Hennady Udovenko, promise to support<br>
the Georgian claim to some of the naval vessels of the former<br>
Soviet Black Sea fleet in order to patrol and protect the Georgian<br>
coastline.<br>
<p>
6 September: The chairman of the South Ossetian parliament, Lyudvig<br>
Chibirov, announces his government's decision to form a South<br>
Ossetian presidency and to introduce presidential rule in the<br>
region.  The South Ossetian parliament schedules a special session<br>
for September 13 to formalize the governmental restructuring and to<br>
alter the South Ossetian constitution accordingly.<br>
<p>
7 September: In response to the decision by the South Ossetian<br>
parliament to form a new presidential system of government,<br>
Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze announces that the South<br>
Ossetian move unilaterally undercuts the understandings previously<br>
reached with parliamentary chairman Chibirov at their recent<br>
meeting in Vladikavkaz.  The Russia and the Organization for<br>
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) issue separate statements<br>
warning that this decision endangers the recent progress toward a<br>
political solution to the conflict.<br>
<p>
7 September: Georgian defense ministry officials announce an<br>
agreement with Germany allowing for the military training of 15<br>
Georgian officers in an annual military exchange program.  This<br>
follows the Georgian parliament's ratification of an earlier<br>
Georgian-Turkish military cooperation agreement with stipulations<br>
for the exchange of military equipment and hardware, joint military<br>
exercises and cooperation in the military production sector.<br>
<p>
8 September: Abkhazian President Vladislav Ardzinba announces that<br>
a referendum will be held next month on the question of<br>
independence.  Georgian government officials have expressed their<br>
opposition to the parliamentary elections in Abkhazia scheduled for<br>
November 23rd. <br>
<p>
9 September: Georgian Defense Minister Lt. General Vardiko<br>
Nadibaidze and Uzbek Defense Minister Colonel General Rustem<br>
Ahmedov hold a joint press conference to announce that Georgia and<br>
Uzbekistan will not join a military coalition of the Commonwealth<br>
of Independent States (CIS).  The two ministers, having completed<br>
two days of talks, also announce a new bilateral agreement on<br>
military cooperation and partnership.  The Georgian-Uzbek military<br>
agreement calls for the reciprocal use of each country's airfields<br>
and bases, as well as the sharing of military technical services<br>
and training facilities.<br>
<p>
22 September:  Parliamentary elections are held for eighty seats in<br>
the Ajarian legislature.  A coalition of Ajarian parliamentary<br>
chairman Aslan Abashidze's All-Georgia Revival Union party and the<br>
Union of Georgia's Citizens party of Georgian President<br>
Shevardnadze win at least 72 of the 80 seats.  An estimated 225,000<br>
voters took part in the election which was conducted without<br>
incident.<br>
<p>
24 September: The chairman of the South Ossetian Council of<br>
Ministers, Vyacheslav Gaborayev, is dismissed from his post by the<br>
South Ossetian parliament.  The move is seen as the latest<br>
development in the rivalry between Gaborayev and the parliamentary<br>
chairman, Lyudvig Chibirov.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
------<br>
<p>
Republic of Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Total area:<br>
81,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Maine<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Armenia (West) 566 km<br>
Armenia (southwest) 221 km<br>
Georgia 332 km<br>
Iran (south) 432 km<br>
Iran (southwest) 179 km<br>
Russia 284 km<br>
Turkey 9 km<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
7.3 million<br>
54% urban<br>
89 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
71% Azerbaijani<br>
11% Talish<br>
6% Russian<br>
4% Lezgi<br>
3% Kurdish<br>
3% Daghestani<br>
2% Avar<br>
<p>
The autonomous republic of Nakhichevan (pop. 350,000; 5,500 sq. km)<br>
was placed under Azerbaijani administration in 1921.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Leadership:  Geidar Aliyev, President; Artur Rasizade, Prime<br>
Minister; Hasan Hasanov, Foreign Minister; Shamshaddin Khanbabayev,<br>
Premier of Nakhichevan.<br>
<p>
Independence:  Azerbaijan established its independence on August<br>
30, 1991.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Azerbaijan joined the CIS on September 24,<br>
1993.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  A new constitution was passed by referendum in<br>
November 1995.<br>
<p>
Elections: Parliamentary elections for a new 125-seat legislature<br>
were held November 1995.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  The United States representative to<br>
Azerbaijan is Ambassador Richard Kauzlarich.  The Azerbaijani<br>
representative to the United States is Ambassador Hafiz Pashayev. <br>
The Azerbaijani representative to the United Nations is Yashar<br>
Aliyev.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
1 September: In the latest complication over the transportation<br>
issue of the expected initial oil from the international project to<br>
develop the offshore Caspian Sea reserves, Russian officials reveal<br>
that several sections of the Baku-Grozny-Novorossiisk pipeline have<br>
been damaged from the fighting in Chechnya and due to numerous<br>
illegal attempts to siphon oil from the pipeline.  The pipeline<br>
through Chechnya is essential to the multi-billion dollar oil deal<br>
between Azerbaijan and a consortium of Western oil companies, which<br>
plans on utilizing the route to transport the expected 32 million<br>
tons of oil over a span of seven years from the offshore Azeri,<br>
Chirag and Guneshli oil fields.  Petroleum industry experts<br>
estimate that the pipeline route requires some $55-60 million in<br>
financing to modernize and upgrade the pipeline to allow for the<br>
secure shipment of oil from Baku to the main Russian facility at<br>
the Black Sea port of Novorossiisk.  Although officials of the<br>
Azerbaijan International Operating Company (the operating arm of<br>
the international consortium) are exploring a secondary route<br>
utilizing a pipeline through Georgia, analysts report that the<br>
Georgian pipeline is damaged in over two thousand separate sections<br>
and would require over $245 million to repair and modernize the<br>
pipeline to become fully operational. <br>
<p>
2 September: The vice-president of the Azerbaijani state oil<br>
company SOCAR announces that new negotiations will begin shortly<br>
with Iranian energy officials to launch a joint Azeri-Iranian<br>
venture to drill new offshore oil wells in the Caspian Sea. <br>
According to Azerbaijani officials, the joint venture will consist<br>
of a 51 percent share for SOCAR and 49 percent for the Iranian<br>
National Oil Construction and Engineering Company (INOCEC).<br>
<p>
4 September: The British company Ramco announces that it has plans,<br>
jointly with the international Price Waterhouse firm, to develop<br>
the offshore Muradkhanly deposits, one of the Caspian Sea's largest<br>
reserves.  Ramco is already an active participant in the consortium<br>
of international oil companies formed to develop the offshore<br>
Azeri, Chirag and Guneshli fields. <br>
<p>
4 September: Russian foreign ministry Special Ambassador Fyodor<br>
Kovalchuk arrives in Baku to meet with senior Azerbaijani officials<br>
to review the problematic disagreement between the two countries<br>
over the legal status of the offshore oil reserves in the Caspian<br>
Sea.  The Russian government is seeking to include all states<br>
bordering the Caspian in an attempt to gain collective sharing<br>
rights over all energy reserves in the Caspian Sea.  Azerbaijan<br>
naturally insists on retaining the exclusive right to develop the<br>
oil fields.<br>
<p>
5 September: The Azerbaijani Supreme Court sentences a former<br>
associate of ousted President Ayaz Mutalibov, Adyl Gadzhiev, and<br>
Kenan Gyurel, an Austrian citizen of Turkish origin, to 14 and 15<br>
year prison terms respectively for their part in the coup attempt<br>
of March 1995.  President Geidar Aliyev has long accused former<br>
president Mutalibov, in exile in Moscow, of plotting his overthrow.<br>
<p>
6 September: The vice-president of the Japanese State Oil Company,<br>
Satasi Tono, announces that his group is interested in increasing<br>
Japanese investment in developing Azerbaijan's Caspian Sea energy<br>
reserves.  Japanese officials have revealed that nearly twenty<br>
Japanese corporations are exploring multi-billion dollar investment<br>
deals in the Azerbaijani energy sector.  A leading Japanese firm<br>
has been the Itochu Oil Company which recently acquired the share<br>
of the U.S. McDermott company in the international consortium and<br>
has further increased its share by another 4 percent with the<br>
purchase of Pennzoil's shares as well.  Another large Japanese oil<br>
concern, Mitsui, has offered the Azerbaijan state oil company SOCAR<br>
$1 billion in an effort to obtain the right of sole, exclusive<br>
development of a promising oil field along the Caspian Sea shelf. <br>
Additional Japanese investment is being considered for the<br>
modernization and development of Azerbaijan's petrochemical<br>
industries, pipeline facilities including the route through<br>
Azerbaijan to Georgian port terminals along the Black Sea, and the<br>
country's construction and communications sectors.  To date,<br>
Azerbaijan has received some $5 billion in various aid projects<br>
making Azerbaijan the leading recipient of Japanese aid of all<br>
former Soviet states including even Russia.<br>
<p>
7 September: The political council of the ruling "Yeni (new)<br>
Azerbaijan" political party releases a statement calling for a<br>
special session of the parliament to review the conduct and<br>
performance of parliamentary speaker Rasul Guliyev.  The political<br>
council, the leadership body of President Aliyev's party, is said<br>
to be investigating charges of the speaker's misconduct and<br>
corruption.  This development, directed against the second most<br>
powerful political figure in Azerbaijan, is the latest in a fairly<br>
comprehensive governmental shakeup which began with the dismissal<br>
of the prime minister last month.  The dispute between the<br>
president and the parliamentary speaker is reportedly over the pace<br>
of economic reforms, with the president and his economic advisers<br>
advocating a slower, more restrained course in contrast to the<br>
speaker's calls for more radical reforms for the Azerbaijani<br>
economy.<br>
<p>
9 September: In an extraordinary session of the Azerbaijani<br>
parliament chaired by President Geidar Aliyev, parliamentary<br>
chairman Rasul Guliyev resigns from his post amid accusations of<br>
corruption and a sharp internal dispute over the pace of economic<br>
reforms.  By a vote of 98-8 with four abstentions, the 110-seat<br>
legislature accepts the resignation. The resignation signals the<br>
victory of the chief presidential economics adviser, Vahid Ahundov,<br>
who strongly advocates a slowing of economic reforms and<br>
privatization.  This conflict is said to have first erupted during<br>
last month's negotiations with the International Monetary Fund<br>
(IMF) over the terms of IMF assistance to Azerbaijan.  President<br>
Aliyev has increasingly favored slower reform in order to ease the<br>
social effects of the IMF's austerity plan.  The outgoing<br>
parliamentary chairman is offered the post of Azerbaijani<br>
ambassador to Norway as an attempt to both marginalize the powerful<br>
chairman and to ease tensions over his departure. <br>
<p>
10 September: Azerbaijani Foreign Minister Hasan Hasanov, in<br>
comments on the recent situation in northern Iraq, announces<br>
Azerbaijan's support for Turkey's decision to establish a military<br>
"security zone" in the Kurdish area of northern Iraq.  Baku also<br>
states that it supports Turkey's "right to take every measure" to<br>
preserve its territorial integrity.<br>
<p>
11 September: The Organization for Security and Cooperation in<br>
Europe (OSCE) Special Envoy Frank Lambach meets with Azerbaijani<br>
officials in Baku.  The meeting reviews the current Azerbaijani<br>
position regarding the Nagorno Karabagh conflict and discusses the<br>
results of last month's meeting in Germany between the Armenian and<br>
Azerbaijani presidential advisers.<br>
<p>
11 September: Azerbaijan announces the formation of a new<br>
international consortium, the Caspian International Oil Company<br>
(CIOC), empowered to exploit and develop the offshore reserves of<br>
the "Karabagh" sector of the Caspian Sea.  The CIOC is the second<br>
international consortium and is established on the terms of a<br>
November 1995 agreement and expects a United States investment of<br>
$35,000 in early 1997.  The new consortium comprises the Russian<br>
state oil company Lukoil, holding a 32.5 percent share, the U.S.<br>
company Pennzoil and the Italian firm Agipa, each with a thirty<br>
percent stake, and the Azerbaijani state oil company SOCAR, with a<br>
7.5 percent share.  Initial offshore exploration will be launched<br>
shortly in the Karabagh field, eighty kilometers south of Baku. <br>
The Karabagh oil field is expected to contain some 85 million tons<br>
of oil and 18 billion cubic meters of natural gas.<br>
<p>
12 September: The World Bank announces that it is to extend a $5<br>
million loan package to the Turkish state oil and gas company BOTAS<br>
to undertake a feasibility study of the projected annual export of<br>
some 45 million metric tons of crude oil from Azerbaijan and<br>
Central Asia.  The World Bank is interested in exploring the<br>
possible transit routes from Baku to the Turkish port facilities at<br>
Ceylon on the Mediterranean Sea.  The projected routes would either<br>
transit Armenia or Georgia, or possible Azerbaijan-Armenia-<br>
Nakhichevan.<br>
<p>
16 September: President Nursultan Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan signs<br>
with Azerbaijan a treaty of bilateral relations, a series of ten<br>
inter-governmental accords, and a joint statement on the<br>
international legal status of the offshore reserves and resources<br>
of the Caspian Sea.  The Caspian Sea statement calls for further<br>
negotiations between the Caspian's littoral states.  President<br>
Nazarbayev also expresses interest in participating in the project<br>
to construct a "Transcaucasian" railway line connecting the<br>
transport networks of Georgia, Azerbaijan, Uzbekistan and<br>
Turkmenistan.<br>
<p>
27 September: The Japanese Itochu Corporation announces that it is<br>
to open an office in Baku to coordinate its planned investment in<br>
the Azerbaijani energy sector.  According to the company's general<br>
manager in Baku, Kotaro Morishita, the investment is the latest<br>
element in the new Japanese focus on the Transcaucasus.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Republic of Nagorno Karabagh<br>
<p>
<p>
Total area:<br>
4,800 sq. km<br>
Slightly smaller than Delaware<br>
<p>
Bordering states:<br>
Azerbaijan<br>
<p>
Population:<br>
150,000<br>
31 persons/sq. km<br>
<p>
Ethnic composition:<br>
95% Armenian<br>
5% Assyrian, Greek,<br>
Kurdish, other<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Leadership:  Robert Kocharian, President (elected December 22,<br>
1994);  Leonard Petrossian, Prime Minister;  Arkady Gukasyan,<br>
Foreign Minister;  Samvel Babayan, Defense Minister.<br>
<p>
Independence:  The Republic of Nagorno Karabagh was established on<br>
September 2, 1991 and declared its independence on January 6, 1992.<br>
<p>
CIS membership status:  Nagorno Karabagh is not a member of the<br>
CIS.<br>
<p>
Constitution:  The Parliament, which approved a temporary<br>
constitution in June 1992, had been working on drafting a<br>
constitution for the republic.  This task will now be assumed by<br>
the new parliament.<br>
<p>
Elections:  The Law on the Presidency, enacted December, 1994,<br>
establishes a five-year presidential term, although the election of<br>
Kocharian is limited to two years.  Parliamentary elections were<br>
held April 30, 1995 for a new 33-seat parliament.<br>
<p>
Diplomatic representation:  Nagorno Karabagh's representative to<br>
the United States is Ardem Haroutunian.  Varoujan Krikorian is the<br>
representative of Nagorno Karabagh to the European Community and<br>
the European Parliament.<br>
<p>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
MONTHLY CHRONOLOGY<br>
<p>
1 September: Azerbaijan's presidential adviser Vafa Guluzade states<br>
that a peaceful solution to the Karabagh conflict may be found<br>
soon.  The comment by the Azerbaijani official follows his recent<br>
meeting with Armenian presidential adviser Jirair Libaridian in<br>
Frankfurt, Germany.  According to Guluzade, Armenian government<br>
officials are anxious to reach a solution to the Nagorno Karabagh<br>
conflict due to their "economic difficulties" and because the<br>
Armenian government is convinced that neither an annexation of the<br>
Republic of Nagorno Karabagh by Armenia nor international<br>
recognition of the independence of the republic is possible.  News<br>
reports quote Libaridian as stating that a draft agreement<br>
currently being prepared by the Armenian government would satisfy<br>
Azerbaijan.  Republic of Nagorno Karabagh representation is notably<br>
absent from these talks. <br>
<p>
2 September: During a special session of the Karabagh parliament<br>
commemorating the fifth anniversary of the unilateral declaration<br>
of independence and establishment of the Republic of Nagorno<br>
Karabagh, a resolution is passed calling for a new presidential<br>
election to be held on November 24, 1996.  Current President Robert<br>
Kocharian, elected as the republic's first president, is serving a<br>
temporary term which expires in December 1996.  According to the<br>
new Law on Presidential Elections, the new president will serve for<br>
a five-year term. Presidential candidates are required to gather a<br>
minimum of 1500 signatures of support in at least four of the six<br>
districts of the Republic of Nagorno Karabagh.  The Nagorno<br>
Karabagh Central Electoral Commission states that official<br>
registration for the presidential race will begin on October 10th. <br>
An Armenian delegation led by Prime Minister Hrant Bagratian<br>
attending the commemorative parliamentary session is welcomed by<br>
parliamentary chairman Artur Tovmassian. <br>
<p>
2 September: The Nagorno Karabagh government issues a statement<br>
refuting recent allegations leveled by Azerbaijani Prosecutor<br>
General Eldar Hasanov accusing Karabagh of engaging in the<br>
production and smuggling of narcotics. The Karabagh statement<br>
alleges that it is Azerbaijani that is suspected by the<br>
international community of narcotics trafficking and that the<br>
Stepanakert government remains committed to assisting in all<br>
efforts to combat the drug trade.<br>
<p>
3 September: Armenian deputy Foreign Minister Vartan Oskanian, in<br>
an interview with a visiting reporter, states that the recent peace<br>
plan between Russia and Chechnya is a viable precedent and fair<br>
model for settling the Nagorno Karabagh conflict.  According to the<br>
Armenian official, the Chechen plan, negotiated by Russian national<br>
security adviser Aleksandr Lebed, sets forth a five-year cease-fire<br>
to be followed by a national referendum within Chechnya on the<br>
region's political status.  Other officials of the Armenian foreign<br>
ministry predict that greater international mediation efforts will<br>
be underway once the presidential election in Armenia is completed. <br>
The deputy foreign minister added that his government expects<br>
serious progress on the long series of mediation talks and predicts<br>
a final solution within the next two years.<br>
<p>
4 September: Representatives of the International Committee of the<br>
Red Cross announce that shipments of 120 tons of wheat seed will be<br>
provided to eight needy villages in Nagorno Karabagh's Mardakert<br>
district.  The Red Cross also plans to continue its humanitarian<br>
aid program with a particular focus on providing clean drinking<br>
water to villages in the Hadrut and Mardakert districts. <br>
<p>
9 September: Nagorno Karabagh parliamentary chairman Artur<br>
Tovmassian meets with Armenian Prime Minister Hrant Bagratian to<br>
discuss parliamentary cooperation and to review problems related to<br>
the visit of Armenian parliamentary chairman Babken Ararktsian to<br>
Stepanakert.<br>
<p>
10 September: According to officials of the International Committee<br>
of the Red Cross, there are some 50,000 land mines present within<br>
the Republic of Nagorno Karabagh.  Red Cross officials warn of the<br>
danger to residents posed by these unseen fatal hazards and report<br>
that during 1994-1995, over 24 percent of those wounded in Karabagh<br>
were victims of these land mines.  The reconstruction of the<br>
infrastructure of Nagorno Karabagh is seriously hampered by the<br>
presence of the land mines and its remains a daunting humanitarian<br>
priority.<br>
<p>
16 September: The vice chairman of the Nagorno Karabagh parliament,<br>
Boris Aroushanian, announces his resignation from his post for<br>
unspecified reasons.  The parliament accepts the resignation<br>
without naming a replacement.<br>
<p>
17 September: Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe<br>
(OSCE) German representative Frank Lambach and U.S. Ambassador<br>
Joseph Presel conclude meetings with Nagorno Karabagh officials in<br>
Stepanakert.  The OSCE officials held meetings with Karabagh<br>
President Robert Kocharian and were given a tour of the republic.<br>
<p>
18 September: According to a report of the head of the Nagorno<br>
Karabagh migration office of the Refugees Department, Lilia Kalian,<br>
a total of 40,000 thousand refugees have recently returned to<br>
Karabagh.  The total number of refugees who fled or were forced<br>
from their homes due to the Karabagh conflict are estimated at<br>
360,000.<br>
<p>
19 September: The vice speaker of the British House of Lords, Lady<br>
Caroline Cox, arrives in Nagorno Karabagh for her 29th visit in the<br>
last six years to deliver 20 tons of humanitarian aid for the<br>
Karabagh population.  Lady Cox, with assistance from the<br>
International Christian Solidarity organization, is to complete<br>
another humanitarian mission early next year with a shipment of<br>
Christmas presents for refugee children.<br>
<p>
20 September: Nagorno Karabagh officials announce that a new<br>
comprehensive privatization program is being readied for<br>
implementation shortly.  The new certificate-based privatization<br>
program is aimed at expanding the government's market economic<br>
reforms in the republic.<br>
<p>
*******************************************************************<br>
<p>
*The E-mail version of the TransCaucasus: A Chronology differs from<br>
the   official printed version in two ways:  (1) text formatting<br>
and (2) the   printed version includes maps of the Transcaucasus<br>
countries.<br>
